c\u2500wpa_supplicant\n \u2514\u2500xinetd\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>System monitor and top screenshots which show the zombie process is using resources:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/gL27e.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/Vgfxs.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["software-recommendation","password-manager"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":30908,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30908\/comments","question_id":30907,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1300450297,"last_edit_date":1300452450,"last_activity_date":1300452450,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"Password Management Applications?","body":"<h1><a href=\"http:\/\/www.keepassx.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>KeePassX<\/strong><\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/apt.marcoceppi.com\/p\/keepassx\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/bit.ly\/software-large\" alt=\"install\"><\/a><\/h1>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>KeePassX is a free\/open-source password manager or safe which helps you to manage your passwords in a secure way. You can put all your passwords in one database, which is locked with one master key or a key-disk. So you only have to remember one single master password or insert the key-disk to unlock the whole database. The databases are encrypted using the algorithms AES or Twofish.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/8EiLZ.png\" alt=\"Screenshot\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30909,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30909\/comments","question_id":30907,"owner":{"user_id":6341,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"B. Roland","reputation":677,"email_hash":"ee620dd197780fb0e5a0920cdcf973a4"},"creation_date":1300450422,"last_edit_date":1300452184,"last_activity_date":1300452184,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Password Management Applications?","body":"<p>Hi!<\/p>\n\n<p>I suggest you the free, cross-platform <a href=\"http:\/\/www.keepassx.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">KeePassX<\/a>. I'm using it in my Android phone too(combined with <a href=\"http:\/\/dropbox.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dropbox<\/a>). You can install from the software center <a href=\"http:\/\/apt.ubuntu.com\/p\/keepassx\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/bit.ly\/software-small\" alt=\"install\"><\/a>.  <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/ZRRPC.png\" alt=\"window\"><\/p>\n\n<p>You can find the features <a href=\"http:\/\/www.keepassx.org\/features\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>, and more screenshots <a href=\"http:\/\/www.keepassx.org\/screenshots\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30912,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30912\/comments","question_id":30907,"owner":{"user_id":5297,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Reuben Swartz","reputation":337,"email_hash":"1d88ea49e14be3dea7db64fd2bc42d87"},"creation_date":1300451122,"last_activity_date":1300451122,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Password Management Applications?","body":"<p>Seahorse is an application that is installed in ubuntu by default and manages passwords for various applications<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30924,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30924\/comments","question_id":30907,"owner":{"user_id":2692,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Kendor","reputation":364,"email_hash":"451b108a4f680a0c4edd7e9a3edd22f1"},"creation_date":1300457359,"last_activity_date":1300457359,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Password Management Applications?","body":"<p>I really like <a href=\"http:\/\/lastpass.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">LastPass<\/a> It's not open source, but is very well supported across platforms, browsers and devices. They recently acquired XMarks (great cross platform\/cross browser bookmark sync tool). LastPass is incredibly secure, offers 2nd pass authentication and is very reliable.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30907\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30907\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30907\/answers","question_id":30907,"owner":{"user_id":9701,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Achu","reputation":320,"email_hash":"bf758c9580940c3234a7cd0089c401cd"},"creation_date":1300449810,"last_edit_date":1300452606,"last_activity_date":1300457359,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Password Management Applications?","body":"<p>I have some passwords long, complicated and hard to remember. I need to use a password manager application to save all my password instead of saving using a text editor.  but i'm not sure which one is the best password manager. <\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","screensaver"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30922\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30922\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30922\/answers","question_id":30922,"owner":{"user_id":10616,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"EvilPhoenix","reputation":563,"email_hash":"6b92567199ee8a3e4a61c40a4406aff4"},"creation_date":1300457002,"last_activity_date":1300457002,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"gnome-screensaver: Screen Saver Does Not Show When On Battery","body":"<p>I use gnome-screensaver on my system, and it operates near my expectations.  One question.  Is there a way to get the screensaver to show up  when the system is operating on battery power only?  Right now, the system just blanks the screen, but I'd really like to see an actual screensaver when I blank my screen.  Any way to do this?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["gnome","icons","themes","appearance","gtk"],"answer_count":8,"answers":[{"answer_id":2515,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2515\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":289,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Li Lo","reputation":2835,"email_hash":"b078a0ec2a7bb1235720515928c9ca4b"},"creation_date":1282075015,"last_edit_date":1300453237,"last_activity_date":1300453237,"up_vote_count":9,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":9,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.webupd8.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Web Upd8<\/a> is where I got a lot of nice themes and tips for customization. Plus they maintain a PPA with modding\/utility apps.They also have a PPA <code>ppa:webupd8team\/themes<\/code> (<a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\">How to add PPAs<\/a>) specifically for themes.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2503,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2503\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":146,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Xuacu","reputation":311,"email_hash":"682eb67e78ef1f82799214609710170c"},"creation_date":1282065662,"last_activity_date":1282065662,"up_vote_count":8,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":8,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>Here you'll find some Ubuntu related art:\n<a href=\"http:\/\/browse.deviantart.com\/?q=gallery%3Aubuntu-artists%2F24290476\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/browse.deviantart.com\/?q=gallery%3Aubuntu-artists%2F24290476<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>And here, Ubuntu awareness material (and release countdown buttons) :\n<a href=\"http:\/\/spreadubuntu.neomenlo.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/spreadubuntu.neomenlo.org\/<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Regards!<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2504,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2504\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":333,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"dustyprogrammer","reputation":2738,"email_hash":"fab591eb34c76cbd0716024ce22d4906"},"creation_date":1282065926,"last_activity_date":1282065926,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":372,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>This weblog does alot of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.omgubuntu.co.uk\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">customization<\/a> tutorials and various other ubuntu thematics related topics. <\/p>\n\n<p>Plus its in England<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2646,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2646\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":662,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alin Andrei","reputation":417,"email_hash":"f301ea9f912fe216ad8175baba86318c"},"creation_date":1282216101,"last_edit_date":1300456825,"last_activity_date":1300456825,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>Here are some themes PPAs:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~tiheum\/+archive\/equinox\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~tiheum\/+archive\/equinox<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~elementaryart\/+archive\/ppa\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~elementaryart\/+archive\/ppa<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~elegant-gnome\/+archive\/ppa\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~elegant-gnome\/+archive\/ppa<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>All of those are amazing themes. The first PPA comes with the updated Ubuntu Light Themes backported from Ubuntu 10.10 to Ubuntu 10.04.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2535,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2535\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":189,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"tinker","reputation":155,"email_hash":"ae4edec4182d73db9fc8cad5f1083733"},"creation_date":1282095817,"last_activity_date":1282095817,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>Reddit pics (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.reddit.com\/r\/pics\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/www.reddit.com\/r\/pics\/<\/a>) is sometimes a good source for artistic, odd, funny, or bueautiful images that make good desktop backgrounds. Here are a few I've found (I especially like landscapes):<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/SPY3v.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/SPY3v.jpg<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/UBl94l.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/UBl94l.jpg<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/science.nationalgeographic.com\/wallpaper\/science\/photos\/canyons-gallery\/canyon-de-chelly\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/science.nationalgeographic.com\/wallpaper\/science\/photos\/canyons-gallery\/canyon-de-chelly\/<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2690,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2690\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":1496,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"autocrosser","reputation":21,"email_hash":"ab6ee6d014de4b35d4f28bf1c4cb6d8b"},"creation_date":1282279287,"last_activity_date":1282279287,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>And the \"Granddaddy\" of them all is gnomelook.org---not a PPA, but when you can just take a .tar &amp; drop it on Appearance--why a PPA?<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2651,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2651\/comments","question_id":2502,"creation_date":1282226517,"last_activity_date":1282226517,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>You might want to look at this eye-candy project from France, it's amazing:\n<a href=\"http:\/\/www.bisigi-project.org\/?page_id=8&amp;lang=en\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/www.bisigi-project.org\/?page_id=8&amp;lang=en<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>It works great, I didn't have any problems with the themes and they are complete, meaning that you have their icons not only on your desktop but also in nautilus file browser.<\/p>\n\n<p>I apologize in case an answer from above has already mentioned it.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":2696,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/2696\/comments","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":37,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Derek B.","reputation":94,"email_hash":"5cd042fca607ac4194b8c448ec38ddf7"},"creation_date":1282288519,"last_activity_date":1282288519,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p><a href=\"http:\/\/omgubuntu.co.uk\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/omgubuntu.co.uk<\/a> showcases some occasionally.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":2515,"favorite_count":3,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/2502\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/2502\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/2502\/answers","question_id":2502,"owner":{"user_id":458,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Richard Holloway","reputation":2956,"email_hash":"ebeb96b621079b2daa21723f68a6db39"},"creation_date":1282065289,"last_edit_date":1282229993,"last_activity_date":1300456825,"up_vote_count":13,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":372,"score":13,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I get themes and eye-candy for my desktop?","body":"<p>Apart from those themes in the repository and Gnome-look.org are there other places to get themes for my Ubuntu Desktop.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, are there any 3rd party repositories of themes and other eye-candy?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["java","desktop-environments","looking-glass"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":29852,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29852\/comments","question_id":29844,"owner":{"user_id":6256,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"James Lee Denham","reputation":61,"email_hash":"16a8405cf9f6dbe70b9b3be928b48bd4"},"creation_date":1299797157,"last_edit_date":1299871960,"last_activity_date":1299871960,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":114,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I find a package for \"project looking Glass\"? (\"The Java desktop\")","body":"<p>Found this link for some source and additional info: <a href=\"http:\/\/java.net\/projects\/lg3d\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/java.net\/projects\/lg3d\/<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>You can get the software by using <a href=\"http:\/\/subversion.apache.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">subversion<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/apt.ubuntu.com\/p\/subversion\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/bit.ly\/software-small\" alt=\"install subverison\"><\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Enter the command:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>svn co https:\/\/svn.java.net\/svn\/lg3d~svn\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"answer_id":30839,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30839\/comments","question_id":29844,"owner":{"user_id":10698,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alvar","reputation":367,"email_hash":"f01cf0cc14447f738b549ab015b0e559"},"creation_date":1300403807,"last_activity_date":1300403807,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":114,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I find a package for \"project looking Glass\"? (\"The Java desktop\")","body":"<p>This credit should be all on @takkat and @octavianDamiean.<\/p>\n\n<p>@Takkat\nHe found <a href=\"http:\/\/sourceforge.net\/projects\/lg3d-livecd\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this ISO<\/a> almost immediately after I posted this question! And he try to use Virtual VM, but it didn't work so we had to re think this problem.<\/p>\n\n<p>I try to install the ISO on the ubuntu \"start up disc creator\" but it failed so I asked @octavianDamiean.\nHe said throw <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/30048\/how-can-i-create-a-bootable-usb-disk-from-a-cd-image\">this<\/a> question what I should do to boot from the ISO throw a USB-stick.  <\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":30839,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29844\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29844\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29844\/answers","question_id":29844,"owner":{"user_id":10698,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alvar","reputation":367,"email_hash":"f01cf0cc14447f738b549ab015b0e559"},"creation_date":1299794965,"last_edit_date":1300455602,"last_activity_date":1300455602,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":114,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Where can I find a package for \"project looking Glass\"? (\"The Java desktop\")","body":"<p>Hi, \nI really really want to find this package. Because after I saw the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=SMWd1FOgr18\" rel=\"nofollow\">youtube clip<\/a> I realized it's just one of those things I must have done before I die.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.ubuntugeek.com\/install-sun-looking-glass-desktop-environment-in-ubuntu.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">This tutorial<\/a> would be great if the repository were online.<\/p>\n\n<p>My question is:<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Where can I find the file, and how can I install it without changing my current desktop?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The project was called \"project looking glass\" and was released in 2007. It is now an \"inactive open source project\", according to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Project_Looking_Glass\" rel=\"nofollow\">its Wikipedia article<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>by using my answer I managed to make a boot able device and <\/p>\n\n<p>I had an error while booting so I will ask that question on <a href=\"http:\/\/unix.stackexchange.com\/\">http:\/\/unix.stackexchange.com\/<\/a> .<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["ppa","launchpad","search","package"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":16394,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/16394\/comments","question_id":16393,"owner":{"user_id":5691,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"karthick87","reputation":8739,"email_hash":"b41802fe7f333c0b2b2b68be7da4f757"},"creation_date":1291619828,"last_edit_date":1291620710,"last_activity_date":1291620710,"up_vote_count":6,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":92,"score":6,"community_owned":false,"title":"Search Launchpad for PPAs matching software or package name?","body":"<p>You can search for PPAs matching software or package in the following link<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+ppas\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+ppas<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/ibASN.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30905,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30905\/comments","question_id":16393,"owner":{"user_id":662,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alin Andrei","reputation":417,"email_hash":"f301ea9f912fe216ad8175baba86318c"},"creation_date":1300448749,"last_activity_date":1300448749,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":92,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Search Launchpad for PPAs matching software or package name?","body":"<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.webupd8.org\/2011\/01\/y-ppa-manager-004-released-with-new.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Y PPA Manager<\/a> can be used to search PPAs for a certain package. Once some PPAs are found, you can easily list the packages and see what other packages (and their versions) that PPA provides. Check it out... I think you'll like it :)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":16411,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/16411\/comments","question_id":16393,"owner":{"user_id":235,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jorge Castro","reputation":13044,"email_hash":"d4f7d15de2abdec49cacaac7d14f00fc"},"creation_date":1291639642,"last_activity_date":1291639642,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":92,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Search Launchpad for PPAs matching software or package name?","body":"<p><a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\/7639#7639\">ppasearch<\/a> looks handy for command line environments.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":16394,"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/16393\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/16393\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/16393\/answers","question_id":16393,"owner":{"user_id":41,"user_type":"moderator","display_name":"Marco Ceppi","reputation":9125,"email_hash":"c127c8150f8052e4b89d66f42b99be56"},"creation_date":1291619360,"last_edit_date":1300455560,"last_activity_date":1300455560,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":92,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Search Launchpad for PPAs matching software or package name?","body":"<p>Is there a way to search though LaunchPad's PPAs for a certain package name? For instance if I was looking for PPAs with Firefox packages I could search for \"firefox\" and retrieve a list of all the PPAs which contain a firefox package.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["webserver"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30921,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30921\/comments","question_id":30917,"owner":{"user_id":3778,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Kaustubh P","reputation":1978,"email_hash":"1d92cc045a796c912ab2e255ad9b3b65"},"creation_date":1300455348,"last_activity_date":1300455348,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":9,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I change so the Jetty webserver is listening on port 80?","body":"<p>You will need to edit the <code>\/etc\/jetty\/jetty.xml<\/code> file. Look for a paragraph that says:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;Call name=\"addConnector\"&gt;\n      &lt;Arg&gt;\n          &lt;New class=\"org.mortbay.jetty.nio.SelectChannelConnector\"&gt;\n            &lt;Set name=\"host\"&gt;&lt;SystemProperty name=\"jetty.host\" \/&gt;&lt;\/Set&gt;\n            &lt;Set name=\"port\"&gt;&lt;SystemProperty name=\"jetty.port\" default=\"8090\"\/&gt;&lt;\/Set&gt;\n            &lt;Set name=\"maxIdleTime\"&gt;30000&lt;\/Set&gt;\n            &lt;Set name=\"Acceptors\"&gt;2&lt;\/Set&gt;\n            &lt;Set name=\"statsOn\"&gt;false&lt;\/Set&gt;\n            &lt;Set name=\"confidentialPort\"&gt;8443&lt;\/Set&gt;\n        &lt;Set name=\"lowResourcesConnections\"&gt;5000&lt;\/Set&gt;\n        &lt;Set name=\"lowResourcesMaxIdleTime\"&gt;5000&lt;\/Set&gt;\n          &lt;\/New&gt;\n      &lt;\/Arg&gt;\n    &lt;\/Call&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Change the <code>jetty.port<\/code> Property to <code>80<\/code> as follows:<\/p>\n\n<p><code>&lt;Set name=\"port\"&gt;&lt;SystemProperty name=\"jetty.port\" default=\"80\"\/&gt;&lt;\/Set&gt;<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Restart jetty. That should do it.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":30921,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30917\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30917\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30917\/answers","question_id":30917,"owner":{"user_id":4692,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jonas","reputation":251,"email_hash":"894e4c1f3bc33e5f9a5008d355287830"},"creation_date":1300454084,"last_activity_date":1300455348,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":9,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I change so the Jetty webserver is listening on port 80?","body":"<p>I would like to use Jetty as a webserver.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have edited the configuration file at <code>\/etc\/default\/jetty<\/code> and set: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code># change to 0 to allow Jetty start\nNO_START=0\n\n# Listen to connections from this network host\n# Use 0.0.0.0 as host to accept all connections.\nJETTY_HOST=0.0.0.0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now I can reach the Jetty webserver at <code>http:\/\/192.168.1.10:8080<\/code> but I would like to have Jetty listening on port 80.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have tried this setting in the same configuration file:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code># The network port used by Jetty\nJETTY_PORT=80\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and then restart Jetty with <code>sudo service jetty restart<\/code> but it doesn't work.<\/p>\n\n<p>How can I change so that the Jetty webserver is listening on port 80?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","package-management"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":19646,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/19646\/comments","question_id":19640,"owner":{"user_id":5651,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Col","reputation":64,"email_hash":"ca1c8833c0b6e076b8833fbb75018f9c"},"creation_date":1293907013,"last_activity_date":1293907013,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":230,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Problem with APTonCD application","body":"<p>If you still have the original iso created by aptoncd you can do a restore from that directly. Follow the wizard through choosing<\/p>\n\n<p>Screen1: choose option <strong>restore<\/strong> <\/p>\n\n<p>Screen2: choose option <strong>load<\/strong> <\/p>\n\n<p>Screen3: choose option <strong>iso image<\/strong> you can browse to your iso image that you made before burning and it will load your packages for selection and let you restore. <\/p>\n\n<p>If you do not have the original iso still, I am sorry but I do not know.  <\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":19647,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/19647\/comments","question_id":19640,"owner":{"user_id":132,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Martin Owens -doctormo-","reputation":7611,"email_hash":"7f6f9e75239bfcc5bfb41014e9dc9a26"},"creation_date":1293907038,"last_activity_date":1293907038,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":230,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Problem with APTonCD application","body":"<p>It sounds like the DVD image is broken or not burned correctly. This could have been any number of issues.<\/p>\n\n<p>First thing to do is to check the dvd in another computer to confirm if it works or not there.<\/p>\n\n<p>If it does, then you have an odd problem with your Ubuntu machine, and you should try some other dvds in that drive.<\/p>\n\n<p>If it doesn't, then you may need to try and create another dvd.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":26594,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26594\/comments","question_id":19640,"owner":{"user_id":10929,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user10929","reputation":11,"email_hash":"54804568e20e79c970872dc57c5b164b"},"creation_date":1297837131,"last_activity_date":1297837131,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":230,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Problem with APTonCD application","body":"<p>I read somewhere that it is an issue with the cdrom mount points being generated dynamically. Some people were creating a symbolic link or whatever they are called so the disc can be seen from the same location as in older ubuntu releases where the mount point was static.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/19640\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/19640\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/19640\/answers","question_id":19640,"owner":{"user_id":8188,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Harikrishnan","reputation":26,"email_hash":"c004ab455a4d12902c8027674da142a4"},"creation_date":1293903649,"last_edit_date":1293905344,"last_activity_date":1300455218,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":230,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"Problem with APTonCD application","body":"<p>I created a iso image using aptoncd &amp; burned it to a dvd. Now when i tried to restore, the program does not detect the dvd in the drive. It shows \"Please insert a disc in the drive.\" and if we click \"ok\" it shows <code>E: Failed to mount the cdrom<\/code>. The dvd is in the drive itself.<\/p>\n\n<p>I tried <code>sudo lshw -C disk<\/code> and the output is:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>*-cdrom\n   description: DVD-RAM writer\n   product: DVDRAM GH22NS50\n   vendor: HL-DT-ST\n   physical id: 1\n   bus info: scsi@1:0.0.0\n   logical name: \/dev\/cdrom\n   logical name: \/dev\/cdrw\n   logical name: \/dev\/dvd\n   logical name: \/dev\/dvdrw\n   logical name: \/dev\/scd0\n   logical name: \/dev\/sr0\n   logical name: \/media\/APTonCD\n   logical name: \/media\/apt\n   version: TN02\n   capabilities: removable audio cd-r cd-rw dvd dvd-r dvd-ram\n   configuration: ansiversion=5 mount.fstype=iso9660 mount.options=ro,relatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,iocharset=utf8,mode=0400,dmode=0500 state=mounted status=ready\n *-medium\n      physical id: 0\n      logical name: \/dev\/cdrom\n      logical name: \/media\/APTonCD\n      logical name: \/media\/apt\n      configuration: mount.fstype=iso9660 mount.options=ro,relatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,iocharset=utf8,mode=0400,dmode=0500 state=mounted\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then i checked in disk utility application. in that dvd rom is shown as <code>\/dvd\/sr0<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>My ubuntu version is 10.10.           <\/p>\n\n<p>Please help me to solve the problem.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["vmware","shared","folders"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30920,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30920\/comments","question_id":29284,"owner":{"user_id":12598,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"snth","reputation":101,"email_hash":"d8aec090bed3518ebcb66c2063dbdf0b"},"creation_date":1300455167,"last_activity_date":1300455167,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":72,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I mount shared folders (win7 host) in Ubuntu (guest) using VMware(tools v6)","body":"<p>I've been having the same problem but I think I have just been able to make some progress.<\/p>\n\n<p>Type <code>vmware-hfgs<\/code> and then press the <code>&lt;Tab&gt;<\/code> key which will show you that there is also a <code>vmware-hgfsmounter<\/code> command. If you call that without any options it will print some help that shows you how to call this as part of the `mount' command. Using that info I then ran the following which worked for me:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>cd \/mnt\nsudo mkdir win7share\nsudo mount -t vmhgfs .host:\/win7share \/mnt\/win7share\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I was then able to access the Win 7 share and copy files to and from there. <\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to make this permanent then I suspect that you will need to edit the <code>\/etc\/fstab<\/code> file but I can't help you there yet.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":2,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29284\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29284\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29284\/answers","question_id":29284,"owner":{"user_id":10976,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"V-Light","reputation":11,"email_hash":"ebfad9dcc8d2c2c54f10c49dbe66af62"},"creation_date":1299432129,"last_edit_date":1299469683,"last_activity_date":1300455167,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":72,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I mount shared folders (win7 host) in Ubuntu (guest) using VMware(tools v6)","body":"<p>Hello, Experts. I've successfully installed VMware tools for Ubuntu. Everything seems to work fine, but shared folders were not mounted automatically.<br>\nHow do I get them to work?<\/p>\n\n<p>If I run <code>vmware-hgfsclient<\/code> in terminal, I get the list of shared folders, but <code>ls -l \/mnt\/hgfs<\/code> is empty. Actually there's no <code>hgfs<\/code> dir in <code>\/mnt<\/code>. I know I should probably use the <code>vmware-hgfsclient<\/code> tool, but I realy don't know how. <\/p>\n\n<p>P.S. I wouldn't ask if I could understand the <code>vmware-hgfsclient<\/code> help I've read. <\/p>\n\n<p>Any suggestions?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","tomboy"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30919\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30919\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30919\/answers","question_id":30919,"owner":{"user_id":9454,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"CaptnLenz","reputation":8,"email_hash":"4acb4a273d03ed3c0cb25b8d617bbdf1"},"creation_date":1300454933,"last_activity_date":1300454933,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":8,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"tomboy desktop integration","body":"<p>Hello,<\/p>\n\n<p>is there a possibility to integrate tomboy a bit more startling as the tray integration.\nI'm using on king of index-note where i always start in the navigation.\nMaybe it can show up this note everytime on startup?<\/p>\n\n<p>Hope there is a plugin or something:)<\/p>\n\n<p>greetings<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["package-management","firefox"],"answer_count":8,"answers":[{"answer_id":10776,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/10776\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":790,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Chris Coulson","reputation":622,"email_hash":"9fe1ff906cbd816123227e5778b62372"},"creation_date":1288631513,"last_edit_date":1300405741,"last_activity_date":1300405741,"up_vote_count":23,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":1715,"score":22,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>Semi-official packages of Firefox 4.0 will be maintained in the firefox-stable PPA, and will be based on the packages that we ship in Natty.<\/p>\n\n<p>To install the packages from this <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\">PPA<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:mozillateam\/firefox-stable\nsudo apt-get update &amp;&amp; sudo apt-get upgrade\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note, that this will upgrade your current Firefox version to 4.0. The packages in this PPA will not be parallel installable with the packages in the official Ubuntu archive.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can also report bugs against these packages to <a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu-mozilla-ppa-bugs\/+filebug\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu-mozilla-ppa-bugs\/+filebug<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":6348,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/6348\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":1418,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Peter Smit","reputation":860,"email_hash":"56586328ab69d46520cf729d2c46c58b"},"creation_date":1286876824,"last_edit_date":1300454510,"last_activity_date":1300454510,"up_vote_count":23,"down_vote_count":3,"view_count":1715,"score":20,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p><em>Note: this answer has been completely rewritten to be more time-generic<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~mozillateam\" rel=\"nofollow\">mozillateam<\/a> is the group who maintains Firefox packages for Ubuntu. Two of their channels are especially interesting, <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~mozillateam\/+archive\/firefox-stable\" rel=\"nofollow\">firefox-stable<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/~mozillateam\/+archive\/firefox-next\" rel=\"nofollow\">firefox-next<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The first contains the latest stable release of Firefox, the latter contains the latest alpha,beta or rc build.<\/p>\n\n<p>What I would advise to do is add both these PPA's.<\/p>\n\n<p>What will happen is the following: when you think a certain version of firefox has a mature enough release (for example beta) install it with it version name. e.g. firefox-4.0 After it is released this package will appear in the stable channel and you can keep using it until you decide to go to a new unstable version.<\/p>\n\n<p>How to add PPA is explained <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\">here<\/a> (both for command-line and graphical). The ppa's you need are:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>ppa:mozillateam\/firefox-stable\nppa:mozillateam\/firefox-next\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>After that install through the software center or on the command-line the version you want.<\/p>\n\n<p>Note, that this will upgrade your current Firefox version to 4.0. The packages in this PPA will not be parallel installable with the packages in the official Ubuntu archive.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can also report bugs against these packages to <a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu-mozilla-ppa-bugs\/+filebug\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu-mozilla-ppa-bugs\/+filebug<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>See also the <a href=\"https:\/\/help.ubuntu.com\/community\/FirefoxNewVersion\" rel=\"nofollow\">ubuntu wiki page about new Firefox versions<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":6376,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/6376\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":3004,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Huygens","reputation":995,"email_hash":"32857d0f2ac2a60aaba519222786d494"},"creation_date":1286881618,"last_edit_date":1286909161,"last_activity_date":1286909161,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1715,"score":4,"community_owned":true,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>There is 2 ways to install the Firefox 4 beta version. But first, here are a few points to learn before entering the beta:<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>A. Prior to test the Firefox 4 beta<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>1. Firefox Sync<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>If you are using Firefox Sync (previously called Weave). It is integrated in the beta. So you do not need the add-on. What does it implies to early adopter? Some glitches that the user of the final release won't notice.<\/p>\n\n<p>Mozilla needs to enhance the scalability of the Sync architecture, as this is going to be directly incorporated in the Firefox 4 release, the number of user is going to grow. So they change quite a few bit of the Sync architecture, that's why you probably saw an new update of the add-on if you're using it with the current stable release. Now this add-on is in version 1.5 (incompatible with add-on of earlier release, which means if you've updated this add-on on one of your Firefox, you have to do it on all the other).<\/p>\n\n<p>As far as I know the current beta of Firefox (beta 6) is \"compatible\" with the Sync 1.4 protocol, so Sync will not work any longer with the beta if you have updated your add-on to the 1.5 release. However, as soon as beta 7 is out (should be days now), this will work.<\/p>\n\n<p>On the other side, if you're still using the 1.4 version of the Sync add-on on your stable Firefox release, then it should work with the beta 6, and as soon as you upgrade to beta 7, it will migrate your Sync data to the new architecture. So if you want to still use Firefox 3.6 on other machine, you will have to upgrade the add-on.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you are definitively using Firefox 4 on a machine, you can uninstall the Firefox Sync plug-in, as it is not needed anymore.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>2. Warnings<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>This is still a beta, so things don't work always. They are still numerous slowdown, site that don't work (e.g. one.ubuntu.com is partly broken, I cannot upload file, or publish them from the web interface).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>B. A generic way<\/strong>, that work on all Linux distribution<\/p>\n\n<p>You can either go to <a href=\"http:\/\/www.mozilla.com\/en-US\/firefox\/beta\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Firefox Beta page<\/a> and download the latest beta. But this will download the 32bit version of Firefox, which is buggy on a 64bit system. Or you could go to <a href=\"http:\/\/releases.mozilla.org\/pub\/mozilla.org\/firefox\/releases\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Firefox Repository page<\/a> where you can find the link for the latest beta (currently 4.0b6) then choose linux-x86_64 for the 64bit version, then select your language or en_US for English. And there you can download the file ending in .bz2<\/p>\n\n<p>Then you could create a directory where you're going to test this release of Firefox, unpack the downloaded package (I assume it is in your $HOME\/Downloads folder) and launch it:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>cd $HOME\nmkdir Apps\ncd Apps\ntar jxf ~\/Downloads\/firefox-4.0b*.tar.bz2\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>To launch it, it's probably more interesting to create a \"Launcher\" (Gnome specific), an icon on your desktop to launch the beta. I guess there are similar steps for KDE. For this:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Display your Desktop<\/li>\n<li>Right click and choose <code>Create launcher...<\/code> from the popup menu<\/li>\n<li>Type <code>Firefox 4 beta<\/code> for the name<\/li>\n<li>Next to <code>Command<\/code> click on the \"Browse\" button, and browser through to the Apps -> firefox and select <code>firefox<\/code><\/li>\n<li>Click on <code>OK<\/code> and double-click the Launcher :-)<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p><strong>C. An Ubuntu specific way<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>You just have to add the Mozilla Daily PPA to your list of sources. There is a really good answered question about what is a PPA and how to add one, so I'm not going to repeat it here, just check the answers here: <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\">What are PPAs and how do I use them<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The PPA name to add (you will need it when you will follow the answers) is: <code>ppa:ubuntu-mozilla-daily<\/code> And Install Firefox 4 Beta as instructed in the same answered question.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Warning<\/strong> As some others have warned, take care that this PPA contains Firefox and a bunch of other Mozilla applications in beta. So choose carefully which ones you want to install.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":6395,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/6395\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":2950,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"lovinglinux","reputation":2565,"email_hash":"73c1778606201bd3dcff1987f2e9782e"},"creation_date":1286886068,"last_edit_date":1294181646,"last_activity_date":1294181646,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1715,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>There are several methods of installing a non-default version of Firefox, that are covered by my tutorial <a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/installing-other-versions\" rel=\"nofollow\">Installing Other Versions<\/a>, which has detailed explanations and method comparisons. So I will post here only the relevant information regarding Firefox 4. Please do not use multiple methods. Pick one and stick with it or revert the changes before trying a different one. I recommend the manual installation method, since depending on the PPA you choose, you will also update Firefox 3.6 and other Mozilla products.<\/p>\n\n<p>Since it is still a Beta release and there are some radical changes in this version, is recommended that you install it side-by-side with the default version and use a different <a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/profiles-and-backups\" rel=\"nofollow\">user profile<\/a>, in order to avoid data loss.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Method #1 - Manual Download &amp; Installation<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>First you need to download it form Mozilla [pick one only]:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http:\/\/www.mozilla.com\/en-US\/firefox\/beta\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">latest \"stable\" beta release<\/a> [32bit only]<\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http:\/\/nightly.mozilla.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">latest nightly builds<\/a> [32bit and 64bit]<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>The easiest way to install Firefox 4 downloaded from Mozilla is to use my extension <a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/addons\/foxtester\" rel=\"nofollow\">FoxTester<\/a>. It allows you to instal any number of different Firefox versions, without interfering with your default installation and user profile. Everything is done through Firefox context menu, without typing commands or even closing Firefox. Although this extension is not intended for upgrading Firefox, it also allows to make any version installation permanent.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you prefer to do it manually, then follow the instructions of method #1 from the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/installing-other-versions\" rel=\"nofollow\">Installing Other Versions<\/a> tutorial. Basically, you will extract the downloaded file to your \/home directory or the \/opt and execute the firefox file inside it. There are also additional steps on that tutorial if you want to make it fully compatible with plugins.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Method #2 - Ubuntuzilla repository<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>This method will only be available to 32bit users, after the release of the final version of Firefox 4.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Method #3 - Installing from PPA repositories<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Firefox 4 is currently available through <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/%7Eubuntu-mozilla-daily\/+archive\/ppa\" rel=\"nofollow\">ubuntu-mozilla-daily<\/a> PPA repository (semi-official) and <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=1352580\" rel=\"nofollow\">SilverWave<\/a> PPA repository (non-official). You need to add one of those ppa repositories to your sources list, then update and install Firefox 4.<\/p>\n\n<p>To install from ubuntu-mozilla-daily on Karmic, Lucid or Maverick, run the following commands:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:ubuntu-mozilla-daily\/ppa\nsudo apt-get update\nsudo apt-get install firefox-4.0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>For additional info about PPA repositories see <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\">What are PPAs and how do I use them?<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>To install from SilverWave PPA, see <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=1352580\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=1352580<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Notes:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><i>    The ubuntu-mozilla-daily ppa also upgrade your default Firefox installation with the latest testing version of Firefox 3.x and other Mozilla applications. So although the SilverWave PP is not official, it might be less troublesome to use it instead.<\/i><\/li>\n<li><i>When you install Firefox 4 using one of those repositories, a clone of your Firefox user profile is created under ~\/.mozilla\/firefox-4.0. So everything you do on Firefox 4 won't be saved on your default profile. This could cause confusion and apparent loss of data (bookmarks, passwords...) if you switch back and forth between Firefox 3.6 and Firefox 4 or when the last one becomes default and start using the default profile folder (i.e ~\/.mozilla\/firefox).<\/i><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>Add-on Compatibility<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>During the beta phase and to some extent after the final release of Firefox 4, most extensions and themes won't be compatible with it and thus not activated. Usually when you are testing a minor update version, you can disable compatibility check, to force extensions to be installed and activated. But is not so simple in this case, due to radical changes in the UI and the extension API of Firefox 4. So even with the compatibility check disable, several extensions won't work at all or could break other extensions and even Firefox.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you are using a different profile or make regular <a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/profiles-and-backups\" rel=\"nofollow\">backups<\/a>, then you could use the <a href=\"https:\/\/addons.mozilla.org\/en-US\/firefox\/addon\/15003\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Addon Compatibility Reporter<\/a> extension, to disable the compatibility.<\/p>\n\n<p>If something goes wrong and you can't even access the add-ons manager to disable the extensions, then <a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/extension-optimization\" rel=\"nofollow\">start Firefox in safe mode and disable all extensions<\/a>. After starting Firefox in safe mode, you can enable only the compatible ones.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is strongly advised to start the \"Error Console\" (CTRL+SHIFT+J) while using Firefox with extensions that are incompatible. Disable any extension that cause an error. You might have to enable only the error report to avoid lots of css messages from web sites.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Optimization<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Although Firefox 4 is a lot faster than Firefox 3.6, is always a good idea to keep it fast by optimizing databases and tweaking some preferences.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/database-optimization\" rel=\"nofollow\">Database Optimization<\/a>: improves startup time and performance considerably, specially on features like the awesome bar suggestions or bookmark management.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.webgapps.org\/firefox\/preferences-tweaks\" rel=\"nofollow\">Preferences Tweaks<\/a>: improves network speed, page rendering, memory usage and fixes some common issues.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/addons.mozilla.org\/en-US\/firefox\/addon\/67651\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">BarTab<\/a>: this nice extension allows to prevent tabs from loading the page content until they are needed. So if you usually start Firefox with several tabs, this will save memory space and improve startup time and responsiveness.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/addons.mozilla.org\/en-US\/firefox\/addon\/6371\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Better Cache<\/a>: this extension allows to better control how Firefox handle the content cache, allowing to avoid constantly reloading pages and elements, thus reducing page display time considerably. Make sure you read the manual, because you might prevent sites that need to constantly reloaded from displaying new content (works with compatibility disabled).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Customization<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The very anticipated new UI hasn't been released for Linux yet. So, Firefox 4 still looks very similar to 3.6, except for a few changes, like for example the ability to place tabs on top [View &gt;&gt; Toolbars &gt;&gt; Tabs on Top]. Nevertheless, you can change a lot of things as usual, using the built-in options, themes, scripts, extensions or changing the userChrome.css.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":6446,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/6446\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":3581,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"pianom4n","reputation":27,"email_hash":"f7384cb64315953606376b956cdd80f1"},"creation_date":1286894611,"last_activity_date":1286894611,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":2,"view_count":1715,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>Here is what I found works best:<\/p>\n\n<p>Download it from mozilla.com and extract it (to wherever you want). It creates a folder called \"firefox\" and in that folder there is a file called \"firefox\". Drag this file onto your panel, and it asks you to give the new launcher a name (call it Firefox, but it doesn't matter), and you're done.  To open Firefox just use the new launcher on the panel (the correct icon should be there automatically).<\/p>\n\n<p>Be wary though that the <code>firefox<\/code> command still opens your old installation.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30362,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30362\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":12067,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Hossam Riyad","reputation":98,"email_hash":"49eb15afcb55e8d592394326e45c2e71"},"creation_date":1300126504,"last_edit_date":1300127054,"last_activity_date":1300127054,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1715,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>step 1 :\n Setup the Mozilla - Ubuntu daily PPA and update your package list using the following command:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:ubuntu-mozilla-daily\/ppa &amp;&amp; sudo apt-get update\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>step 2:\nAfter the repository gets updated, you can install Firefox-4.0 on your Ubuntu system using the following command:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get install firefox-4.0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"answer_id":30868,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30868\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1300425374,"last_activity_date":1300425374,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1715,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>You can add the <code>ppa:mozillateam\/firefox-next<\/code> PPA which holds the Release builds(alpha, beta, RC) of the current development version of Firefox which currently is rc1.<\/p>\n\n<p>Firstly add the PPA <code>ppa:mozillateam\/firefox-next<\/code>(<a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4983\/what-are-ppas-and-how-do-i-use-them\">How to Add a PPA<\/a>) then install firefox-4.0 from the software center.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30364,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30364\/comments","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":8453,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Abhijeet","reputation":107,"email_hash":"6ac5ae4d0605656d55ae4ee75668f0ac"},"creation_date":1300126781,"last_edit_date":1300188277,"last_activity_date":1300188277,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":2,"view_count":1715,"score":-1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>hi,\nright now I suggest you not to install the firefox. Just download the tar file from <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.mozilla.com\/en-US\/firefox\/RC\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Download firefox 4<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Untar this tar file in your home and double click the file run-mozilla.sh and you will have your firefox 4. If you want you can create a shortcut to the home folder for instant access.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":6348,"favorite_count":7,"bounty_closes_date":1300993966,"bounty_amount":100,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/6339\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/6339\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/6339\/answers","question_id":6339,"owner":{"user_id":3445,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"danimajo","reputation":233,"email_hash":"4dd6c1c4728fd99a71b1cf6a6082d0bd"},"creation_date":1286874525,"last_edit_date":1300133773,"last_activity_date":1300454510,"up_vote_count":26,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1715,"score":26,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I install Firefox 4 Beta and RC?","body":"<p>I want to install Firefox Version 4 Beta on my Ubuntu (64bit) box.<\/p>\n\n<p>What is the best way to do this? Is there a specific update site or should I download the binaries manually? If doing manually, in which directory should I put the files? In my home directory, or is there a better place?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["unity","nomenclature"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":10245,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/10245\/comments","question_id":10228,"owner":{"user_id":2181,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"mgunes","reputation":4339,"email_hash":"bc8506ff5f5d6efe8d699350e56a494b"},"creation_date":1288354242,"last_edit_date":1300213908,"last_activity_date":1300213908,"up_vote_count":25,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":1409,"score":24,"community_owned":false,"title":"What's the right terminology for Unity's UI elements?","body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>Is the bar at the top called \"panel\"?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Does the Ubuntu logo at the top left\n  corner have a name?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>It's called the \"home button\" though it's jokingly referred to as the <a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/unity\/+bug\/681504\" rel=\"nofollow\">BFB by developers<\/a>, for \"Big Freaking Button\"<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Is the left sidebar called \"dock\"?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>It's called the Launcher.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Are the coloured tiles with app icons\n  on them called \"launchers\"?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>\"Launcher icons\" or \"Launcher items\".<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Is the purple tile called \"workspace\n  switcher\"?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Are the fullscreen things that appear\n  when you click the Ubuntu logo, the\n  Places tile or the Apps tile, called\n  \"dash\"? Do they all have the same\n  name?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Right; \"Dash\" is the component name for <a href=\"http:\/\/imgur.com\/UOVbp.png\" rel=\"nofollow\">the overlay<\/a> that's used for Applications and Places. In non-technical contexts it seems to be used as the Applications Dash and the Places Dash<\/p>\n\n<h3>Other Terms<\/h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>The menu is referred to as the <a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/DesktopExperienceTeam\/ApplicationMenu\" rel=\"nofollow\">Application Menu<\/a>, not global menu. This is to distinguish it from the other <a href=\"http:\/\/code.google.com\/p\/gnome2-globalmenu\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">global menu<\/a> project. <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>There seems to be no term decided upon for items kept on the launcher via the \"Keep in launcher\" function. The relevant dbusmenu functionality is named \"pinning_item\" in the code; \"sticky\" doesn't appear anywhere in the wiki and bug reports, and \"Favorites\" is used in the architecture document once and somewhat ambiguously to refer to what seems to be the \"pinned\" application items. So \"Pinned\" and \"Favorites\" seem both fine for now.<\/p>\n\n<p>For further information, see the <a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/Unity?action=AttachFile&amp;do=view&amp;target=Unity_Architecture.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Unity Architecture<\/a> document, and <a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/Unity\/Lenses\" rel=\"nofollow\">\/Unity\/Lenses<\/a> on the wiki.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":19166,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/19166\/comments","question_id":10228,"owner":{"user_id":1067,"user_type":"moderator","display_name":"Stefano Palazzo","reputation":13752,"email_hash":"040289b472d3404383959370d112ea48"},"creation_date":1293574724,"last_edit_date":1300454303,"last_activity_date":1300454303,"up_vote_count":16,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1409,"score":16,"community_owned":false,"title":"What's the right terminology for Unity's UI elements?","body":"<p>In addition to mgunes' great answer:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/kw77f.png\" alt=\"alt text\">\n<img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/CacMM.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Launcher<\/li>\n<li>Launcher Items<\/li>\n<li><p>Workspace Switcher<\/p>\n\n<p>Menu Bar:<\/p><\/li>\n<li>Window Title<\/li>\n<li>Application Menu<\/li>\n<li><p>The Indicators:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Network Indicator<\/li>\n<li>Sound Menu<\/li>\n<li>Messaging Menu<\/li>\n<li>Clock<\/li>\n<li>Me Menu<\/li>\n<li>Session Menu<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>And others<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Window Decoration<\/p><\/li>\n<li>Window Buttons<\/li>\n<li>Toolbar<\/li>\n<li>Status Bar<\/li>\n<li>Desktop<\/li>\n<li>Home Button<\/li>\n<li>Dash<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":10245,"favorite_count":6,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/10228\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/10228\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/10228\/answers","question_id":10228,"owner":{"user_id":4862,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Bou","reputation":867,"email_hash":"1cf1cab341dfd899d862d1490ce78775"},"creation_date":1288348094,"last_edit_date":1299904680,"last_activity_date":1300454303,"up_vote_count":22,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1409,"score":22,"community_owned":false,"title":"What's the right terminology for Unity's UI elements?","body":"<p>Hi, <\/p>\n\n<p>I've sent a few mails to the Ayatana mailing list regarding some UI suggestions for Unity, but I'm afraid I keep confusing the right terms for the UI element, so I would like to have some clarification.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Is the bar at the top called \"panel\"?<\/li>\n<li>Does the Ubuntu logo at the top left corner have a name?<\/li>\n<li>Is the left sidebar called \"dock\"?<\/li>\n<li>Are the coloured tiles with app icons on them called \"launchers\"?<\/li>\n<li>Is the purple tile called \"workspace switcher\"?<\/li>\n<li>Are the fullscreen things that appear when you click the Ubuntu logo, the Places tile or the Apps tile, called \"dash\"? Do they all have the same name?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","gnome","keyboard","shortcuts"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30918\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30918\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30918\/answers","question_id":30918,"owner":{"user_id":12597,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"c089","reputation":101,"email_hash":"a367f00d21bc986d5f74f6b56dabddb6"},"creation_date":1300454208,"last_activity_date":1300454208,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":5,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Broken keyboard shortcuts","body":"<p>When I freshly installed maverick on my new notebook, I set up my keyboard shortcuts like this: Switch to WS 1 = <code>Mod4+1<\/code>, Move Window to WS 1 = <code>Mod4+Shift+1<\/code>, Switch to WS 2 = <code>Mod4+2<\/code> and so on (Mod4 being the \"Windows\" key). But now the three-key combinations (i.e. the ones I use for \"move to...\") stopped working. When I go to keyboard preferences, I still see them and I can even change them to a different combination and then again to the desired one - but they won't execute the window movement afterwards :\/ Any suggestions how to fix this?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["firefox","fonts","font-rendering"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":30207,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30207\/comments","question_id":29827,"owner":{"user_id":4501,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"JPL","reputation":56,"email_hash":"1e35100c2ad64263e5a3345d22a202db"},"creation_date":1300041356,"last_activity_date":1300041356,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Weird font hinting in Firefox 4","body":"<p>I had something like this problem a while back, and tried all the stuff suggested in those posts.  What finally fixed it for me was simply removing <code>~\/.fonts.conf<\/code> (after a backup, of course).<\/p>\n\n<p>The reason I think this works is because the system-wide config is in <code>\/etc\/font\/fonts.conf<\/code>, and that file gets generated by <code>fontconfig<\/code>.  I think my problematic <code>~\/.fonts.conf<\/code> was left over from a much older (Dapper Drake era) install.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30910,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30910\/comments","question_id":29827,"owner":{"user_id":790,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Chris Coulson","reputation":622,"email_hash":"9fe1ff906cbd816123227e5778b62372"},"creation_date":1300450831,"last_edit_date":1300453409,"last_activity_date":1300453409,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Weird font hinting in Firefox 4","body":"<p>Firefox (correctly) uses fontconfig to determine the font properties based on a set of rules, and then falls back to the GNOME settings for any properties that were not determined by fontconfig. This allows you to configure things such as per-font hinting settings etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>The issue is that we (incorrectly) ship the match-all rules in fontconfig for antialias and hinting settings. This means that the fontconfig settings <em>always<\/em> override the GNOME settings in Firefox, and is really a bug in our fontconfig package.<\/p>\n\n<p>This looks like part of the problem that you are seeing.<\/p>\n\n<p>To fix this, you can do the following:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo rm \/etc\/fonts\/conf.d\/10-*\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note that \/etc\/fonts\/conf.d just contains a set of symlinks to the full set of configuration files in \/etc\/fonts\/conf.avail. To restore the default configuration in Ubuntu, you can run:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>cd \/etc\/fonts\/conf.d\nsudo ln -s \/etc\/fonts\/conf.avail\/10-antialias.conf\nsudo ln -s \/etc\/fonts\/conf.avail\/10-hinting.conf\nsudo ln -s \/etc\/fonts\/conf.avail\/10-hinting-slight.conf\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Also, your fonts may look slightly different depending on which build of Firefox you use. The Ubuntu build of Firefox carries a cairo patch to turn on Freetype LCD filtering, which will make its fonts look similar to those of other applications and reduce colour fringing.<\/p>\n\n<p>The official mozilla.org build does not have this patch, and its fonts will have noticeably more colour fringing compared to fonts in other applications.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":29834,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29834\/comments","question_id":29827,"owner":{"user_id":449,"user_type":"moderator","display_name":"Oli","reputation":20546,"email_hash":"f0af40756420859b5b63cbceb6d30505"},"creation_date":1299791383,"last_activity_date":1299791383,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Weird font hinting in Firefox 4","body":"<p>The suggestion from previous threads (I think I have one lurking around somewhere) is Firefox doesn't look to Gnome for font hinting settings, it goes to <code>fontconfig<\/code> which isn't synced in.<\/p>\n\n<p>So if you're using full-hinting, you want something like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>cd \/etc\/fonts\/conf.d\/\nsudo rm 10-hinting-slight.conf\nsudo ln -s ..\/conf.avail\/10-hinting-full.conf\nsudo dpkg-reconfigure fontconfig\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>There are literally dozens of suggested fixes in <a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/firefox-3.5\/+bug\/379761?comments=all\" rel=\"nofollow\">this bug report<\/a> though. I suggest you look for the saner looking ones, give them a try and if they don't work, have a go with the less sane looking ones.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'll try and track down what fixed it for me. I remember it was rediculously simple.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30174,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30174\/comments","question_id":29827,"owner":{"user_id":1029,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Bobby","reputation":472,"email_hash":"96d7c823e1a4c990ebcbc0bffa719020"},"creation_date":1300016050,"last_activity_date":1300016050,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Weird font hinting in Firefox 4","body":"<p>If I remember right, Firefox uses the file <code>~\/.fonts.conf<\/code> to get his font-settings. If it doesn't exist, just create it with the following content:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\"?&gt;\n&lt;!DOCTYPE fontconfig SYSTEM \"fonts.dtd\"&gt;\n&lt;fontconfig&gt;\n  &lt;match target=\"font\"&gt;\n    &lt;edit name=\"antialias\" mode=\"assign\"&gt;&lt;bool&gt;true&lt;\/bool&gt;&lt;\/edit&gt;\n  &lt;\/match&gt;\n  &lt;match target=\"font\"&gt;\n    &lt;edit name=\"hintstyle\" mode=\"assign\"&gt;&lt;const&gt;hintfull&lt;\/const&gt;&lt;\/edit&gt;\n  &lt;\/match&gt;\n&lt;\/fontconfig&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"bounty_closes_date":1300616851,"bounty_amount":100,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29827\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29827\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29827\/answers","question_id":29827,"owner":{"user_id":12082,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"sexyprout","reputation":26,"email_hash":"afb2c221f41d3081b023bb7f76f69578"},"creation_date":1299787169,"last_edit_date":1299793005,"last_activity_date":1300453409,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"Weird font hinting in Firefox 4","body":"<p>Hi everyone. I know this a recurrent topic but I just can't find a decent solution--although I found one for Chrome.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Just take look at the following screenshots:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>Chrome 9<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/N0qXE.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/N0qXE.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/a><\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Firefox 4  <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/WodsT.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/WodsT.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/a><\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>See the slight difference? I can't identify the exact difference but I can tell fonts in Chrome look smoother.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Here are my system preferences (prefer to show a screenshot as I don't know the <em>exact<\/em> translations in English):  <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/ZjcCA.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Anyone got a solution? Thanks.  <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Update<\/strong>: from my point of view, it doesn't seem to actually be a hinting problem. I'd say Firefox uses subpixel rendering instead of grayscale rendering. (yet I can't find the setting in <code>fontconfig<\/code>) But <em>this is a subjective opinion<\/em>, can you confirm?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["unity","11.04","dropbox","notification-area"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30748,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30748\/comments","question_id":30742,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1300357164,"last_edit_date":1300453369,"last_activity_date":1300453369,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":95,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I access the system tray?","body":"<p>You have to whitelist dropbox (and your other applications) to allow them to access the system tray.<\/p>\n\n<p>Press <kbd>Alt<\/kbd> + <kbd>F2<\/kbd> and paste <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gsettings set com.canonical.Unity.Panel systray-whitelist \"['JavaEmbeddedFrame', 'Wine','Skype','Dropbox']\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"answer_id":30777,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30777\/comments","question_id":30742,"owner":{"user_id":1992,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Roland Taylor","reputation":6690,"email_hash":"d629b6ac45d58dbd918c0246b364748d"},"creation_date":1300371977,"last_edit_date":1300440924,"last_activity_date":1300440924,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":95,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I access the system tray?","body":"<p>You can upgrade dropbox (as in the latest builds it has an indicator on ubuntu).\nFor other applications, if the developers do not add indicator support for them, you can simply whitelist them as Alaukik says, and also notify the developer that they need to fix the application.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30742\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30742\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30742\/answers","question_id":30742,"owner":{"user_id":6699,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jon","reputation":247,"email_hash":"3c7af62d226bc7420d49128d03a5b139"},"creation_date":1300353084,"last_edit_date":1300371780,"last_activity_date":1300453369,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":95,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I access the system tray?","body":"<p>So I'm messing around with Natty a little, and I noticed that all the apps that would normally use the system tray (or \"notification area\"?) aren't displaying there. Is that a bug, or is that the way it's going to be? I heard something about Ubuntu getting rid of that feature entirely. Is there a way to add it back? I mean, I didn't really like it, either, especially when there were apps that used it unnecessarily, but I can't use CryptKeeper at all now, or easycrypt, and I don't know whether Dropbox has synced without opening Nautilus. <\/p>\n"},{"tags":["firewall","ufw"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":30789,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30789\/comments","question_id":30781,"owner":{"user_id":861,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Scaine","reputation":3462,"email_hash":"0f9bda74e3a976957db2ab8bb277cb58"},"creation_date":1300376513,"last_activity_date":1300376513,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"See configured rules even when inactive","body":"<p>From the command line, there doesn't seem to be a way.  However, if you're SSH'ing from an Ubuntu box (to an Ubuntu box), you might want to try this, slightly convoluted method :<\/p>\n\n<p>Basically, install gufw on the remote box, then connect with X forwarding and run the GUI.<\/p>\n\n<p>On the remote device, after connecting with <code>-X<\/code> as an option :<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get install gufw\nsudo gufw\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>That will show you the ruleset without having to activate it.<\/p>\n\n<p>Be warned that if the remote device is a true \"headless\" server, then installing GUFW might pull down an unpleasant number of dependencies.  But unless someone here know a trick to make UFW show you the output you need without activating it first, then this might be your only option.<\/p>\n\n<p>I did try <code>sudo ufw show raw<\/code>, but that shows the iptables output, which I can't make head nor tail of.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30800,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30800\/comments","question_id":30781,"owner":{"user_id":9340,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"arrange","reputation":1086,"email_hash":"c71e30af876e731128bee852de255a22"},"creation_date":1300381261,"last_activity_date":1300381261,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"See configured rules even when inactive","body":"<p>General rules are in <code>\/etc\/ufw<\/code>. User defined rules are in <code>\/lib\/ufw\/user*<\/code>.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30916,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30916\/comments","question_id":30781,"owner":{"user_id":5020,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jdstrand","reputation":336,"email_hash":"b01ac1ceca8e6f343727dd008d28778e"},"creation_date":1300453003,"last_activity_date":1300453003,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"See configured rules even when inactive","body":"<p>There is currently not a way to show the rules you have entered before enabling the firewall via the CLI command. You can inspect the rules files directly however. \/lib\/ufw\/user*.rules contain the rules controlled via the 'ufw' CLI command. Eg:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> $ sudo grep '^### tuple' \/lib\/ufw\/user*.rules\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will show output like the following (for the rule added with 'sudo ufw allow OpenSSH):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> \/lib\/ufw\/user.rules:### tuple ### allow tcp 22 0.0.0.0\/0 any 0.0.0.0\/0 OpenSSH - in\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The 'tuple' is the shorthand used internally by ufw to keep track of rules, and can be interpreted as one of these:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> ### tuple ### &lt;action&gt; &lt;proto&gt; &lt;dst port&gt; &lt;dst&gt; &lt;src port&gt; &lt;src&gt; &lt;direction&gt;\n ### tuple ### &lt;action&gt; &lt;proto&gt; &lt;dst port&gt; &lt;dst&gt; &lt;src port&gt; &lt;src&gt; &lt;dst app name&gt; &lt;src app name&gt; &lt;direction&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>It might be useful to be able to add another status command to support this. Please consider filing a bug.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30781\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30781\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30781\/answers","question_id":30781,"owner":{"user_id":11409,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Bryan","reputation":38,"email_hash":"daa4a4e3efd674c83d6a504d31a18ea9"},"creation_date":1300373308,"last_edit_date":1300405082,"last_activity_date":1300453003,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"See configured rules even when inactive","body":"<p>Hello,<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm wondering if it's possible to get UFW to list the configured firewall rules even when it's not enabled. I only have ssh access to the server at this time, and I don't want to enable UFW if there's not a rule configured allowing ssh. However, since UFW is currently not enabled, I just get an \"inactive\" message when I run \"ufw status\".<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a special flag I can use or even some config file I can look at to see what rules are configured even when the firewall is disabled?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["command-line","terminal","man"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":28791,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28791\/comments","question_id":28788,"owner":{"user_id":9598,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Geppettvs D'Constanzo","reputation":1450,"email_hash":"4d2570453441053a1f6c5a51abc92a57"},"creation_date":1299112293,"last_edit_date":1299119523,"last_activity_date":1299119523,"up_vote_count":8,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":85,"score":8,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to jump to the end of a 'man' page","body":"<p>When inside of the document viewer through the man command, press <kbd>h<\/kbd> or <kbd>H<\/kbd> in order to view the man's help.<\/p>\n\n<p>From man's help screen:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>JUMPING\n\n  g  &lt;  ESC-&lt;       *  Go to first line in file (or line N).\n  G  &gt;  ESC-&gt;       *  Go to last line in file (or line N).\n  p  %              *  Go to beginning of file (or N percent into file).\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Another good idea would be to press the <kbd>Home<\/kbd> or the <kbd>End<\/kbd> keys. :)<\/p>\n\n<p>Good luck!<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":28790,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28790\/comments","question_id":28788,"owner":{"user_id":1128,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Kwinto","reputation":11,"email_hash":"963b379fa9791aabab7ba5ea55096de4"},"creation_date":1299111663,"last_edit_date":1300452667,"last_activity_date":1300452667,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":85,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to jump to the end of a 'man' page","body":"<ul>\n<li><p>Press <kbd>G<\/kbd><\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Press <kbd>q<\/kbd><\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>You can type <code>man less<\/code> to get more information.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":28834,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28834\/comments","question_id":28788,"owner":{"user_id":8844,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jgbelacqua","reputation":2949,"email_hash":"4808cca0b254b6203fc9bdf4d9e58e09"},"creation_date":1299139875,"last_edit_date":1299140706,"last_activity_date":1299140706,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":85,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to jump to the end of a 'man' page","body":"<p>The normal ways to do this have been suggested (see @geppettvs-dconstanzo's answer).  This leaves numerous unnatural, wrong, and bad ways.   <\/p>\n\n<p>So I'll deal with a couple of those. <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>First, you don't have to read the man pages from a terminal (even though it will make you a better person).  You can read them in html, for instance. <\/p>\n\n<p>You can generate the html yourself from the sources on your system, but it's easier to go to <a href=\"http:\/\/manpages.ubuntu.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">manpages.ubuntu.com<\/a> .<\/p>\n\n<p>Here's the hefty <code>bash<\/code> page, turned into light and fluffy web-renderable html :<br>\n<a href=\"http:\/\/manpages.ubuntu.com\/manpages\/maverick\/man1\/bash.1.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Bash Manpage from manpages.ubuntu.com<\/a><\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Here's a hack that can actually be useful :  use <code>tail<\/code> to slice off some number of lines from the end of the man page output, and view that.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Least usefully, most trivally: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>man bash | tail -100\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>might be useful : <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>man bash | tail -1500 | more\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>(or <code>man bash | tail -1500 | less<\/code>)<\/p>\n\n<p>More useful (if contrived): <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ man bash | wc -l    # how many lines are in the man-page?\n5375\n$ man bash | tail -2600 | less  # jump to the middle of the output\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Of course, this is what I'd do: <\/p>\n\n<p><code>man tac | tac | less<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>(Although you might start out reading <code>man tac<\/code> forwards.)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30911,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30911\/comments","question_id":28788,"owner":{"user_id":12595,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Chander","reputation":1,"email_hash":"a37779fbfe1440a4089c6f71023b20ce"},"creation_date":1300450890,"last_activity_date":1300450890,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":85,"score":-1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to jump to the end of a 'man' page","body":"<p>Press <strong>q<\/strong> to come baack to your command prompt. <\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":28791,"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/28788\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/28788\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/28788\/answers","question_id":28788,"owner":{"user_id":2978,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"richzilla","reputation":1296,"email_hash":"1e2a494a20e7debf9c885f2edfd9483e"},"creation_date":1299110994,"last_edit_date":1299134925,"last_activity_date":1300452667,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":85,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to jump to the end of a 'man' page","body":"<p>When I open up the manual for a command (<code>man wget<\/code> for example) the manual can be many hundreds of lines long. How can I get: <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>to the end of the manual quickly and<\/li>\n<li>back to my terminal prompt?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n"},{"tags":["evolution","ldap","ms-exchange"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30914\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30914\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30914\/answers","question_id":30914,"owner":{"user_id":12303,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"pedrorolo","reputation":1,"email_hash":"daacb6d0a16d95a3858ccae59b44860d"},"creation_date":1300451684,"last_edit_date":1300452309,"last_activity_date":1300452309,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":4,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How To Configure Evolution To Use DavMail's LDAP contacts?","body":"<p>My doubts are in the Authentication Section:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Authentication Method ?!<\/li>\n<li>Session?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>And I also don't know how to fill in the Details tab:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Search base ?<\/li>\n<li>Search Scope ?<\/li>\n<li>Search filter ?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>How should I fill these in?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["evolution","ms-exchange"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":29255,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29255\/comments","question_id":29188,"owner":{"user_id":6450,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Allan","reputation":2260,"email_hash":"ee2c87a3ad81c5394d119a6a2bf026a1"},"creation_date":1299420596,"last_activity_date":1299420596,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":64,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Evolution - exchange-connector, Rackspace global catalog server","body":"<p>The Global Catalog Server name can be found in your outlook Names<\/p>\n\n<p>Steps below<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Open a new email message in Outlook.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>then<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Click on the \"To:\" button to get the\n\"Select Names\" dialog<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>then<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Put \"Show Names from the\" to \"Global\nAddress List\".<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>finally<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Right-click on the \"Global Address\nList\" to get \"Properties\"<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>This opens a dialog with the name of the Global Address List server and the path. You just need the server name and plug this into Evolution.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can always change your email application to Thunderbird instead if it is more compatible with an Exchange server setup.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hope this helps. <\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":29315,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29315\/comments","question_id":29188,"owner":{"user_id":11935,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"user10669","reputation":1,"email_hash":"cc275f6292a3422ca65de4fc7dad29a3"},"creation_date":1299448119,"last_edit_date":1299448523,"last_activity_date":1299448523,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":64,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Evolution - exchange-connector, Rackspace global catalog server","body":"<p>Edit: This should have been directed at the above answer.<\/p>\n\n<p>I've put that in (its of the form 12345-various letters.exchange.rackspace.com), but that doesn't work - It tells me \"LDAP authentication failed (oxfffffff Can't contact LDAP server).<\/p>\n\n<p>I couldn't find any options to allow Thunderbird to sync with Exchange, it only seemed to offer IMAP options.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30915,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30915\/comments","question_id":29188,"owner":{"user_id":12303,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"pedrorolo","reputation":1,"email_hash":"daacb6d0a16d95a3858ccae59b44860d"},"creation_date":1300452214,"last_activity_date":1300452214,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":64,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Evolution - exchange-connector, Rackspace global catalog server","body":"<p>I have tried to do this with davmail. I am already able to send mail, receive mail, and sync the calendar. I just dunno how to configure Evolution to support davmail's LDAP configuration.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29188\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29188\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29188\/answers","question_id":29188,"owner":{"user_id":10669,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user10669","reputation":21,"email_hash":"a6ed24ea3045269df23a06d730cc89e2"},"creation_date":1299369410,"last_activity_date":1300452214,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":64,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Evolution - exchange-connector, Rackspace global catalog server","body":"<p>I'm (trying to) switch to Ubuntu from Windows XP on my work laptop. Unfortunately, one of the dealbreakers is that I need full Exchange contact\/calendar syncing.<\/p>\n\n<p>Our email is hosted by Rackspace (owa.mailseat.com). We login using the usernames of the format first.lastname@ourcompany.com.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm trying to set up Evolution to use this account, using exchange-connector-setup-2.32. The first step, entering the OWA URL, usename and password works, and progresses to step 2, where I need to enter a Global Catalog server. I have no idea what to enter here. Everything fails.<\/p>\n\n<p>My questions are\n- What is the \"Global Catalog server\" - can I enter\/run some dummy server here?\n- If its necessary, where can I get the information from this? I have a Windows XP machine synced up using Outlook 2007, so if I need to gather any information from that setup I can.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["server","upgrade","linux-distro"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":10510,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/10510\/comments","question_id":10480,"owner":{"user_id":1990,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"aatdark","reputation":1098,"email_hash":"b3527ba4ed509c67acb5fbd1ebf8bfa5"},"creation_date":1288488980,"last_edit_date":1300452109,"last_activity_date":1300452109,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":42,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"I have two System informations display","body":"<p>Somebody @ <a href=\"http:\/\/wwww.ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?p=10046052\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/wwww.ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?p=10046052<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>recommended to check <code>\/etc\/motd<\/code> (Message of the day)<\/p>\n\n<p><code>gksudo gedit \/etc\/motd<\/code> should do the trick<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":10510,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/10480\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/10480\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/10480\/answers","question_id":10480,"owner":{"user_id":1326,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"AntonioCS","reputation":154,"email_hash":"8495abb9d44de2866b83a6d164948e0c"},"creation_date":1288464173,"last_activity_date":1300452109,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":42,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"I have two System informations display","body":"<p>Hey! I have upgraded from 10.04 to 10.10 using the the \napt-get dist-upgrade command.<\/p>\n\n<p>Everything went ok (at least for now everything seems to be working) but now when I login via ssh I get two system informations display, the first from 10.10 abd the second from 10.04.1 LTS<\/p>\n\n<p>What did I do wrong?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","server","settings","console"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":9614,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/9614\/comments","question_id":9540,"owner":{"user_id":2978,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"richzilla","reputation":1296,"email_hash":"1e2a494a20e7debf9c885f2edfd9483e"},"creation_date":1288103940,"last_edit_date":1300451857,"last_activity_date":1300451857,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":433,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I change the computer name?","body":"<p>You need to edit the computer name in two files:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\/etc\/hostname \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\/etc\/hosts\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>These will both need administrative access, so run<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gksu gedit \/path\/to\/file\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Simply replace any instances of the existing computer name with your new one. When complete, restart your computer, and the name will have been changed.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":9549,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/9549\/comments","question_id":9540,"owner":{"user_id":325,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Riccardo Murri","reputation":3975,"email_hash":"bbfb73b621fa823c5f0b70053603464e"},"creation_date":1288082169,"last_activity_date":1288082169,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":433,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I change the computer name?","body":"<p>The <em>host name<\/em> uniquely identifies your computer on the local network (and possibly on the Internet as well) so it's not a good idea to change it unless you know what you are doing.<\/p>\n\n<p>But you can change the shell prompt not to display the <code>.belkin<\/code> (domain name part):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>export PS1='\\u@\\h \\w&gt; '\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>See the <a href=\"http:\/\/manpages.ubuntu.com\/1\/bash\" rel=\"nofollow\">bash man page<\/a> and specifically the <a href=\"http:\/\/manpages.ubuntu.com\/manpages\/maverick\/en\/man1\/bash.1.html#contenttoc26\" rel=\"nofollow\">section on prompting<\/a> for more information.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":9610,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/9610\/comments","question_id":9540,"owner":{"user_id":3798,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user3798","reputation":209,"email_hash":"a5f3d249cc5053cdc1eb4ede60fd2f45"},"creation_date":1288103553,"last_activity_date":1288103553,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":433,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I change the computer name?","body":"<p>Open a terminal and<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo sed -i '1s\/.*\/desired-name\/g' \/etc\/hostname\n\n# you need restart to effect with...\n\nsudo shutdown -r 0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":9614,"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/9540\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/9540\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/9540\/answers","question_id":9540,"owner":{"user_id":3921,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Wolfy","reputation":372,"email_hash":"55d3d3416881f997fa76e2e59da07284"},"creation_date":1288080059,"last_edit_date":1300451978,"last_activity_date":1300451978,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":433,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I change the computer name?","body":"<p>Hello,<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm noot sure if my title is corect... corect me if I'm wrong :)<\/p>\n\n<p>When I connect to my server (ubuntu server 10.10), I get this:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>name@server-name.belkin ~><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>How can I remove \".belkin\"?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["xorg","display","brightness"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":9249,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/9249\/comments","question_id":9248,"owner":{"user_id":3973,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"N 1.1","reputation":206,"email_hash":"3983438e2b3ae0258d247597301b6439"},"creation_date":1287945405,"last_activity_date":1287945405,"up_vote_count":7,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1114,"score":7,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is there a software utility to adjust screen gamma\/brightness\/contrast?","body":"<p><a href=\"http:\/\/jonls.dk\/redshift\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Redshift<\/a><br>\nI have been using this. Its very nice.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:jonls\/redshift-ppa<br>\n  sudo apt-get update &amp;&amp; sudo apt-get install redshift gtk-redshift<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>gtk-redshift is just the gui, not required.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.stereopsis.com\/flux\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">f.lux<\/a> is also an option.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":9291,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/9291\/comments","question_id":9248,"owner":{"user_id":3778,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Kaustubh P","reputation":1978,"email_hash":"1d92cc045a796c912ab2e255ad9b3b65"},"creation_date":1287974983,"last_activity_date":1287974983,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1114,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is there a software utility to adjust screen gamma\/brightness\/contrast?","body":"<p>Yea, I second <a href=\"http:\/\/www.stereopsis.com\/flux\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">f.lux<\/a>. There are 4 temperature options: Tungsten, Halogen, Fluoroscent, Sunlight that you can set depending upon the brightness you want. You just have to enter your latitude and longitude, and it does the rest.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":18722,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/18722\/comments","question_id":9248,"owner":{"user_id":7851,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Kramer2010","reputation":1,"email_hash":"d1964393c871f7a9f85d832ac17631bf"},"creation_date":1293197760,"last_edit_date":1300451848,"last_activity_date":1300451848,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1114,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is there a software utility to adjust screen gamma\/brightness\/contrast?","body":"<p>To those who have problem with brightness configuration after installing Ubuntu 10.10 and  are using Acer Aspire 4741, here's a solution for you:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gksu gedit \/etc\/default\/grub\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Change the line <code>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"\"<\/code> into <code>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"acpi_osi=Linux\"<\/code><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo update-grub\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Restart your linux<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":18760,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/18760\/comments","question_id":9248,"owner":{"user_id":7800,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jason","reputation":165,"email_hash":"9f1f34884b5fd78c373a70ee11a5228e"},"creation_date":1293221984,"last_activity_date":1293221984,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1114,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is there a software utility to adjust screen gamma\/brightness\/contrast?","body":"<p>You can always do Windows-M or Windows-N.  The first inverts colors of all windows showing, the second does it to the current window in focus.<\/p>\n\n<p>Really helps when reading PDFs with tired eyes<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":9249,"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/9248\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/9248\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/9248\/answers","question_id":9248,"owner":{"user_id":2390,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Ivan","reputation":2114,"email_hash":"f84eb4d8ec7ec9a694d18ca9e54db3f0"},"creation_date":1287945220,"last_activity_date":1300451848,"up_vote_count":6,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":1114,"score":6,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is there a software utility to adjust screen gamma\/brightness\/contrast?","body":"<p>I use to work at night and it is eye-hurting to watch at lightbulb-bright screens (I've got two - laptop's built-in panel and an external 18-inch CRT) in a dark environment. So I adjust my screens to be darker.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can I do this a software way instead of pressing monitors' buttons that many times every time?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","internet","modem-manager"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":8928,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/8928\/comments","question_id":6001,"owner":{"user_id":1736,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"mniess","reputation":638,"email_hash":"49da80dd0232882bee8b791976924f73"},"creation_date":1287773564,"last_edit_date":1300451836,"last_activity_date":1300451836,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":965,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to configure TATA Photon+ EC1261 HUAWEI","body":"<p>In fact, not much has to be done to use this dongle and you don't really need to install anything. You need to edit one file, though.<\/p>\n\n<p>Press <kbd>ALT<\/kbd>+<kbd>F2<\/kbd> and enter <code>gksu gedit \/etc\/udev\/rules.d\/15-huawei-e161.rules<\/code> to create the file we need. Now paste the content below into the file and save it.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>SUBSYSTEM=\"usb\"\nSYSFS{idProduct}=\"1446\"\nSYSFS{idVendor}=\"12d1\"\nRUN+=\"\/lib\/udev\/modem-modeswitch --vendor 0x12d1 --product 0x1446 --type option-zerocd\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now just plug in your dongle and configure your connection using NetworkManager.<\/p>\n\n<p>Explanation: The above file makes sure the command modem-modeswitch is run, whenever you plug in your dongle. The command itself just changes the dongle from cdrom-mode to modem-mode.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":8859,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/8859\/comments","question_id":6001,"owner":{"user_id":3550,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"hhlp","reputation":4080,"email_hash":"096126abf903bd5c988f01846ee42c64"},"creation_date":1287751931,"last_edit_date":1287756211,"last_activity_date":1287756211,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":965,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to configure TATA Photon+ EC1261 HUAWEI","body":"<p>1.- follow this guide :<\/p>\n\n<p>How to install Tata Photon+ on Ubuntu 10.04<\/p>\n\n<p>STEP #1:<\/p>\n\n<p>Plug-in your device and download two .deb files on your Ubuntu desktop.<\/p>\n\n<p>usb-modeswitch-data<\/p>\n\n<p>usb-modeswitch<\/p>\n\n<p>Download the above links or from the latest Debian repo listed below.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/packages.debian.org\/search?keywords=usb-modeswitch&amp;searchon=names&amp;suite=all&amp;section=all\" rel=\"nofollow\">link text<\/a> <em>use sid debian version in both package<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>STEP #2:<\/p>\n\n<p>Installing required packages<\/p>\n\n<p>i. RIGHT CLICK on the package usb-modeswitch-data, SELECT \"Open with GDebi Package Installer\".<\/p>\n\n<p>ii. If there is no error message then CLICK on \"Install Package\" button.<\/p>\n\n<p>iii. RIGHT CLICK on the package usb-modeswitch, SELECT \"Open with GDebi Package Installer\".<\/p>\n\n<p>vi. If there is an error regarding architecture\nthen DOWNLOAD different package and repeat above step again.<\/p>\n\n<p>v. If there is no error message then CLICK on \"Install Package\" button.<\/p>\n\n<p>vi. After this verify installation of these packages by following PART-I > Step1 with another debian version.<\/p>\n\n<p>REBOOT your system [recommended]<\/p>\n\n<p>STEP #3 [Important]<\/p>\n\n<p>Modifying usb-modeswitch file<\/p>\n\n<p>i. OPEN Terminal again (\"Applications\" > \"Accessories\" > \"Terminal\")<\/p>\n\n<p>ii. KEEP TATA Photon device connected, TYPE \"lsusb\" and you will get results like below.\nBus 003 Device 002: ID 12d1:140b Huawei Technologies Co., Ltd.<\/p>\n\n<p>iii. If your device shows no. different than 140b then use that in below steps.<\/p>\n\n<p>iv. GO TO \"\/etc\/usb_modeswitch.d\/12d1:1446\" and edit it.\n(GO TO parent most folder and then TYPE \"CD \/etc\/usb_modeswitch.d\/\",<\/p>\n\n<p>v. TYPE \"gedit 12d1:1446\", the file will get opened in text editor.)<\/p>\n\n<p>vi. ADD \"140b\" to the \"targetList=\" and SAVE the file. <\/p>\n\n<p>Configuring Tata Photon+ as \"Mobile Brodband\" from Network Manager.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step1 : GO TO \"System\" > \"Preferences\" > \"Network Connections\".<\/p>\n\n<p>Step2 : CLICK on \"Mobile Broadband\" tab.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step3 : CLICK on \"ADD\" button.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step4 : Observe the device name below \"Create a connection for this mobile broadband device\".\n\"HUAyWEI TECHNOLOGIES HUAWEI Mobile\" should already be selected in drop down.\nIf not SELECT it and CLICK on \"FORWARD\".\nNOTE:- If this device does not shows here that means\nyour Ubuntu is still not treating this device as USB MODEM.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step5 : SELECT country (e.g. India) from the list CLICK on \"FORWARD\".<\/p>\n\n<p>Step6 : SELECT PROVIDER (e.g. Tata Indicom (Photon+)) from the list CLICK on \"FORWARD\".<\/p>\n\n<p>Step7 : You will see \"Your Device\" and \"Your Provider\", CLICK \"Apply\" button.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step8 : FILL following information under \"Mobile Broadband\" tab.\nNumber: #777\nUsername: internet\nPassword: internet\nOptionally you can CHECK \"Connect Automatically\" option.\nCLICK on \"Apply\" button<\/p>\n\n<p>Step9 : TYPE first user password and CLICK on \"Authenticate\".\nYou will see \"Tata Indicom (Photon+)\" in Mobile Broadband connection list.<\/p>\n\n<p>PART-III :- Starting \"Mobile Broadband\" Connection<\/p>\n\n<p>Step1 : RIGHT CLICK on \"Network Manager\" icon on top-left corner of the screen.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step2 : CHECK \"Enable Mobile Broadband\" option.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step3 : Now CLICK on the same icon.<\/p>\n\n<p>Step4 : CLICK on \"Tata Indicom (photon+) connection1\"<\/p>\n\n<p>And THATS IT !!!!!!<\/p>\n\n<p>2.- <\/p>\n\n<p>another option is upgrade from 10.04 to 10.10 because THE DRIVER FOR TATA PHOTON+ IS PRE INSTALLED, so no need to install .deb file. Plug in your photon device and select the appropriate options from the Ubuntu network manager.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":6096,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/6096\/comments","question_id":6001,"owner":{"user_id":1724,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Mathieu Trudel-Lapierre","reputation":506,"email_hash":"8bd40006c99ffff077d7ececae1e8ab4"},"creation_date":1286826617,"last_edit_date":1287079174,"last_activity_date":1287079174,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":965,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to configure TATA Photon+ EC1261 HUAWEI","body":"<p>How did you test the speed if you were still not able to get online?<\/p>\n\n<p>The steps in that link look correct, usb-modeswitch in Lucid is a little outdated and installing the version 1.1.4-1 from Debian usually fixes the problem. So, how many steps did you successfully go through? If all, you would probably want <a href=\"https:\/\/help.ubuntu.com\/community\/ReportingBugs\" rel=\"nofollow\">to open a bug<\/a> on Launchpad and attach logs from NetworkManager and ModemManager.<\/p>\n\n<p>As for the logs, there's a wiki page I updated on how to get them: <a href=\"http:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/DebuggingNetworkManager\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/DebuggingNetworkManager<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The trick is roughly to (in a terminal):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo stop network-manager\nsudo killall modem-manager\nsudo \/usr\/sbin\/modem-manager --debug &gt; ~\/mm.log 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;\nsudo \/usr\/sbin\/NetworkManager --no-daemon &gt; ~\/nm.log 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then reproduce the issue and attach both nm.log and mm.log from your home directory to the bug.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":8853,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/8853\/comments","question_id":6001,"owner":{"user_id":3497,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Open Help","reputation":442,"email_hash":"918d7f26b828c0b11001b2d9b10f1379"},"creation_date":1287750503,"last_edit_date":1300451830,"last_activity_date":1300451830,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":965,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to configure TATA Photon+ EC1261 HUAWEI","body":"<p>what it says on the link you tried had worked perfectly with me. can you just post the edited file here<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gksu gedit \/etc\/usb_modeswitch.d\/12d1:1446\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":8859,"favorite_count":2,"bounty_amount":50,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/6001\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/6001\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/6001\/answers","question_id":6001,"owner":{"user_id":3215,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user3215","reputation":289,"email_hash":"709a11533e36376cf5c94d84a4724911"},"creation_date":1286806755,"last_edit_date":1299323668,"last_activity_date":1300451836,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":965,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to configure TATA Photon+ EC1261 HUAWEI","body":"<p>I'm running ubuntu 10.04. I have a newly purchased TATA Photon+ Internet connection which supports Windows and Mac. On the Internet I found a article saying that it could be configured on Linux. I followed the steps to install it on Ubuntu from this <a href=\"http:\/\/digitizor.com\/2010\/06\/28\/how-to-use-tata-photon-plus-in-ubuntu-10-04-lucid-lynx\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">link<\/a>. I am still not able to get online, and need some help.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, it is very slow, but I was told that I would see speeds up to 3.1MB.<\/p>\n\n<p>I dont have wvdial installed and cannot install it from apt as I'm not connected to internet<\/p>\n\n<p>Booting from windows I dowloaded \"wvdial\" .deb package and tried to install on ubuntu but it's ended with dependency problem. Automatically, don't know how, I got connected to internet only for once. Immediately I installed wvdial package after this I followed the tutorials(I could not browse and upload the files here) . From then it's showing that the device is connected in the network connections but no internet connection. Once I disable the device, it won't show as connected again and I'll have to restart my system. Sometimes the device itself not detected(wondering if there is any command to re-read the all devices).<\/p>\n\n<p>output of <strong>wvdialconf \/etc\/wvdial.cof<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>#wvdialconf \/etc\/wvdial.conf\n\nEditing `\/etc\/wvdial.conf'.\n\nScanning your serial ports for a modem.\n\nttyS0&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- failed with 2400 baud, next try: 9600 baud\nttyS0&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- failed with 9600 baud, next try: 115200 baud\nttyS0&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- and failed too at 115200, giving up.\nModem Port Scan&lt;*1&gt;: S1   S2   S3   \nWvModem&lt;*1&gt;: Cannot get information for serial port.\nttyUSB0&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- failed with 2400 baud, next try: 9600 baud\nttyUSB0&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- failed with 9600 baud, next try: 9600 baud\nttyUSB0&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- and failed too at 115200, giving up.\nWvModem&lt;*1&gt;: Cannot get information for serial port.\nttyUSB1&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- failed with 2400 baud, next try: 9600 baud\nttyUSB1&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- failed with 9600 baud, next try: 9600 baud\nttyUSB1&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- and failed too at 115200, giving up.\nWvModem&lt;*1&gt;: Cannot get information for serial port.\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 Z -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 &amp;D2 -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 &amp;D2 +FCLASS=0 -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: Modem Identifier: ATI -- Manufacturer: +GMI: HUAWEI TECHNOLOGIES CO., LTD\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: Speed 9600: AT -- OK\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: Max speed is 9600; that should be safe.\nttyUSB2&lt;*1&gt;: ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 &amp;D2 +FCLASS=0 -- OK\n\nFound a modem on \/dev\/ttyUSB2.\nModem configuration written to \/etc\/wvdial.conf.\nttyUSB2&lt;Info&gt;: Speed 9600; init \"ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 &amp;D2 +FCLASS=0\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>output of <strong>wvdial<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>#wvdial\n--&gt; WvDial: Internet dialer version 1.60\n--&gt; Cannot get information for serial port.\n--&gt; Initializing modem.\n--&gt; Sending: ATZ\nATZ\nOK\n--&gt; Sending: ATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 &amp;D2 +FCLASS=0\nATQ0 V1 E1 S0=0 &amp;C1 &amp;D2 +FCLASS=0\nOK\n--&gt; Sending: AT+CRM=1\nAT+CRM=1\nOK\n--&gt; Modem initialized.\n--&gt; Sending: ATDT#777\n--&gt; Waiting for carrier.\nATDT#777\nCONNECT\n--&gt; Carrier detected.  Starting PPP immediately.\n--&gt; Starting pppd at Sat Oct 16 15:30:47 2010\n--&gt; Pid of pppd: 5681\n--&gt; Using interface ppp0\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; local  IP address 14.96.147.104\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; remote IP address 172.29.161.223\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; primary   DNS address 121.40.152.90\n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n--&gt; secondary DNS address 121.40.152.100  \n--&gt; pppd: (u;[08]@s;[08]`{;[08]\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Output of log message <strong>\/var\/log\/messages<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Oct 16 15:29:44 avyakta-desktop pppd[5119]: secondary DNS address 121.242.190.180\nOct 16 15:29:58 desktop pppd[5119]: Terminating on signal 15\nOct 16 15:29:58 desktop pppd[5119]: Connect time 0.3 minutes.\nOct 16 15:29:58 desktop pppd[5119]: Sent 0 bytes, received 177 bytes.\nOct 16 15:29:58 desktop pppd[5119]: Connection terminated.\nOct 16 15:30:47 desktop pppd[5681]: pppd 2.4.5 started by root, uid 0\nOct 16 15:30:47 desktop pppd[5681]: Using interface ppp0\nOct 16 15:30:47 desktop pppd[5681]: Connect: ppp0 &lt;--&gt; \/dev\/ttyUSB2\nOct 16 15:30:47 desktop pppd[5681]: CHAP authentication succeeded\nOct 16 15:30:47 desktop pppd[5681]: CHAP authentication succeeded\nOct 16 15:30:48 desktop pppd[5681]: local  IP address 14.96.147.104\nOct 16 15:30:48 desktop pppd[5681]: remote IP address 172.29.161.223\nOct 16 15:30:48 desktop pppd[5681]: primary   DNS address 121.40.152.90\nOct 16 15:30:48 desktop pppd[5681]: secondary DNS address 121.40.152.100\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT 1<\/strong> :<\/p>\n\n<p>I tried the following<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo stop network-manager\nsudo killall modem-manager\n\nsudo \/usr\/sbin\/modem-manager --debug &gt; ~\/mm.log 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;\n\nsudo \/usr\/sbin\/NetworkManager --no-daemon &gt; ~\/nm.log 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Output of <strong>mm.log<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>#vim ~\/mm.log:\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Option High-Speed\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Option\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Huawei\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Longcheer\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin AnyData\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin ZTE\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Ericsson MBM\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Sierra\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Generic\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Gobi\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Novatel\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin Nokia\n\n** Message: Loaded plugin MotoC\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Output of <strong>nm.log<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>#vim ~\/nm.log:\n\nNetworkManager: &lt;info&gt;  starting...\n\nNetworkManager: &lt;info&gt;  modem-manager is now available\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: init!\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: update_system_hostname\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPluginIfupdown: guessed connection type (eth0) = 802-3-ethernet\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: update_connection_setting_from_if_block:     \n\nname:eth0, type:802-3-ethernet, id:Ifupdown (eth0), uuid: 681b428f-beaf-8932-dce4-678ed5bae28e\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: addresses count: 1\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: No dns-nameserver configured in \/etc\/network\/interfaces\n\nNetworkManager: nm-ifupdown-connection.c.119 - invalid connection read from \/etc\/network\/interfaces: (1) addresses\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPluginIfupdown: management mode: unmanaged\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: devices added (path: \/sys\/devices\/pci0000:00\/0000:00:14.4\/0000:02:02.0\/net\/eth1, iface: eth1)\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: device added (path: \/sys\/devices\/pci0000:00\/0000:00:14.4\/0000:02:02.0\/net\/eth1, iface: eth1): no ifupdown configuration found.\n\nNetworkManager:    SCPlugin-Ifupdown: devices added (path: \/sys\/devices\/virtual\/net\/lo, iface: lo)\n\n@\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["gnome","suspend-resume","screensaver","lock-screen"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":17234,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/17234\/comments","question_id":17157,"owner":{"user_id":5691,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"karthick87","reputation":8739,"email_hash":"b41802fe7f333c0b2b2b68be7da4f757"},"creation_date":1292263756,"last_edit_date":1300451823,"last_activity_date":1300451823,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":202,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I stop the screen from being locked on suspend?","body":"<ul>\n<li><p>Edit your <strong>acpi-support<\/strong> file by pressing <kbd>Alt<\/kbd> + <kbd>F2<\/kbd> and pasting<\/p>\n\n<p><code>gksu gedit \/etc\/default\/acpi-support<\/code><\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Find the line that says <strong>LOCK_SCREEN=true<\/strong> and comment it out to disable screen locking on resume.<br>\n<img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/BZxBo.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n"},{"answer_id":21580,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/21580\/comments","question_id":17157,"owner":{"user_id":8739,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jeffrey Finkelstein","reputation":21,"email_hash":"4ddea00d396b2f0b635bd1897a02edef"},"creation_date":1295038195,"last_activity_date":1295038195,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":202,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I stop the screen from being locked on suspend?","body":"<p>Run <code>gconf-editor<\/code>, then under <code>\/apps\/gnome-power-manager\/lock<\/code> uncheck the <code>suspend<\/code> checkbox.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":17158,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/17158\/comments","question_id":17157,"owner":{"user_id":7035,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"CYREX","reputation":3644,"email_hash":"678ae90bb6622525bcad23783725b474"},"creation_date":1292202700,"last_edit_date":1292245972,"last_activity_date":1292245972,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":202,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I stop the screen from being locked on suspend?","body":"<p>Did you verify that the option in the screen-saver about LOCKING the PC is off. Go to System > Preferences > Screensaver<\/p>\n\n<p>Verify that <strong>Lock Screen when Screensaver is active<\/strong> is turned off. Also verify that <strong>Activate Screensaver when computer is idle<\/strong> is off too.<\/p>\n\n<p>Looking around i found that you can also edit several Power Management options via the gconf-editor.<\/p>\n\n<p>Press ALT+F2 and type gconf-editor<\/p>\n\n<p>Go to:  Apps > Gnome-Power-Manager > Lock<\/p>\n\n<p>Check the option <strong>use screensaver settings<\/strong> This way it checks for the option you put in the screensaver window.<\/p>\n\n<p>There might be other options there that will help you like <strong>gnome_keyring_hibernate<\/strong> and <strong>gnome_keyring_suspend<\/strong> (If they use the keyring they might be the ones asking for the password when locked)<\/p>\n\n<p>This are EXTREME cases please let me know if they work so i can copy them here and make a reference:<\/p>\n\n<p>First do this: <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showpost.php?p=9509427&amp;postcount=10\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showpost.php?p=9509427&amp;postcount=10<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Then do this: <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showpost.php?p=9756347&amp;postcount=11\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showpost.php?p=9756347&amp;postcount=11<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":17159,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/17159\/comments","question_id":17157,"owner":{"user_id":1992,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Roland Taylor","reputation":6690,"email_hash":"d629b6ac45d58dbd918c0246b364748d"},"creation_date":1292203014,"last_edit_date":1299369129,"last_activity_date":1299369129,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":202,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I stop the screen from being locked on suspend?","body":"<p>I have since found out that it seems to be a bug\/feature? of the system indicator. If I use the normal shutdown dialog it works (puzzling). I guess I'll just have to report a bug :(.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks to everyone for trying to help, turns out there is nothing I can do about it until the bug? is fixed.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":17159,"favorite_count":2,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/17157\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/17157\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/17157\/answers","question_id":17157,"owner":{"user_id":1992,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Roland Taylor","reputation":6690,"email_hash":"d629b6ac45d58dbd918c0246b364748d"},"creation_date":1292202405,"last_activity_date":1300451823,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":202,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I stop the screen from being locked on suspend?","body":"<p>On GNOME the screen locks when I suspend, and I find that a bit annoying (no one else in the house uses ubuntu anyway haha). What can I do to stop this?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["script","shutdown"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":1179,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1179\/comments","question_id":1175,"owner":{"user_id":612,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"popey","reputation":1464,"email_hash":"a153cc0ebef591904c04d8bf487661de"},"creation_date":1281022505,"last_activity_date":1281022505,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":586,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Execute script before shutting down","body":"<p>You could add your command to the file <code>\/etc\/gdm\/PostSession\/Default<\/code> before the <code>exit 0<\/code> line.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":1180,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1180\/comments","question_id":1175,"owner":{"user_id":333,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"dustyprogrammer","reputation":2738,"email_hash":"fab591eb34c76cbd0716024ce22d4906"},"creation_date":1281022607,"last_activity_date":1281022607,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":586,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Execute script before shutting down","body":"<p>Sounds like a question for superuser.com to me. Anyway, after some <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=185261\" rel=\"nofollow\">Googling I found How to run a script on logout?<\/a> which says to add the script to $HOME\/.bash_logout.<\/p>\n\n<p>If that doesn't work, add<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$HOME\/.bash_logout\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>to \/etc\/gdm\/PostSession\/Default so it executes the logout script properly.<\/p>\n\n<p>Seeing as before shutdown the user is logged off anyway, this should cover both bases.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":1178,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1178\/comments","question_id":1175,"owner":{"user_id":334,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Tommy Brunn","reputation":1033,"email_hash":"6e0af51287dd1f197f47ca5616875e93"},"creation_date":1281022480,"last_activity_date":1281022480,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":586,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Execute script before shutting down","body":"<p>If you do <code>.\/app-to-run &amp;&amp; sudo shutdown -h now<\/code> the computer should shut down once app-to-run is done.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":1181,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1181\/comments","question_id":1175,"owner":{"user_id":667,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"dv3500ea","reputation":10210,"email_hash":"7f3d5b197677567789c00d95032e28a3"},"creation_date":1281022674,"last_edit_date":1300451781,"last_activity_date":1300451781,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":586,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Execute script before shutting down","body":"<p>You can do this by creating a script in \/etc\/rc0.d (for shutdown) and \/etc\/rc6.d (for reboot).\nTo do this, run:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gksu gedit \/etc\/rc0.d\/K01mycustomscript\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Edit your shutdown script in the text editor then run:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo chmod +x \/etc\/rc0.d\/K01mycustomscript\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And if you want it to run on reboot also then run this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo cp \/etc\/rc0.d\/K01mycustomscript \/etc\/rc6.d\/K01mycustomscript\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=436346\" rel=\"nofollow\">this forum thread<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":2,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/1175\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/1175\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/1175\/answers","question_id":1175,"owner":{"user_id":48,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"juanefren","reputation":20,"email_hash":"9483a851217a5775b8fbc20b7e985dba"},"creation_date":1281021957,"last_activity_date":1300451781,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":586,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Execute script before shutting down","body":"<p>When I shut down my computer I want to show some pending tasks that I have to do before leaving the office...  I did a local application to manage those tasks, basically I just want to run a command, and shut down after I kill the app executed.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["arm"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30913\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30913\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30913\/answers","question_id":30913,"owner":{"user_id":814,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Oxwivi","reputation":325,"email_hash":"1db5a33e98229a20cde25431bd690bfd"},"creation_date":1300451627,"last_activity_date":1300451627,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":5,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Does any version of Ubuntu ARM support ARM926EJ-S rev 5 (v5l)","body":"<p>The Android System info application on my tablet says that my processor is <strong>ARM926EJ-S rev 5 (v5l)<\/strong>. Which version of Ubuntu ARM will work on it?<\/p>\n\n<p>Will I have any issues finding packages for the ARM architecture?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","sudo"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":23515,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/23515\/comments","question_id":23512,"owner":{"user_id":742,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jo\u00e3o Pinto","reputation":5838,"email_hash":"29020331a486bb3f9e88031a0cfea800"},"creation_date":1296135762,"last_activity_date":1296135762,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":112,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"sudo: setuid must be root","body":"<p>Based on your error, you didn't simply changed the permissions of \/usr to 777, you did it recursively which is a more serious and problematic change.<\/p>\n\n<p>Unless you have backups of your system directories, your best option is just to reinstall.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/23512\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/23512\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/23512\/answers","question_id":23512,"creation_date":1296108891,"last_edit_date":1296132986,"last_activity_date":1300451618,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":112,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"sudo: setuid must be root","body":"<p>I changed the ownership of my <code>\/usr<\/code> directory to <code>777<\/code> by mistake and now my system give this error whenever I try to use sudo:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo: setuid must be root\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["partitioning","dual-boot"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30071\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30071\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30071\/answers","question_id":30071,"owner":{"user_id":11979,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Steven","reputation":101,"email_hash":"8f14a34c56dde8c48ab3143a24482fc2"},"creation_date":1299949866,"last_edit_date":1300451591,"last_activity_date":1300451591,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"\"the partition is misaligned\" error in Disk Utility - should I repartition?","body":"<p>I have a Dell XPS M1330 laptop that has Vista installed and I just installed Ubuntu 10.4 LTS so I can dual boot.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Everything seems to be working well, but when I opened the Disk Utility to have a look, almost all the partitions on the hard disk are showing the warning <code>WARNING: The partition is misaligned by xxx bytes<\/code> with xxx being anything from 512 to 2048 to 3072 depending on which partition we are examining.  <\/p>\n\n<p>The warning is suggesting repartitioning, but I am not sure if it would be helpful.  So here are my questions: is repartitioning really necessary, what tool should I use to do this, and will repartitioning the Vista partition damage it? <\/p>\n"},{"tags":["fun","always-friday-in-iceland"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":30886,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30886\/comments","question_id":30878,"owner":{"user_id":3922,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"bdr529","reputation":275,"email_hash":"6264ae470937f3decede1828a4528f31"},"creation_date":1300434552,"last_edit_date":1300451541,"last_activity_date":1300451541,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":4,"community_owned":true,"title":"What will you change in ubuntu if you owned canonical?","body":"<p>First, i would clearly communicate my aims with ubuntu, so everybody knows where it's going.<\/p>\n\n<p>Second, i would concentrate on only one desktop, in this case unity. Let others take care about the other ones.<\/p>\n\n<p>Third, i would start with unity, when it's ready, even if i had to skip a release.<\/p>\n\n<p>Fourth, i would develop at least 5 well designed themes for unity, so everyone can easy turn unity to his favourite style. Then develop an easy graphical tool to build up new unity-themes and start a platform like gnome-look.org just for unity themes and an one-click installation for new themes. <\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30881,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30881\/comments","question_id":30878,"owner":{"user_id":5434,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Evan","reputation":41,"email_hash":"884db8fa9847249e5b21c2a105741b8f"},"creation_date":1300431269,"last_activity_date":1300431269,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":2,"community_owned":true,"title":"What will you change in ubuntu if you owned canonical?","body":"<p>Change unity slightly. Get rid of the Application, Places and Commands button and move it all into the Ubuntu button. Possibly right next to the \"Search\" (works like tabs). I would also move the expo button to the bottom of the launcher so it will still be easily visible if there are a lot of applications on the launcher. I'll also have a mounted volumes place.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30885,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30885\/comments","question_id":30878,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1300433944,"last_activity_date":1300433944,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":1,"community_owned":true,"title":"What will you change in ubuntu if you owned canonical?","body":"<p>I would release the proprietary landscape's code with a free license and remove the canonical's contributor's agreement.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30884,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30884\/comments","question_id":30878,"owner":{"user_id":12271,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jrtayloriv","reputation":131,"email_hash":"9a279500b3c24f2a47e5b5684b3e154c"},"creation_date":1300432746,"last_activity_date":1300432746,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":203,"score":0,"community_owned":true,"title":"What will you change in ubuntu if you owned canonical?","body":"<p>I would convert Canonical into a non-profit corporation, and base my development model on that of Debian.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"closed_date":1300450354,"closed_reason":"off topic","question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30878\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30878\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30878\/answers","question_id":30878,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1300430571,"last_edit_date":1300445993,"last_activity_date":1300451541,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":3,"view_count":203,"score":-1,"community_owned":true,"title":"What will you change in ubuntu if you owned canonical?","body":"<p>What changes will you bring in ubuntu (and related projects) if you became owned canonical ?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["evolution","gmail"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":28428,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28428\/comments","question_id":28423,"owner":{"user_id":2313,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Detnuomnu","reputation":189,"email_hash":"d41433920f07c562a7aabec8924ed03c"},"creation_date":1298900630,"last_edit_date":1300450544,"last_activity_date":1300450544,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":87,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Use Evolution to back up Gmail \"Sent folder\"","body":"<p>i'm assuming your using IMAP<\/p>\n\n<p>open edit --> preferences<br>\nselect your account and press edit<br>\ngoto defaults tab<br>\nchange sent messages folder to: [Gmail]\/sent mail<\/p>\n\n<p>this will automatically add sent mail to your gmail account from now on.\njust drag old sent mails onto this folder<\/p>\n\n<p>Luri asked which would be best, POP or IMAP...<\/p>\n\n<p>best is a matter of preference here. IMAP will treat all your gmail labels as seperate folders. Staying with pop, with all your sent and received mail in your inbox you could just create a filter locally. to create a filter goto: edit --> message filters. check its set to incoming. click add. for your sent mail: Sender, is, you@gmail.com, move to folder, destination folder. ok. Now goto your inbox press CTRL+A then CTRL+Y, this will apply the filter. play around a bit with filters for the rest of your email. <\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":28425,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28425\/comments","question_id":28423,"owner":{"user_id":6450,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Allan","reputation":2260,"email_hash":"ee2c87a3ad81c5394d119a6a2bf026a1"},"creation_date":1298898065,"last_activity_date":1298898065,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":87,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Use Evolution to back up Gmail \"Sent folder\"","body":"<p>your sent emails if they are pop should be here <code>\/home\/luri\/.evolution\/mail\/local\/sent<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/G96rG.png\" alt=\"picture of sent mbox file\"><\/p>\n\n<p>the one with no extension is the mbox file<\/p>\n\n<p>hope this helps<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30819,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30819\/comments","question_id":28423,"owner":{"user_id":12560,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user12560","reputation":1,"email_hash":"775038dcb916115395809936f48d64a0"},"creation_date":1300390248,"last_activity_date":1300390248,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":87,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Use Evolution to back up Gmail \"Sent folder\"","body":"<p>My requirements are:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>I want to download and keep a backup on my PC and at the same time syncing Gmail (leaving the mail on the server too)<\/li>\n<li>I want to reflect the changes (read\/unread\/reply etc except delete maybe) at one to another.<\/li>\n<li>I want Gmail <strong>labels<\/strong><\/li>\n<li>I want to be able to export import my email (with attachments) to any other Email client in future<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p><strong>Will Evolution be able to do this? On IMAP? Is selecting \"Automatically synchronize remote mail locally\"<\/strong> does the trick?<\/p>\n\n<p>@Allan: Which theme are you using? Looks nice, I would like to try if doesn't involve much hassle :-)<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":28428,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/28423\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/28423\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/28423\/answers","question_id":28423,"owner":{"user_id":8851,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"luri","reputation":1202,"email_hash":"fae09ce7fae86755c3283a0b1e3c6a71"},"creation_date":1298897085,"last_edit_date":1298941378,"last_activity_date":1300450544,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":87,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Use Evolution to back up Gmail \"Sent folder\"","body":"<p>I want to retrieve (initially via POP) my Gmail account mails, but the idea is just to keep a backup of those mails. But Gmail \"Sent\" mail is retrieved and put altogether with recieved mail into my Evolution inbox.\nHow can I get mails in my Gmail \"Sent\" folder from Evolution?<\/p>\n\n<p>(if I could get my Gmail labels, too, that'll be great, but it's not a primary goal)<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["server","mysql"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30872,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30872\/comments","question_id":30851,"owner":{"user_id":12205,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"mount.cifs","reputation":204,"email_hash":"7e5f72a378314f0a53b0730708891c67"},"creation_date":1300428172,"last_edit_date":1300449245,"last_activity_date":1300449245,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"problem installing mysql on ubuntu server 10.10 machine","body":"<p>Does the file <code>mysqld.sock<\/code> exist? If not, try the following:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo mkdir \/var\/run\/mysqld\nsudo touch \/var\/run\/mysqld\/mysqld.sock\nsudo chown -R mysql \/var\/run\/mysqld\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"answer_id":30889,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30889\/comments","question_id":30851,"owner":{"user_id":6969,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Lekensteyn","reputation":3644,"email_hash":"e6875b9fee07521eed2e2c7e7214e531"},"creation_date":1300438518,"last_activity_date":1300438518,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"problem installing mysql on ubuntu server 10.10 machine","body":"<p>You've corrupted your packages I see. You said you cancelled the installation of MySQL server, which is the package <code>mysql-server-5.1<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Try clearing your MySQL configuration and reinstalling it:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo rm -rf \/etc\/mysql \/var\/lib\/mysql\nsudo apt-get install mysql-server-5.1\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note that the first command clears previous settings and passwords of the MySQL database including the MySQL database itself. If you've just installed the server (as I can make up from your question), this is not an issue.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30851\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30851\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30851\/answers","question_id":30851,"owner":{"user_id":12574,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"badperson","reputation":1,"email_hash":"0e078ee5805b1ac13352393e82190e84"},"creation_date":1300410957,"last_edit_date":1300438303,"last_activity_date":1300449245,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"problem installing mysql on ubuntu server 10.10 machine","body":"<p>I tried installing mysql server a couple of times and I'm having problems. First of all, when I install it gives me a message that it's setting up and it just hangs. I can't ctl + c out of it, so I reboot the server and try to log into the db with <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo mysql -u root -p\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I enter my password and then get<\/p>\n\n<p>ERROR 2002 (HY000): Can't connect to local MySQL server through socket '\/var\/run\/mysqld\/mysqld.sock' (2)<\/p>\n\n<p>I restart the server: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ sudo \/etc\/init.d\/mysql start\nRather than invoking init scripts through \/etc\/init.d, use the service(8)\nutility, e.g. service mysql start\n\nSince the script you are attempting to invoke has been converted to an\nUpstart job, you may also use the start(8) utility, e.g. start mysql\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I try this: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ aptitude search mysql | grep ^i\ni A libdbd-mysql-perl               - Perl5 database interface to the MySQL data\ni   libmysql-java                   - Java database (JDBC) driver for MySQL     \ni A libmysqlclient16                - MySQL database client library             \ni   mysql-client-5.1                - MySQL database client binaries            \ni A mysql-client-core-5.1           - MySQL database core client binaries       \ni   mysql-common                    - MySQL database common files, e.g. \/etc\/mys\ni   mysql-embedded                  - MySQL - embedded library                  \ni   mysql-server-core-5.1           - MySQL database server binaries \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>When I navigate to the folder to see if the *.sock file exists:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>'\/var\/run\/mysqld\/mysqld.sock'\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>it does not. I also try this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ service mysql status\nstatus: Unable to connect to system bus: Failed to connect to socket \/var\/run\/dbus\/system_bus_socket: No such file or directory\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Any ideas? On my other machines installing mysql has been a snap, not sure what the problem is here.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["xorg","nvidia","vaio"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30906\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30906\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30906\/answers","question_id":30906,"owner":{"user_id":12594,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"ahmad598","reputation":1,"email_hash":"721cad1fd3e94c28527547dda9c05f93"},"creation_date":1300448895,"last_activity_date":1300448895,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":4,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Ubuntu on Vaio VPCS136FG - just black screen","body":"<p>Hi all I've recently bought a Vaio S series laptop, in case S136. the problem is that when i try to boot from live disc to install or test, just a black screen appears. the problem, as addressed in many threads, is that xorg can't find the EDID of monitor, thus fails. I've tried several solutions described in several forums, but still no success; except that before trying these solutions, the monitor was absolutely off, but now it has the backlight but it is still black. this is my situation:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>my vaio is VPC S136 FG with a GeForce 310M.<\/li>\n<li>my xorg log file doesnt say any error about the edid file. you can find it in the following.<\/li>\n<li>i can boot up ubuntu in failsafe mode with\n1280*... resolution, but it doesnt\nuse nvidia driver. <\/li>\n<li>I've installed Nvidia driver, version 260.19.06-0ubuntu1.<\/li>\n<li>I've recently installed xorg-edgers from the ppa,\nbut it just adds a thin line of\nlight, up in the monitor.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>this is my xorg.conf:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code># nvidia-xconfig: X c