date":1300448162,"last_activity_date":1300448162,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":48,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to go back to maverick meerkat from natty Alpha 3","body":"<p>There is no way to downgrade; you'd be installing 10.10 in order to go back.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30890\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30890\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30890\/answers","question_id":30890,"owner":{"user_id":12588,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Alex clay","reputation":6,"email_hash":"df4aecc960edf9c5e104e8d2617ff769"},"creation_date":1300439443,"last_edit_date":1300445199,"last_activity_date":1300448162,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":48,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to go back to maverick meerkat from natty Alpha 3","body":"<p>Hi guys, i'm wondering if there is anyway to directly downgrade back to meerkat as I have been experiencing bugs and want to go back to something more stable on my main machine. <\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","network-manager","networking"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":8134,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/8134\/comments","question_id":8038,"owner":{"user_id":3301,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"nathwill","reputation":612,"email_hash":"ef9dc2280ebf56882db34449186f4453"},"creation_date":1287425463,"last_activity_date":1287425463,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":561,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Networking is disabled after installing Maverick","body":"<p>check <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/2901\/unmanaged-network-icon-network-manangement-disabled\/3828#3828\">http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/2901\/unmanaged-network-icon-network-manangement-disabled\/3828#3828<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/8038\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/8038\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/8038\/answers","question_id":8038,"owner":{"user_id":4277,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Zifre","reputation":101,"email_hash":"688da15c29b1fc47987de667a817e82c"},"creation_date":1287363204,"last_activity_date":1300448018,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":561,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Networking is disabled after installing Maverick","body":"<p>I recently installed Ubuntu 10.10 (Maverick Meerkat). Everything was working fine. Then I just started up the computer again, and the networking doesn't work.<\/p>\n\n<p>The network manager applet says \"Networking disabled\". The button is disabled, so I can't enable it.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/2901\/unmanaged-network-icon-network-manangement-disabled\">This question<\/a> seems to be basically the same issue I have. <code>managed<\/code> in was set to <code>false<\/code>, but changing it to <code>true<\/code> does not fix the problem.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any other way to fix this problem?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","keyboard"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30903,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30903\/comments","question_id":30888,"owner":{"user_id":4998,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"dimitris mistriotis","reputation":151,"email_hash":"ba8ee82aef683dcfa130780d33b9f514"},"creation_date":1300447060,"last_activity_date":1300447060,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":15,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why do control keys (ctrl, shift, alt) not work sometimes?","body":"<p>I do not know if it is a sufficient answer, but it happens to me many times when I accidentally click at the desktop. They then work, but not on the last active window.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30888\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30888\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30888\/answers","question_id":30888,"owner":{"user_id":583,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"EricSchaefer","reputation":112,"email_hash":"9dc432b57f4370eaf4b91baa1e6b8147"},"creation_date":1300438308,"last_edit_date":1300439146,"last_activity_date":1300447060,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":15,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why do control keys (ctrl, shift, alt) not work sometimes?","body":"<p>Sometimes (about once a week) the control keys (ctrl, shift, alt) so not work anymore. They do work when I boot up, but after a while they stop working. Logging out and in again repairs it. What can cause something like that?<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit:<\/strong><br>\nIt just happened again. Incidentally it happened right after vmware-player crashed just as the last time. Coincidence?<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit:<\/strong><br>\nIt is a laptop keyboard (HP EliteBook 8730w) with german layout.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["gnome","themes","gui"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30902\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30902\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30902\/answers","question_id":30902,"owner":{"user_id":12590,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"gabor","reputation":111,"email_hash":"049df0a98cc60a68c063d29760e35698"},"creation_date":1300446202,"last_activity_date":1300446202,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":11,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"how to adjust \"contrast\" of a gtk2 theme?","body":"<p>I'd like to reduce the contrast of the GTK widgets, that is, make the borders less articulate. E.g. in the screenshot below, the separator above and below the toolbar is very strong. I'd like smoother borders.<\/p>\n\n<p>How is this possible?<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/I2xUP.png\" alt=\"current situation\"><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["gnome-panel"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30896\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30896\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30896\/answers","question_id":30896,"owner":{"user_id":5845,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"tinhed","reputation":1063,"email_hash":"0f8f1009c15867d73e0111fc5da85b4e"},"creation_date":1300441952,"last_edit_date":1300445812,"last_activity_date":1300445812,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":19,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Gnome-panels take a long time to load on startup.","body":"<p>I am using the 64 bit of ubuntu maverick desktop. The problem is that as soon as I login, the wallpaper and the desktop icons appear almost instantly, however the panel-takes an eternity to load, sometimes as long as 30 secs. I have a fairly modern system, so I am sure this is software related. Any fixes? Thanks in advance.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["usb-drive","ntfs","gparted"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":30246,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30246\/comments","question_id":30220,"owner":{"user_id":4982,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Mark Rooney","reputation":961,"email_hash":"8e833236fa16f0749640633b1583cc5f"},"creation_date":1300061450,"last_edit_date":1300442994,"last_activity_date":1300442994,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":73,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I resize an external USB NTFS partition?","body":"<p>You will not be able to resize the drive while it is mounted ie: in use - boot into Gparted Live CD, attach the drive (make sure it is not mounted!!) and then you should be able to resize the drive as you want.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is some useful documentation on using Gparted: <a href=\"http:\/\/www.dedoimedo.com\/computers\/gparted.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/www.dedoimedo.com\/computers\/gparted.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/9G8WG.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30260,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30260\/comments","question_id":30220,"owner":{"user_id":10616,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"EvilPhoenix","reputation":563,"email_hash":"6b92567199ee8a3e4a61c40a4406aff4"},"creation_date":1300066093,"last_activity_date":1300066093,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":73,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I resize an external USB NTFS partition?","body":"<p>Using <code>gparted<\/code>, you should start by right-clicking and choosing \"Unmount\".  This will allow you to edit the partition.<\/p>\n\n<p>You should then be able to use the resize command as well as be able to make new partitions on the USB drive, and should allow you to create an ext4 partition alongside the NTFS partition.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30901,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30901\/comments","question_id":30220,"owner":{"user_id":1543,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"sagarchalise","reputation":1269,"email_hash":"e6a4fe95eeee927da0f7146e881789fe"},"creation_date":1300445631,"last_activity_date":1300445631,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":73,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I resize an external USB NTFS partition?","body":"<p>Or you can use gnome-disk-utility found in Administration > Disk Utility. It will list your usb in storage device. <\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30220\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30220\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30220\/answers","question_id":30220,"owner":{"user_id":1272,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"chris","reputation":116,"email_hash":"850aa09e891970d0d3c126146dd23cb6"},"creation_date":1300048175,"last_edit_date":1300133832,"last_activity_date":1300445631,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":73,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I resize an external USB NTFS partition?","body":"<p>I have a new USB drive which came with a single NTFS partition.<\/p>\n\n<p>How can I shrink that so that I can create an ext4 partition?<\/p>\n\n<p>gparted does not seem to have the \"Resize\" option highlighted.<\/p>\n\n<p>Update:<\/p>\n\n<p>After following the directions below, after unmounting I am still not able to resize the partition.  There is a warning though:<\/p>\n\n<p>\"Unable to find mount point.  Unable to read the contents of this file system! Because of this, some operations may be unavailable. The following list of software packages is required for ntfs file system support: ntfsprogs\".<\/p>\n\n<p>However, with the partition mounted, I can read &amp; write to the file system on the drive just fine, and ntfsprogs is installed and current. <\/p>\n\n<p>What's next?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","evolution","updates","email"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26617,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26617\/comments","question_id":25874,"owner":{"user_id":10212,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Ilias el Matani","reputation":397,"email_hash":"a61a51e1614d7ec1fcb35889943ebfc2"},"creation_date":1297850841,"last_activity_date":1297850841,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Evolution email client will not open after last updates","body":"<p>Start Evolution on from the terminal and paste the output on pastebin.com<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Ilias@ubuntu:~$ evolution<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/25874\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/25874\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/25874\/answers","question_id":25874,"owner":{"user_id":10654,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Casey Jones","reputation":1,"email_hash":"e6c4ad2c95ebd590511504f5face9fa7"},"creation_date":1297452713,"last_activity_date":1300444418,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Evolution email client will not open after last updates","body":"<p>After applying available updates today, my Evolution app will not open. There is no sign of activity from the bar icon and, if I try from the Applications drop down menu, a small window briefly flashes on the desktop and then disappears. I tried to reinstall all the components from Synaptic with no change. Any ideas?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","gnome-panel","freeze"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30899\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30899\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30899\/answers","question_id":30899,"owner":{"user_id":11493,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Woltan","reputation":16,"email_hash":"477c0e2ba29fb086150c803c81a09a79"},"creation_date":1300443081,"last_activity_date":1300443081,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":11,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Gnome-Panel freezes occasionally","body":"<p>Hey folks,\nI have a problem with my Gnome-Panel. Occasionally my gnome-panel freezes, meaning that all icons (network status, sound, etc.) freeze along with the time displayed. When I kill the process, the panel restarts automatically and works just fine. Is there a way to prevent the panel from freezing?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thx in advance for any help, suggestion link etc!<\/p>\n\n<p>Cherio Woltan<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["gnome","unity","gnome-panel","desktop","gnome-shell"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30898,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30898\/comments","question_id":30895,"owner":{"user_id":10823,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"kamstrup","reputation":336,"email_hash":"4a6d483c449dc6560e3e12d49d5e12bb"},"creation_date":1300442662,"last_activity_date":1300442662,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Unity install removed window borders, and display drivers.","body":"<p>Are you selecting the \"classic\" session from the login screen? The empty-desktop-of-doom was a bug that plagued Unity a few weeks back - so you might also want to make 110% sure you have all the latest updates installed.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30895\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30895\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30895\/answers","question_id":30895,"owner":{"user_id":5924,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Vivek Sharma","reputation":281,"email_hash":"6de90de3ef09edb22902c259ff66bac9"},"creation_date":1300440570,"last_activity_date":1300442662,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Unity install removed window borders, and display drivers.","body":"<p>I installed unity, used for a while. Then i installed gnome-shell, used it for a while. Now decided to switch back to standard. Gnome is not working the way it use to be. I am using T61 with nvidia-latest drivers. Following issues...  <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Window borders are not showing. Installed compiz settings, and re-check window decorations option.  <\/li>\n<li>I had to re-install nvidia driver, as when I tried to apply normal visual effects, it said no display driver found. <\/li>\n<li>Gnome panel is not coming, and mouse pointer is a \"cross\" than a \"arrow\". I then opened a terminal and enter gnome-panel. Panel came and window borders came back.  <\/li>\n<li>Nothing is showing on desktop, and the right click is also not populating the menu.  <\/li>\n<li>When i loging, an error message saying, docky did not start and it requires compiz to work. After starting gnome-panel from terminal, i went to system>preferences>Appearance. And selected normal visual effects. It activated, i selected keep the settings.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Now when i restart or re-login, everything is gone. I have to run gnome-panel manually, and then re-enable visual setting. Ofcourse i can add gnome-panel in startup applications, but i want to know what has installing unity\/gnome-shell has done, that these setting are messed up. <\/p>\n\n<p>I manually removed mutter, as Appearance application was showing mutter installed, cant enable effects. What shall i do to get back a standard gnome-desktop back.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["unity","11.04"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30897,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30897\/comments","question_id":30775,"owner":{"user_id":10823,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"kamstrup","reputation":336,"email_hash":"4a6d483c449dc6560e3e12d49d5e12bb"},"creation_date":1300442098,"last_activity_date":1300442098,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":22,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why doesn't unity dash respect the gnome Main Menu entries?","body":"<p>Yes, this was due to a bug in Unity. When you get the latest version of the package unity-place-applications (version 0.2.40-0ubuntu1) this should work. The package hit the main archive last night and should be available in local mirrors shortly.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30775\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30775\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30775\/answers","question_id":30775,"owner":{"user_id":6699,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jon","reputation":247,"email_hash":"3c7af62d226bc7420d49128d03a5b139"},"creation_date":1300371525,"last_activity_date":1300442098,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":22,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why doesn't unity dash respect the gnome Main Menu entries?","body":"<p>I'm testing out Natty, and one thing I notice is that the custom commands I put in my old main menu don't appear in dash. I click \"Applications\" and what I get is different from the list in the \"Main Menu\" preferences. I'd like to be able to write a custom command and have it launched with Unity Dash, is that possible? <\/p>\n"},{"tags":["upgrade"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30455,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30455\/comments","question_id":30431,"owner":{"user_id":4384,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Reda Lazri","reputation":253,"email_hash":"509b57d362f01ec156f13dbdb415f25d"},"creation_date":1300185027,"last_edit_date":1300441182,"last_activity_date":1300441182,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":56,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"I got error when updating Ubuntu","body":"<p><strong>EDIT:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Try this instead:<\/p>\n\n<p>Close all package management, press ALT+F2 and type:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo cp \/var\/lib\/dpkg\/status \/var\/log\/dpkg\/status.old\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will create a backup file. Then:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gksudo gedit \/var\/lib\/dpkg\/status\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will open Gedit.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/54HWD.png\" alt=\"screenshot\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Search the package that causes the problem and delete its entry, make sure you leave a blank line between the entries after you delete.<\/p>\n\n<p>Now open Synaptic and reinstall the package or remove it if you are sure you don't want it.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30431\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30431\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30431\/answers","question_id":30431,"owner":{"user_id":9049,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Tom","reputation":11,"email_hash":"4ebd319924e8eff8899fa8a34fe979b2"},"creation_date":1300168243,"last_edit_date":1300184420,"last_activity_date":1300441182,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":56,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"I got error when updating Ubuntu","body":"<p>I am using Ubuntu 10.04.  I got an error when using update-manager to update.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/7luSU.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["c++"],"answer_count":5,"answers":[{"answer_id":30670,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30670\/comments","question_id":30668,"owner":{"user_id":1477,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user1477","reputation":181,"email_hash":"6cc1fd68cca76f691e5b22fd75f03f8b"},"creation_date":1300302540,"last_activity_date":1300302540,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":149,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Visual Studio alternatives for ubuntu?","body":"<p>There's no Visual Studio.  Microsoft doesn't tend to develop for Linux after all.  There is Anjuta, Eclipse, and several other IDEs that you can use, but you'd have to decide if any are to your liking.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30680,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30680\/comments","question_id":30668,"owner":{"user_id":11916,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Shawn J. Goff","reputation":180,"email_hash":"c9d6171a05be1fff6b0c6fc781fd3d05"},"creation_date":1300307224,"last_activity_date":1300307224,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":149,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Visual Studio alternatives for ubuntu?","body":"<p>In addtion to the ones listed by others: (<a href=\"http:\/\/projects.gnome.org\/anjuta\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Anjuta<\/a> &amp; <a href=\"http:\/\/www.eclipse.org\/cdt\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Eclipse<\/a>), there is also <a href=\"http:\/\/qt.nokia.com\/products\/developer-tools\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">QT Creator<\/a>. This probably provides the most Visual Studio -like experience.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30672,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30672\/comments","question_id":30668,"owner":{"user_id":2405,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Chris Wilson","reputation":2207,"email_hash":"ba6aba5790e7412dd4f6041c42a24c7e"},"creation_date":1300303367,"last_activity_date":1300303367,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":149,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Visual Studio alternatives for ubuntu?","body":"<p>In the Software Centre, there is an application called Eclipse. This, however, is a Java IDE and so is obviously unsuitable for a C++ developer. However, there is a version of Eclipse, not in the Software Centre, that does compile C++, called Eclipse CDT, and this can be <a href=\"http:\/\/www.eclipse.org\/cdt\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">downloaded from the Eclipse website<\/a>.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30879,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30879\/comments","question_id":30668,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1300430669,"last_activity_date":1300430669,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":149,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Visual Studio alternatives for ubuntu?","body":"<p><strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.anjuta.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Anjuta DevStudio<\/a><\/strong> (<a href=\"http:\/\/apt.marcoceppi.com\/p\/anjuta\" rel=\"nofollow\">Click to Install<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Anjuta DevStudio has been designed to be simple to operate yet powerful enough to fulfill all your programming needs. We've added many new features to Anjuta over the course of its development. Our focus is on delivering power and usability at the same time and making your software development enjoyable without overloading your senses. We intend to continue improving and stabilizing Anjuta to give you the best IDE experience possible. We hope you will have a good time using Anjuta. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/5HuHl.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30674,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30674\/comments","question_id":30668,"owner":{"user_id":8500,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"psusi","reputation":1989,"email_hash":"ce0150ff68789389639241c568dca423"},"creation_date":1300304269,"last_activity_date":1300304269,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":149,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Visual Studio alternatives for ubuntu?","body":"<p>It isn't as pretty and user friendly as VS or some of the other IDEs, but emacs is infinitely more powerful.  You do need to spend some time reading the manual to learn to use it though.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":30670,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30668\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30668\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30668\/answers","question_id":30668,"owner":{"user_id":12499,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Nadim A. Hachem","reputation":12,"email_hash":"ac4e93da230c624f5336c5feba045c1e"},"creation_date":1300302374,"last_edit_date":1300440879,"last_activity_date":1300440879,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":149,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Visual Studio alternatives for ubuntu?","body":"<p>Are there any alternative c++ IDEs like Microsoft's Visual Studio on ubuntu?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["performance","swap","ram-usage"],"answer_count":5,"answers":[{"answer_id":1379,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1379\/comments","question_id":1357,"owner":{"user_id":612,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"popey","reputation":1464,"email_hash":"a153cc0ebef591904c04d8bf487661de"},"creation_date":1281089099,"last_edit_date":1300440821,"last_activity_date":1300440821,"up_vote_count":9,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":537,"score":9,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to empty swap if there is free RAM?","body":"<p>Just because swap is allocated, doesn't mean it's being 'used'. Whilst programs like system monitor and top will show some of your swap space being allocated (in your example 770MB) that doesn't mean that the system is actively swapping in\/out.<\/p>\n\n<p>To find out if anything is swapping in\/out you can use the <code>vmstat<\/code> command. Leave it running a few seconds to settle down and watch the <code>si<\/code> (swapin) and <code>so<\/code> (swapout) columns. If nothing is happening then there is no reason to be concerned.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here's the output of running <code>vmstat 1<\/code>, where you can see my machine is not swapping at all.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>procs -----------memory---------- ---swap-- -----io---- -system-- ----cpu----\n r  b   swpd   free   buff  cache   si   so    bi    bo   in   cs us sy id wa\n 0  0  78588 230788   9596  72196    0    0     0     0  543  652 12  6 78  0\n 0  0  78588 230780   9596  72196    0    0     0     0  531  410  1  0 99  0\n 0  0  78588 230796   9596  72196    0    0     0     0  300  335  1  1 97  0\n 1  0  78588 230788   9608  72224    0    0    40     0  737  762  4  4 84  8\n 5  0  78588 230788   9608  72224    0    0     0     0  415  385  9  3 84  0\n 0  0  78588 230540   9616  72224    0    0     0    44  611  556 55  5 31  0\n 0  0  78588 230532   9616  72224    0    0     0     0  574  662  1  6 89  0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Yet here in <code>top<\/code> you can see I have swap space allocated:-<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Mem:    475236k total,   245076k used,   230160k free,     9720k buffers\nSwap:   491512k total,    78588k used,   412924k free,    72476k cached\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"answer_id":1359,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1359\/comments","question_id":1357,"owner":{"user_id":813,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"SpamapS","reputation":1571,"email_hash":"b2a3f5394f97fecc5318f6a034c5c283"},"creation_date":1281077270,"last_activity_date":1281077270,"up_vote_count":9,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":537,"score":8,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to empty swap if there is free RAM?","body":"<p>The Linux kernel underlying Ubuntu will automatically \"swap in\" those pages from disk to RAM as needed, so in general I'd say just let it happen naturally.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, if you really feel that you need to force it, (I can see a scenario where you would want to know the system will be responsive later) you can momentarily disable and re-enable swap<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo swapoff -a\nsudo swapon -a\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Be careful doing this, as you may make your system unstable, especially if its already low on RAM.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":1421,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1421\/comments","question_id":1357,"owner":{"user_id":252,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Erigami","reputation":808,"email_hash":"09f732c9a6b9cb2c405c086e63dc96d4"},"creation_date":1281112491,"last_activity_date":1281112491,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":537,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to empty swap if there is free RAM?","body":"<p>After mucking around with <a href=\"https:\/\/help.ubuntu.com\/community\/SwapFaq\" rel=\"nofollow\">swappiness<\/a> for a couple of days, I've come to the conclusion that the kernel should be left to its own devices. It knows what it's doing, and it's optimized to give you the best experience. <\/p>\n\n<p>Unless you have a really good reason for wanting that disk back, I'd leave it be. <\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":1423,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1423\/comments","question_id":1357,"owner":{"user_id":742,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jo\u00e3o Pinto","reputation":5838,"email_hash":"29020331a486bb3f9e88031a0cfea800"},"creation_date":1281113349,"last_activity_date":1281113349,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":537,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to empty swap if there is free RAM?","body":"<p>There is a common misunderstanding that having too much swap available will lead to performance degradation because the system will start to use it.\nSwap is only used when required, swapping out memory data which is not actively used (long time sleeping\/blocked apps)) will leave more RAM for disk I\/O caching and running apps. If the data is not being accessed SWAP is the best place to be.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":1968,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/1968\/comments","question_id":1357,"owner":{"user_id":139,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Rory McCann","reputation":306,"email_hash":"16e12e337f6edc3750681492656097ed"},"creation_date":1281555309,"last_activity_date":1281555309,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":537,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to empty swap if there is free RAM?","body":"<p>It doesn't affect performance if your swap space is occupied. The only performance penalty is is stuff is going in\/out of swap. If nothing is being swapped in\/swapped out, then you don't have to worry about anything.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":1379,"favorite_count":2,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/1357\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/1357\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/1357\/answers","question_id":1357,"owner":{"user_id":38,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jfoucher","reputation":278,"email_hash":"6343c1ff1b56af54c621adbf2c1638a1"},"creation_date":1281077003,"last_edit_date":1294058990,"last_activity_date":1300440821,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":537,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to empty swap if there is free RAM?","body":"<p>When I open a RAM-intensive app (VirtualBox set at 2 Gb RAM), Some swap space is generally used, depending on what else I have open at the time.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, when I quit that last application, the 2 Gb of RAM are freed, but the same swap space use remains.<\/p>\n\n<p>How can I tell ubuntu to stop using that swap and to revert to using the RAM?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit<\/strong> : Right now, about 2 hours after having closed VirtualBox, I have 1.6 Gb free RAM  and still 770 Mb in swap.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["graphics","ati","9.10","java"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":12594,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/12594\/comments","question_id":12573,"owner":{"user_id":5768,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"aking1012","reputation":1398,"email_hash":"61d2bc0830d4865a62c42c5e23a8c85f"},"creation_date":1289439218,"last_activity_date":1289439218,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count"