my question is if this can be a Java problem or a video card (+ driver) problem ? <\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["windows"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30894\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30894\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30894\/answers","question_id":30894,"owner":{"user_id":12139,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Yosef","reputation":131,"email_hash":"5195dbcd26c2108c60c11d6479bf9777"},"creation_date":1300059536,"last_activity_date":1300440229,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":7,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How make best secure partition of 1 hard drive 320 GB for UBUNTU+VirtualMachine with Windows?","body":"<p>Hi, <\/p>\n\n<p>How make best secure partition of 1 hard drive 320 GB for <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>UBUNTU+Lamp<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Virtual Machine with Windows<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Option for possible windows installation<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>My proposal \n(I don't know about user permission of each part and other issues - please help me with them):<\/p>\n\n<p>primary:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>\/: 30 GB       (?)<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>\/home: 200 GB  (755)<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Extended (logical):<\/p>\n\n<p>3.1 swap: 4 GB  (?)<\/p>\n\n<p>3.2 \/media\/myvirtualmachine 30GB (755)<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p><strong>Which problems with security can be with my proposal, how would you make the partition and what weakness do you have with your proposal?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>My Computer:\n320GB hard disk\n3GB DDR2 RAM<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks,<\/p>\n\n<p>Yosef<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["password","suspend-resume"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":22737,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/22737\/comments","question_id":22735,"owner":{"user_id":861,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Scaine","reputation":3462,"email_hash":"0f9bda74e3a976957db2ab8bb277cb58"},"creation_date":1295694138,"last_edit_date":1295696567,"last_activity_date":1295696567,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":215,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"Disable locking the screen after resuming from suspend","body":"<p>Start gconf-editor (press ALT-F2, then type <code>gconf-editor<\/code>).<\/p>\n\n<p>Seach down to Apps\/gnome-power-manager, then click on \"lock\".<\/p>\n\n<p>You have two choices : either untick \"suspend\", or tick \"use_screensaver_settings\" (of course, you'd then have to go to screensaver preferences and remove the \"lock screen\" option.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/vl4nf.jpg\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/p>\n\n<p>And :<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/tYmxo.jpg\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":25048,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/25048\/comments","question_id":22735,"owner":{"user_id":10321,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"isoma","reputation":1,"email_hash":"d82639cc57e24ace0d81266dc629129a"},"creation_date":1297013206,"last_activity_date":1297013206,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":215,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Disable locking the screen after resuming from suspend","body":"<p>There is more work to do, beyond unticking \u201cuse screensaver settings\u201d.<\/p>\n\n<p>See <a href=\"http:\/\/library.gnome.org\/users\/gnome-power-manager\/stable\/preferences-advanced.html.en\" rel=\"nofollow\">Advanced preferences<\/a> for GNOME Power Manager<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":22737,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/22735\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/22735\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/22735\/answers","question_id":22735,"owner":{"user_id":2192,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Ingo Gerth","reputation":921,"email_hash":"7cf8ec4216fbd6711dd698276151ccb7"},"creation_date":1295692775,"last_edit_date":1300438742,"last_activity_date":1300438742,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":215,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Disable locking the screen after resuming from suspend","body":"<p>One thing I like for MacBooks is that they are usable within a second after opening their lid when they were on stand by.<\/p>\n\n<p>Ubuntu always requires me to enter my password when I resume from suspend, which can be very annoying.<br>\nHow can I disable this?<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Related bugs<\/strong><br>\nIt turns out that this really is undesired behavior, and there are several bugs related to this issue.<br>\n<a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/gnome-power\/+bug\/553646\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bug #553646 on launchpad<\/a><br>\n<a href=\"https:\/\/bugzilla.gnome.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=643036\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bug #643036 on GNOME bugzilla<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["touchpad","synaptics"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":16522,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/16522\/comments","question_id":16485,"owner":{"user_id":5691,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"karthick87","reputation":8739,"email_hash":"b41802fe7f333c0b2b2b68be7da4f757"},"creation_date":1291717700,"last_edit_date":1291726015,"last_activity_date":1291726015,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":197,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Disable touchpad hardware buttons","body":"<p><strong>Disabling Touchpad:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Press <strong>ALT+F2<\/strong> and type <strong>gconf-editor<\/strong> and click Run.<br>\n<img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/aPqzB.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><br>\nNavigate to desktop>gnome>peripherals>touchpad,in the right panel uncheck the entry <strong>touchpad_enabled<\/strong>.<br>\n<img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/SGiJS.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><br>\nNow your tochpad will be disabled.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>To turn of touchpad completely:<\/strong><br>\nTo turn of touchpad completely install <a href=\"http:\/\/packages.ubuntu.com\/gpointing-device-settings\" rel=\"nofollow\">gpointing-device-settings<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/apt.ubuntu.com\/p\/gpointing-device-settings\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/bit.ly\/software-large\" alt=\"Install gpointing-device-settings\"><\/a> after installation you can access it under <strong>System >>Preferences>>Touchpad<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>UPDATE:<\/strong>   <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>If you want to use synclient then you have to edit your xorg.conf file.   <\/p>\n\n<p><code>sudo gedit \/etc\/X11\/xorg.conf<\/code>          <\/p><\/li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"http:\/\/paste.ubuntu.com\/540610\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Instructions to edit xorg.conf<\/a><\/strong>   <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>FYI:<\/strong><br>\n<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showpost.php?p=10155078&amp;postcount=1\" rel=\"nofollow\">Also See this tutorial on disabling touchpad.<\/a><\/strong><br>\n<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.linuxine.com\/2008\/06\/how-to-disable-touchpad-in-ubuntu.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">How to disable\/enable touchpad in Ubuntu<\/a><\/strong><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/16485\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/16485\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/16485\/answers","question_id":16485,"owner":{"user_id":2245,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jetxee","reputation":121,"email_hash":"40c739bec0c3a9baeb3817acc94d2f56"},"creation_date":1291679477,"last_edit_date":1292599585,"last_activity_date":1300437217,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":197,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Disable touchpad hardware buttons","body":"<p>I'd like to disable hardware buttons on the synaptic touchpad, but still be able to use the touchpand and \"tap\"-click on its surface. I don't find the related options in the output of <code>synclient -l<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Any idea how to do it?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["graphics"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30887\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30887\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30887\/answers","question_id":30887,"owner":{"user_id":8583,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"janoChen","reputation":331,"email_hash":"bdb858f1bf23f8d39d75485dacebb5b4"},"creation_date":1300436852,"last_activity_date":1300436852,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":5,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Disabling autoscaling when the text inside gets bigger than the object in Dia (diagrams editor)?","body":"<p>When the text gets longer than, for instance, a circle.\nIt just scales the circle. Is there any way to make the text go to the next line?<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/3RC7A.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/4F9M2.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["software-recommendation","display","info"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":23831,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/23831\/comments","question_id":23806,"owner":{"user_id":8844,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jgbelacqua","reputation":2949,"email_hash":"4808cca0b254b6203fc9bdf4d9e58e09"},"creation_date":1296278399,"last_edit_date":1298341108,"last_activity_date":1298341108,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":161,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"istat menu 3 of Mac equivalent?","body":"<p>You can get what you want with <a href=\"http:\/\/packages.ubuntu.com\/gkrellm\" rel=\"nofollow\">gkrellm<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/apt.ubuntu.com\/p\/gkrellm\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/9SOjZ.png\" alt=\"Install gkrellm\"><\/a>\n -- it works out of the box, but you will probably want to tinker a bit to get the look and the info you're after. <\/p>\n\n<p>You can install the basic application from the Software Center or via the command line, with <code>apt-get install gkrellm<\/code> , but there are numerous plugins and themes available.  <\/p>\n\n<p>You can see the easily installed plugins with <code>apt-cache search gkrellm<\/code> .  Here's an extract:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gkrellm-bfm - system load plugin for gkrellm with a duck\ngkrellm-hdplop - A hard drive activity monitor GKrellM plugin\ngkrellm-ibam - Advanced battery monitor for laptops - gkrellm plugin\ngkrellm-leds - Keyboard LED monitor for GKrellM\ngkrellm-mailwatch - GKrellM plugin to watch mailboxes in multiple panels\ngkrellm-mldonkey - mldonkey plugin for gkrellm2\ngkrellm-radio - FM radio tuner for GKrellM\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And here's a themes directory (the last time I installed it, this is the site I used to find a theme I liked): <a href=\"http:\/\/www.muhri.net\/gkrellm\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">muhri.net\/gkrellm<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Another option is <a href=\"http:\/\/packages.ubuntu.com\/conky\" rel=\"nofollow\">conky<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/apt.ubuntu.com\/p\/conky\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/bit.ly\/software-large\" alt=\"Install conky\"><\/a>\n .   It is also installable from the Software center or via apt-get.   It is extremely configurable, and if you search, you'll find many screenshots of customized conky installations.  (Here's one from <a href=\"http:\/\/conky-pitstop.wikidot.com\/g10ii%3ag-2010-ii\" rel=\"nofollow\">conky pitstop <\/a> .)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":23807,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/23807\/comments","question_id":23806,"owner":{"user_id":2079,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"MichaelMS","reputation":418,"email_hash":"3c3bdffefbee09034d004f0e446ab0ea"},"creation_date":1296265918,"last_activity_date":1296265918,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":161,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"istat menu 3 of Mac equivalent?","body":"<p>It's not a direct equivalent, but you can add the System Monitor panel applet, which will show you real-time graphs of CPU, Memory, Network, etc.  Right click on the panel > Add To Panel and add the System Monitor applet.  Then, right-click on the applet in the panel and in its preferences you can choose which resources to monitor.  It doesn't have a drop-down menu like istat does, but it opens up the full system monitor when you click on it.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":23850,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/23850\/comments","question_id":23806,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1296292991,"last_edit_date":1296306086,"last_activity_date":1296306086,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":161,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"istat menu 3 of Mac equivalent?","body":"<p>You should try InfoPanel (an screenlet).<\/p>\n\n<p>You could install it by installing screenlets from the software center, then Downloading <a href=\"http:\/\/gnome-look.org\/content\/download.php?content=100042&amp;id=1&amp;tan=56924059\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> then going to Applications -> Accesories -> Screenlets and then Clicking install and selecting the downloaded file.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/ytzqr.png\" alt=\"Screenshot\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":23884,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/23884\/comments","question_id":23806,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1296313882,"last_edit_date":1300435048,"last_activity_date":1300435048,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":161,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"istat menu 3 of Mac equivalent?","body":"<p>You can also use <a href=\"http:\/\/gnome-look.org\/content\/show.php\/conky~meet~faenza?content=133086&amp;PHPSESSID=111fced54abd994675dad2faf33e8843\" rel=\"nofollow\">conky-faenza<\/a> <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/FqHMV.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>To install first install conky from software center then download <a href=\"http:\/\/gnome-look.org\/content\/download.php?content=133086&amp;id=1&amp;tan=94538081&amp;PHPSESSID=111fced54abd994675dad2faf33e8843\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> and extract the archive into your home folder and <kbd>ALT<\/kbd> + <kbd>F2<\/kbd> and run conky or add it to startup applications.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/23806\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/23806\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/23806\/answers","question_id":23806,"owner":{"user_id":1813,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"prosseek","reputation":270,"email_hash":"74758c702067a3490094451e475e28c5"},"creation_date":1296265592,"last_edit_date":1296278004,"last_activity_date":1300435048,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":161,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"istat menu 3 of Mac equivalent?","body":"<p>With Mac, I have istat that shows computer info (memory\/cpu\/network ...) in real time.\nDoes ubuntu has similar application? <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/S7et4.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["intel-graphics","resolution","tv","hdmi","hd-video"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":17984,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/17984\/comments","question_id":17261,"owner":{"user_id":6205,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Andy","reputation":290,"email_hash":"140b66f975c1ef94b99d9532eeb25d26"},"creation_date":1292634731,"last_activity_date":1292634731,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":796,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can fix HDMI HDTV overscan when I my TV has no aspect ratio setting?","body":"<p>You may be able to use <code>xrandr<\/code> to add a new mode to the specific output and then select that new mode.  See <code>xrandr --addmode<\/code> and <code>xrandr --mode<\/code> in the xrandr manpage.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":26595,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26595\/comments","question_id":17261,"owner":{"user_id":3922,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"bdr529","reputation":275,"email_hash":"6264ae470937f3decede1828a4528f31"},"creation_date":1297839163,"last_activity_date":1297839163,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":796,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can fix HDMI HDTV overscan when I my TV has no aspect ratio setting?","body":"<p>Maybe you can try the --pos option of xrandr. See the answer from Vadim Rutkovsky to this question:\n<a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/26475\/geforce-gt240m-how-to-disable-notebook-screen-and-enable-external-monitor\">Geforce GT240M: How to disable Notebook screen and enable external Monitor<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"bounty_amount":50,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/17261\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/17261\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/17261\/answers","question_id":17261,"owner":{"user_id":4839,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Colin Dean","reputation":26,"email_hash":"e3c791e8e5da39bf88b09dfb089de01b"},"creation_date":1292289681,"last_activity_date":1300433617,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":796,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can fix HDMI HDTV overscan when I my TV has no aspect ratio setting?","body":"<p>I have a 32\" Vizio HDTV. It's a few years old, but running well. I just connected a new nettop to it using HDMI out. It's the Intel 3x00 graphics chipset.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm seeing overscan, where the resolution in Ubuntu is set to 1280x720, but the TV itself is 1366x768. When I go into the <strong>Monitors<\/strong> control applet, I cannot change the resolution to anything other than the current or 640x480.<\/p>\n\n<p>A user had a similar overscan problem, but <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4358\/how-do-i-fix-overscan-on-my-hdmi-hdtv\">fixed the overscan by adjusting his TV's aspect ratio settings<\/a>. I do not have that luxury.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a way I can do this without having to delve into <code>xorg.conf<\/code> or other command-line craziness? I'm more than com