AR9287 Wireless Network Adapter (PCI-Express) (rev 01)<\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["video","record"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"closed_date":1300452504,"closed_reason":"exact duplicate","question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30869\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30869\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30869\/answers","question_id":30869,"locked_date":1300452571,"owner":{"user_id":8673,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Gonzalo","reputation":217,"email_hash":"288759e1f8f5f551d9c490f477dfbfd3"},"creation_date":1300425899,"last_activity_date":1300432523,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":44,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"What is the easiest way to record my desktop in Ubuntu?","body":"<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>Possible Duplicate:<\/strong><br>\n  <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/4428\/how-to-create-a-screencast\">How to create a screencast?<\/a>  <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n\n\n<p>I want to make a video tutorial on some Ubuntu functionality but don't know how to record it.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["unity","unity-2d","places","fullscreen"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30882\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30882\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30882\/answers","question_id":30882,"owner":{"user_id":5434,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Evan","reputation":41,"email_hash":"884db8fa9847249e5b21c2a105741b8f"},"creation_date":1300432392,"last_activity_date":1300432392,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":11,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Make Unity 2D Places open up fullscreen","body":"<p>How to make Unity 2D Places open up full-screen?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","64-bit","dpkg","update"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30880,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30880\/comments","question_id":30848,"owner":{"user_id":12271,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jrtayloriv","reputation":131,"email_hash":"9a279500b3c24f2a47e5b5684b3e154c"},"creation_date":1300430687,"last_activity_date":1300430687,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":21,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Update fails with unrecoverable dpkg fatal error","body":"<p>You might want to take a look at the following:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https:\/\/answers.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+question\/145648\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/answers.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+question\/145648<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"https:\/\/answers.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/apt\/+question\/131789\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/answers.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/apt\/+question\/131789<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Unfortunately for you, both of them point to a corrupted disk ...<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30848\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30848\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30848\/answers","question_id":30848,"owner":{"user_id":12573,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jonthue Michel","reputation":6,"email_hash":"9a89aa625b926c3be0984953de3bf585"},"creation_date":1300409781,"last_edit_date":1300413034,"last_activity_date":1300430687,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":21,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Update fails with unrecoverable dpkg fatal error","body":"<p>Hello I keep receiving this error every-time i try to do some updates, I tried sudo dpkg --configure, sudo apt-get update and sudo apt-get install -f but they failed on me.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>installArchives() failed: (Reading database ... \n(Reading database ... 5%\n(Reading database ... 10%\n(Reading database ... 15%\n(Reading database ... 20%\n(Reading database ... 25%\n(Reading database ... 30%\n(Reading database ... 35%\n(Reading database ... 40%\n(Reading database ... 45%\n(Reading database ... 50%\n(Reading database ... 55%dpkg: unrecoverable fatal error, aborting:\n\n failed to read on buffer copy for files list for package `libc6-i386': Is a directory\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["git","crontab"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":13685,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/13685\/comments","question_id":13677,"owner":{"user_id":1614,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"CraigM","reputation":71,"email_hash":"ec18b68fb719cdef24375dc3a0ffb29f"},"creation_date":1290006882,"last_activity_date":1290006882,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":133,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to use crontab, .netrc, and git push?","body":"<p>I think the problem is in your .gitconfig. Have you set the user name in there? Also, if you're backing up to a remote machine, I'd highly recommend using SSH for this instead.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/13677\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/13677\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/13677\/answers","question_id":13677,"owner":{"user_id":2189,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Jon","reputation":148,"email_hash":"919051499920a08803d46fd38265c7f8"},"creation_date":1290004059,"last_edit_date":1290030762,"last_activity_date":1300430017,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":133,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to use crontab, .netrc, and git push?","body":"<p>Hi all,<\/p>\n\n<p>I am in the process of automating the backups from various servers to a central point then pushing those config changes into a git repo so i can track any changes over time.  The rest of the scripts are working well, I can copy \/ rsync the files across the network to a central point.  The last script is to get the config files to be put into \/ updated in repository.  The script is as follows:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>#!\/bin\/bash\nclear\n\nSERVERNAME=\"betty\"\nSCRIPTDIR=\"\/home\/jon\"\nGITROOT=\"\/tmp\/git\"\nTEMPROOT=\"\/tmp\/backups\"\nBACKUPROOTDIR=\"\/mnt\/backups\"\n\necho \"  - running as user: $UID\"\n\necho \"backingup git config on $SERVERNAME\"\necho \"\"\n\n# check to see if root backup folder exists, otherwise create it.\nif [ -d $GITROOT ]; then\n    rm -rf $GITROOT\nfi\nmkdir $GITROOT\n\ncd $GITROOT\n\necho \"  - testing if home is where I think it should be!\"\necho $HOME\necho \"  - testing if it can see netrc\"\ntail $HOME\/.netrc\n\n\ngit clone http:\/\/192.168.10.97:8000\/repositories\/HOH-config-backups.git\ncd HOH-config-backups\n\necho \"  - copy Configuration Folders across\"\ncp -r $BACKUPROOTDIR\/Configuration\/* $GITROOT\/HOH-config-backups\/\ncp -r $BACKUPROOTDIR\/scripts $GITROOT\/HOH-config-backups\/\n\ngit add .\ngit commit -a -m \"committing any new configuration changes!\"\ngit push origin master\n\necho \"\"\necho \"Git repo updated\"\n\necho \"\"\necho \"  - backing up this script\"\nFIREWIGSCRIPTLOC=\"$BACKUPROOTDIR\/scripts\/$SERVERNAME\"\n\nif [ ! -d $FIREWIGSCRIPTLOC ]; then\n    mkdir $FIREWIGSCRIPTLOC\nfi\n\ncp \/home\/jon\/gitConfig.sh  $FIREWIGSCRIPTLOC\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The git repo is on a different machine in the network using Apache and HTTP-backend.exe (smart HTTP protocol).  If I run this script as me \"jon\" it works.  If I run it in crontab it fails.  git uses the \/home\/jon\/.netrc file for authentication:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>machine 192.168.10.97\nlogin gitconfig\npassword 1234579\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The log from crontab is:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>TERM environment variable not set.\n  - running as user: 1000\nbackingup git config on betty\n\n  - testing if home is where I think it should be!\n\/home\/jon\n  - testing if it can see netrc\nmachine 192.168.10.97\nlogin gitconfig\npassword 1234579\ngot 08de5bc2b27b4940d9412256e76d5e3c3d9dbcdd\nwalk 08de5bc2b27b4940d9412256e76d5e3c3d9dbcdd\ngot be880f2d306778a538d592e7a02eb19f416612f7\ngot bd387e8def9f77aafa798bf53e80d949aba443e8\ngot 1bc1a59e12775841d4c59d77c63b8a73823138c2\nwalk bd387e8def9f77aafa798bf53e80d949aba443e8\nGetting alternates list for http:\/\/192.168.10.97:8000\/repositories\/HOH-config-backups.git\ngot 030512237bca72faf211e0e8ec2906164eac34f6\ngot 9bc2f575240bc1f61ff7d69777ce1a165d06b184\ngot b8400f7f01429104a9d4786a6bb1a16d293e37c1\ngot 2403b5bf611010e0b401f776f0e23b09ce744838\ngot 1a27944c48269ef3608a8f2466e43402d06faac0\ngot b686f45b7d57af4fa8ca0d528bb85216d6247e19\nGetting pack list for http:\/\/192.168.10.97:8000\/repositories\/HOH-config-backups.git\nGetting index for pack ae881957c0f0e8c22eb6cc889a22ef78eb4ce6ff\nGetting pack ae881957c0f0e8c22eb6cc889a22ef78eb4ce6ff\n which contains ff84d6d48e9326066438d167a10251218d612b3d\nwalk b686f45b7d57af4fa8ca0d528bb85216d6247e19\ngot 364e30daec17814073e668f490bb84af891fe1f7\ngot 23f6497e7f9b80e0d90adad73bd0407a0e5ac6ce\ngot 9e77c47574b5e23ea669afe0c23ab235e4917ee1\ngot 6654e0d328a216b3783e98c47206cb2d01b3353d\ngot 28821ffd437d2689ffb82c6e4b9c3f5372c95c4b\ngot 8c384a24f645389e4d4b08013c79e9e73a658342\ngot d203be0123736ee025ce20c081f1489098648dfc\ngot 1852603bf7709e71417d8ccec02390279d533642\ngot fb753a26b20b04694419fce8ecdaa8dbec105cf1\ngot 736028997cd84dd1c135f57e9d246674b9cd0b9d\ngot 7af836249e20096d0476a548d5be702a071cdd4b\ngot 240dc39d9db50df63073fc7927b2d002dfa0f54c\ngot 93abd36e3935a01011eb753b635a1a0e984bf31e\ngot c6269e28fecf4d8d0d98b9358aecb3acff02df44\ngot b0aa29432f73e64032682a351d436c24b14078ab\nwalk 240dc39d9db50df63073fc7927b2d002dfa0f54c\ngot 58fb66d9f35f8a5e32ff4683309c5f0c2a3a03c5\ngot 0da2def4de0565483cdbe6b87418ee2beb122e58\ngot 0f6a86c6f87ed52ad2ed01e5c6edd661d364930c\ngot 437a93d27b5bb89c739a0564a34a616e832c3ebe\ngot fe0385abe5c0acd8462268dac330bae00e934f1b\ngot 24259f8f5c5c9ee974a75fe3d1e07c02e3e20fe9\ngot d29f624bf1a5eceedaa86c10fee35f62747c7d04\ngot 0154e4c987132585ea7a92b77d02dba285512d6b\n\ngot eda8bf526567c25ee70addb2ad3c3c6aa57eac77\ngot 9f3d9d7262d66f9fa4f6a13b7c86199953f4bc4e\ngot 8e20881e19667aa22245d0598646991067455a4d\ngot abb1123145689b35eb19519952c71253ee45fa98\ngot dfeff593c79b4156ce2ce1adf043d0e80356488c\ngot e20c5b48b1d360e0bcf34189e3f3d2bbf23e92cc\ngot b13eb81cc274780322ecf786372320343926bec9\nwalk 8de83868b3fac748b0a55eba16c8f668ec852abb\ngot b5961421bbc42afe7a07cc1c8b615aba26ba74d7\ngot 2650ba819019df4193b482733e29ca79b29f3f2c\ngot b3111e1be8103e91803a97a817ed81f28025aca1\ngot b060be934d709684f5eb5dad3c03932a3589e864\ngot cf70d2043f081d7a4438e9d5a290a9f986c84060\ngot 80bf0f1cc836feab86d6935bb7968d8555a8d531\ngot da318d167920e34bc6573e4fc236249ccbbee316\ngot d82ac853d387b760149599e6e1ab96403f6ec672\ngot 0005f691d1f46550fdb4e56025f52e30a5b18cc2\nInitialized empty Git repository in \/tmp\/git\/HOH-config-backups\/.git\/\n  - copy Configuration Folders across\nCreated commit 424df2f: committing any new configuration changes!\n 3 files changed, 55 insertions(+), 1 deletions(-)\n create mode 100755 scripts\/betty\/gitConfig.sh\nerror: Cannot access URL http:\/\/192.168.10.97:8000\/repositories\/HOH-config-backups.git\/, return code 22\nerror: failed to push some refs to 'http:\/\/192.168.10.97:8000\/repositories\/HOH-config-backups.git'\n\n    Git repo updated\n\n      - backing up this script\n    cp: cannot create regular file `\/mnt\/backups\/scripts\/betty\/gitConfig.sh': Permission denied\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>my crontab is:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code># m h  dom mon dow   command\n04 * * * * \/home\/jon\/gitConfig.sh &gt; \/tmp\/gitconfig.log 2&gt;&amp;1\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I open it by doing:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$crontab -e\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>i.e. not as root.<\/p>\n\n<p>I am a bit confused as to why it is not running as my user (or what user id 1000 is).  Not sure what I need to do to get the push with git to work within crontab.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>edit:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>found out about the userid:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>jon@betty:~$ id\nuid=1000(jon) gid=1000(jon)  groups=4(adm),20(dialout),24(cdrom),46(plugdev),109(sambashare),114(lpadmin),115(admin),1000(jon)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>here is my $HOME\/.gitconfig file:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>[user]\n    name = Jon Hawkins\n    email = jonathan1@houseofhawkins.com\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Thanks<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["installation","edubuntu"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30877\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30877\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30877\/answers","question_id":30877,"owner":{"user_id":4157,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Chethan S.","reputation":197,"email_hash":"3d52f30902195380b1850238ef1a623c"},"creation_date":1300429728,"last_activity_date":1300429728,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":12,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Error during Edubuntu installation: process:226","body":"<p>We recently introduced Edbuntu to a team of school teachers. One of them tried installing Edubuntu in their school computers and have reported us this problem. I have no answer for the problem. So can anyone help?<\/p>\n\n<p>One of the teacher's wrote:\nI was able to install edubuntu in some of the pc. But not able to install in PCs with celeron processor 2.40 GHz , 1GB RAM &amp; HDD 40GB. Im getting error message:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>process:226 -  Glib warning: getpwuid_r(): failed due to unknown user id(0)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","kernel","update"],"answer_count":4,"answers":[{"answer_id":30205,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30205\/comments","question_id":30196,"owner":{"user_id":7788,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Trevi\u00f1o","reputation":44,"email_hash":"b452213dba394e3fa816db630320e27a"},"creation_date":1300040683,"last_activity_date":1300040683,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":921,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is it possible to use a 2.6.38 kernel with 10.10?","body":"<p>You can also use the debs coming from Natty... Just go <a href=\"http:\/\/packages.ubuntu.com\/source\/natty\/linux\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> and download the \"linux-image-2.6.38-<em>\" and the needed \"linux-headers-2.6.38-<\/em>\" you want and install the debian files. They should work with no issues.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30515,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30515\/comments","question_id":30196,"owner":{"user_id":12434,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"flammon","reputation":11,"email_hash":"da1f8701b59feb60691ebf9dad802d91"},"creation_date":1300213423,"last_activity_date":1300213423,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":921,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is it possible to use a 2.6.38 kernel with 10.10?","body":"<p>Here are the files that you need.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/kernel.ubuntu.com\/~kernel-ppa\/mainline\/v2.6.38-natty\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/kernel.ubuntu.com\/~kernel-ppa\/mainline\/v2.6.38-natty\/<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30197,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30197\/comments","question_id":30196,"owner":{"user_id":10581,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Olli","reputation":1500,"email_hash":"1f5253390c0abc3691c139f315cbcbc8"},"creation_date":1300034954,"last_activity_date":1300034954,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":921,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is it possible to use a 2.6.38 kernel with 10.10?","body":"<p>Yes, it's possible.<\/p>\n\n<p>I didn't found any PPA repositories offering 2.6.38 for Maverick. However, I found <a href=\"http:\/\/www.megatek.net.br\/customkernels\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this site<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>It doesn't look very promising (Spanish, CSS copied from kernel.org), but I don't think they are trying to mimic kernel.org. For installation, download the <code>.deb<\/code> file and open it with package manager or from terminal with <code>dpkg -i filename.deb<\/code>.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30876,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30876\/comments","question_id":30196,"owner":{"user_id":12585,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"TvL","reputation":1,"email_hash":"99a7b04d0d8e9cb0258e24692064fba5"},"creation_date":1300429231,"last_activity_date":1300429231,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":921,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is it possible to use a 2.6.38 kernel with 10.10?","body":"<p>I've installed the kernel in Olli's post. Works good. I don't notice any difference though.\nI first installed the kernel from natty, but that seems to be compiled with gcc version 4.5. I cannot get the nvidia module to work, because when I compile that, it used the local gcc version 4.4...<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't want to go through too much troubles, so I'll leave my gcc alone.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":2,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30196\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30196\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30196\/answers","question_id":30196,"owner":{"user_id":1982,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"gsedej","reputation":262,"email_hash":"a459835a70a7f9efb1ddf5e9e136fb59"},"creation_date":1300032296,"last_edit_date":1300033019,"last_activity_date":1300429231,"up_vote_count":9,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":921,"score":9,"community_owned":false,"title":"Is it possible to use a 2.6.38 kernel with 10.10?","body":"<p>Hi! I have simple question. Is it possible to use new 2.6.38 kernel with Ubuntu 10.10? Does there exists some PPA or you need to compile?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["unity","11.04","desktop"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30873,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30873\/comments","question_id":30856,"owner":{"user_id":12271,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jrtayloriv","reputation":131,"email_hash":"9a279500b3c24f2a47e5b5684b3e154c"},"creation_date":1300428459,"last_activity_date":1300428459,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Should my Dash be full screen?","body":"<p>Someone has already posted a bug report about this at launchpad:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/unity\/+bug\/732008\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/unity\/+bug\/732008<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30856\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30856\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30856\/answers","question_id":30856,"owner":{"user_id":931,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Lee Jarratt","reputation":166,"email_hash":"44643b6ae96f7deb51a6a708471ddab9"},"creation_date":1300413953,"last_activity_date":1300428459,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Should my Dash be full screen?","body":"<p>I am using Ubuntu Natty with the latest updates and the Unity Dash is in full screen. My laptop has a 17\" screen with a resolution of 1366 x 768. If this is not the normal behaviour I will report it as a bug on Launchpad but I'm not sure of the specifics if anyone could tell me what the specifics are regarding the Dash size.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you in advance.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","sound","pulseaudio","automation","headset"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":22772,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/22772\/comments","question_id":21472,"owner":{"user_id":6658,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Chauncellor","reputation":535,"email_hash":"55a7abb8002c56e68c637d76e18fa2f8"},"creation_date":1295711168,"last_activity_date":1295711168,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":197,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I automatically switch to USB headset when plugged in?","body":"<p>This is actually a bug in Pulseaudio.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/pulseaudio\/+bug\/640328\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here<\/a> is a recent bug report on the situation, but it might be a dupe of <a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/pulseaudio\/+bug\/443306\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> older (but reportedly fixed) one.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here's a workaround that you could possibly use. Create a text file and paste this in:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>#! \/bin\/bash\n\namixer cset iface=MIXER,name='Input Source' 1\namixer cset iface=MIXER,name='Output Source' 1\nexit\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If it is fact your third one then you should replace the end numbers on the commands with the number '2'. If fourth, then '3'. And so on.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can then make a launcher on the panel and click on it every time you plug in the headset. It's an ugly workaround for now but until it is fixed (i.e. Pulseaudio remembers preferred devices) I don't see much else you can do.<\/p>\n\n<p>You could do some <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=1290438\" rel=\"nofollow\">extreme crazy workaround involving writing udev rules<\/a>.... but is it worth it? ;)<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":22772,"favorite_count":2,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/21472\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/21472\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/21472\/answers","question_id":21472,"owner":{"user_id":7146,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"d3vid","reputation":90,"email_hash":"7a3a6b56c78ce76bf8293ba227e76ee6"},"creation_date":1294993697,"last_edit_date":1300426792,"last_activity_date":1300426792,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":197,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I automatically switch to USB headset when plugged in?","body":"<p>Whenever I plugged in my old audio jack headset, sound was immediately diverted from my speakers to the headset speakers, and the microphone was immediately available.<\/p>\n\n<p>When I plug in my new USB headset, I have to open Sound Preferences and switch both input and output to the headset.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any way to make this happen automatically?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm using a Fujitsu-Siemens Amilo Pi laptop, Maverick and a Logitech H330 USB headset.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["ubuntu-one","sync"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":19314,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/19314\/comments","question_id":19300,"owner":{"user_id":7983,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"bisi","reputation":115,"email_hash":"fe235d1b9655ad2c373a8b6cbc911ceb"},"creation_date":1293655321,"last_activity_date":1293655321,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":125,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Laptop not syncing with Ubuntu One","body":"<p>I am not sure about your particular problem, but may have a similar situation. From what I gather, there is a slow syncing ongoing issue: \n<a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/UbuntuOne\/FAQ\/WhyIsItTakingSoLongForMyFilesToSync\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/UbuntuOne\/FAQ\/WhyIsItTakingSoLongForMyFilesToSync<\/a> <\/p>\n\n<p>This might have kicked in when you restarted using your laptop... I did restart and \"reinstall\" it all several times if it didn't work, but letting it do it's thing over night always somehow proved to be working. I read somewhere as well that it could take a long while before syncing actually started as it was checking structure\/syncing new folder structures first.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is supposed to get better with Natty, let's keep fingers crossed, I will apparently have to wait 40 days for my music library to sync! ;)<\/p>\n\n<p>Until then, what I added as programs are ubuntuone-indicator and magicicada. Both give more information than just the Disconnected\/Connected\/Synchronizing... messages ;)\n(I am a rather beginner user of Ubuntu, there will probably be much better answers coming your way!)\nGood luck!<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/19300\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/19300\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/19300\/answers","question_id":19300,"owner":{"user_id":2840,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Lolwhites","reputation":36,"email_hash":"a8032f4608854b701483d7063a3e6929"},"creation_date":1293651411,"last_edit_date":1293654041,"last_activity_date":1300426417,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":125,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Laptop not syncing with Ubuntu One","body":"<p>I have a desktop running Maverick, and a laptop running Lucid. Both are supposed to be linked to my Ubuntu One account.<\/p>\n\n<p>The desktop syncs fine, but when I started the laptop for the first time in a couple of months, it wouldn't sync any more. The Ubuntu One Preferences window either reports \"Synchronisation complete\" even though no recent files have been downloaded nor have any test files created in the relevant synced folder been uploaded, or it says \"Synchronisation in progress\", which does not appear to be happening as it stays like this for ages and the lights on my router suggest no traffic is going through.<\/p>\n\n<p>Have repeatedly tried disconnecting and reconnecting, and removing the device from the account then reattaching it, all to no avail.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["windows","mouse","menu"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":10588,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/10588\/comments","question_id":10586,"owner":{"user_id":667,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"dv3500ea","reputation":10210,"email_hash":"7f3d5b197677567789c00d95032e28a3"},"creation_date":1288543727,"last_activity_date":1288543727,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":235,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"right click menu on mouse release (windows behavior)","body":"<p>This is not the normal behaviour in Ubuntu. The normal behaviour is the same as you described for Windows.<\/p>\n\n<p>As far as I know, there is no way to change this right click behaviour.<\/p>\n\n<p>It might be a problem with running Ubuntu in vmware, although I can't think how this would make a difference. You could try dual booting or using a different virtualisation solution such as virtualbox.<\/p>\n\n<p>Was it like this when you first installed Ubuntu? Also, are you running Ubuntu or Kubuntu? (You tagged your question with KDE, which is only installed by default in Kubuntu).<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":10588,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/10586\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/10586\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/10586\/answers","question_id":10586,"owner":{"user_id":5095,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Berty","reputation":8,"email_hash":"d042f292dabd8223b6fa16ed274b9d4d"},"creation_date":1288542320,"last_edit_date":1288685433,"last_activity_date":1300425967,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":235,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"right click menu on mouse release (windows behavior)","body":"<p>I'm trying to change the behavior of the right click menu in ubuntu 10.10 because I use Windows 7 and Ubuntu.<\/p>\n\n<p>When you right click you need to hold the right click and select something.<\/p>\n\n<p>In Windows the is different\nright click (release)\nselect something with left click<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a way to change this in ubuntu?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm running the ubuntu in vmware 7<\/p>\n\n<p>Is that behavior normal?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","terminal","keyboard","gnome-terminal"],"answer_count":9,"answers":[{"answer_id":7282,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/7282\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":2647,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"enzotib","reputation":1185,"email_hash":"0886accd5a180ff4d084026ba81e74dc"},"creation_date":1287086995,"last_edit_date":1287087757,"last_activity_date":1287087757,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":550,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>It has to do, as you suspect, with \"vi\" mode.<\/p>\n\n<p>\"vi\" mode has separate insert and command modes, as you know. When in command mode, all text sent to the terminal is interpreted as a command.<\/p>\n\n<p>To convice yourself do this:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>copy somewhere a string containing \"isometext\"<\/li>\n<li>go to the terminal and press ESC to go to command mode<\/li>\n<li>paste<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>you should see only \"sometext\", because the initial \"i\" has been interpreted as the insert command.<\/p>\n\n<p>Solution: if in command mode, press \"i\" before inserting.\nIf not sure, press ESC and \"i\" before inserting.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30349,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30349\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":10966,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"David","reputation":230,"email_hash":"187c1ee2eca5cc8e47deb56f81986733"},"creation_date":1300122169,"last_activity_date":1300122169,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>Using the terminal copy and paste utilizes two different methods based on which way you perform the copy and paste.  If you use the highlight and paste-with-third-button, you are utilizing one of the buffers in X to do the work. If you use the menu or right-click to copy and paste, you are utilizing a <em>different<\/em> buffer.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thus, if you copy with a selection from the menu, then you must either paste using the menu or use the right-click menu. You can't select using <code>Edit &gt; Copy<\/code> and then use the third mouse button to paste.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is also the reason you can't copy by highlighting then going to another application and using <code>Edit &gt; Paste<\/code>.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30356,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30356\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":10616,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"EvilPhoenix","reputation":563,"email_hash":"6b92567199ee8a3e4a61c40a4406aff4"},"creation_date":1300124737,"last_activity_date":1300124737,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>For the record, I've run this test on various virtual instances of stock installs, ranging from 9.04 all the way through 11.04 Alpha 3.  I've been unable to replicate your issues.<\/p>\n\n<p>I believe that the issue may be some type of configuration somewhere conflicting with another.  As to the specific configuration, I do not know.  However...\n(quote from chat)<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>I'd blow away my .config stuff for gnome-terminal, but it's a pain to back up profiles.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>You might consider erasing your gnome-terminal configs to start, but after that i am not sure of how you'd fix this.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30867,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30867\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":12582,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"J. Snabb","reputation":11,"email_hash":"8b89d3f5413870b28a39767f0289c32b"},"creation_date":1300423368,"last_edit_date":1300425431,"last_activity_date":1300425431,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>This is a bug in gnome-terminal, the bug report is here with a patch:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/bugzilla.gnome.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=600876\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/bugzilla.gnome.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=600876<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Gnome has not fixed the problem though.<\/p>\n\n<p>Ubuntu has fixed it independently of Gnome. The detailed bug report is here:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/gnome-terminal\/+bug\/630383\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/gnome-terminal\/+bug\/630383<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>According to the bug report, the fixed Ubuntu package is gnome-terminal version 2.32.1-0ubuntu3. It is currently in the upload queue of maverick-proposed repository (with unapproved status). The upload queue is here:<\/p>\n\n<p>launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/maverick\/+queue<\/p>\n\n<p>(Sorry but I can not post more than 2 links it seems...)<\/p>\n\n<p>You could download the source package and build it yourself with debuild.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hopefully it will be soon pushed to normal update repositories.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":7197,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/7197\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":3843,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Daniel","reputation":16,"email_hash":"9eb6161479475b3189d9f0577fa35688"},"creation_date":1287072082,"last_activity_date":1287072082,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>I don't know why, but I ever use the <code>Menu<\/code>-Key(=on the right between <code>Super<\/code> and <code>Ctrl<\/code>) for copy&amp;paste.<br>\nI hope that's a help for you ;-)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":7198,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/7198\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":3301,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"nathwill","reputation":612,"email_hash":"ef9dc2280ebf56882db34449186f4453"},"creation_date":1287072088,"last_activity_date":1287072088,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>i've never had problems with this not working unless the cursor focus was not set to the terminal. make sure you've clicked into terminal before trying to paste.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":7210,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/7210\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":2937,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Pawe\u0142 Karpi\u0144ski","reputation":1697,"email_hash":"4a6ea872f65e0d6a9d7d0ca3136899f3"},"creation_date":1287074102,"last_edit_date":1287074469,"last_activity_date":1287074469,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>try <code>shift-ctrl-v<\/code> (same buttons, different order). You can also reassign your keyboard shortcuts under terminal Edit menu.\nDo not reassign it to Ctrl+C, because Ctrl+C is used for killing processes under terminal (well, sending TERM signal).<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":7239,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/7239\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":3216,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Tadas N.","reputation":89,"email_hash":"2cec18451be8c137b4ce46d0ddbb989d"},"creation_date":1287079397,"last_activity_date":1287079397,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>For me, the easiest way to paste is the middle mouse button click. However I still copy using the menu, because I don't need to copy often.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":7357,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/7357\/comments","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":1116,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"poolie","reputation":888,"email_hash":"5347c683b6963f418d1b16c65917bf3f"},"creation_date":1287105082,"last_activity_date":1287105082,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p>I would guess this is a problem with the terminal's inner widget not having focus, perhaps connected to the inner mouse bar.  If you click in the body of the terminal before pressing the keys does that fix it?<\/p>\n\n<p>(If this is true, it's a bug.)<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":6,"bounty_amount":100,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/7189\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/7189\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/7189\/answers","question_id":7189,"owner":{"user_id":463,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Matthew","reputation":911,"email_hash":"ae860f9442151273f880bb1e0d790a5a"},"creation_date":1287069484,"last_edit_date":1287103404,"last_activity_date":1300425431,"up_vote_count":12,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":550,"score":12,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why does pasting sometimes not work in gnome-terminal?","body":"<p><kbd>Ctrl<\/kbd> + <kbd>Shift<\/kbd> + <kbd>C<\/kbd> and <kbd>Ctrl<\/kbd> + <kbd>Shift<\/kbd> + <kbd>V<\/kbd> are supposed to replace the normal <kbd>Ctrl<\/kbd> + <kbd>C<\/kbd> and <kbd>Ctrl<\/kbd> + <kbd>V<\/kbd> in <code>gnome-terminal<\/code>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Sometimes they work, but usually they have no effect. What are some potential reasons for this? I'm not sure what other information to give.<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: It seems that manually selecting <code>Paste<\/code> from the <code>Edit<\/code> menu does not work either. <code>Right click &gt; Paste<\/code> works, but <code>Edit &gt; Paste<\/code> does not. Copying works, but pasting does not.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, I have vi-mode enabled (<code>set -o vi<\/code> in my <code>~\/.bashrc<\/code>). Could this have something to do with it?<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: Here is <a href=\"http:\/\/dl.dropbox.com\/u\/499772\/out.ogv\" rel=\"nofollow\">a video<\/a> demonstrating the problem. I used <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/screenkey\" rel=\"nofollow\">Screenkey<\/a> (in \"raw\" mode, to catch \"shift\") to show what keys I am pressing.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["packaging","mono"],"answer_count":7,"answers":[{"answer_id":5307,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/5307\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":448,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"trampster","reputation":626,"email_hash":"1c5255f8496fcade0244f12cb6ca6405"},"creation_date":1286448750,"last_activity_date":1286448750,"up_vote_count":6,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":6,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>The place to go for a mono PPA is <a href=\"http:\/\/badgerports.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/badgerports.org\/<\/a> unfortunately it could be months before it will have mono 2.8<\/p>\n\n<p>Novell do not believe it is their responsibility to provide mono packages for ubuntu so the effort has to come from the community.<\/p>\n\n<p>Jo Shields maintains both the official packages and the badgerports PPA. He said it could be months before mono 2.8 is available via his PPA.<\/p>\n\n<p>So your only option at this stage is to build from source. Which is not for the faint hearted.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":6692,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/6692\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":3762,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"SylvainC","reputation":61,"email_hash":"7b64b155b54894131257e727bd92dbdb"},"creation_date":1286948661,"last_activity_date":1286948661,"up_vote_count":6,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":6,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>Mono 2.8 is not available in a PPA. But someone made a <a href=\"http:\/\/www.integratedwebsystems.com\/2010\/10\/mono-2-8-install-script-for-ubuntu-fedora\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">script to automatically download, compile and install Mono 2.8 from source<\/a>. That makes it a little bit easier.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":29649,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29649\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":5149,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alaukik","reputation":2062,"email_hash":"0e9ce7064ba5c8d2813b490ba752c859"},"creation_date":1299675318,"last_edit_date":1300424261,"last_activity_date":1300424261,"up_vote_count":5,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":5,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>You could download this <a href=\"http:\/\/sourceforge.net\/projects\/mono-parallel\/files\/mono-2.10.1-parallel-environment.deb\/download\" rel=\"nofollow\">mono-parallel 2.10 deb package<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>After installing the deb file,paste this in the terminal<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>source mono-2.10-environment\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>After this your terminal will look like <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>[mono] \/var\/dev\/mono @<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/blog.fusonic.net\/2010\/10\/mono-2-8-parallel-environment-debianubuntu-package\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Link<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":12549,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/12549\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":5909,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"MCS","reputation":131,"email_hash":"82a0dd55627cc575f97d96988cb429e9"},"creation_date":1289418191,"last_activity_date":1289418191,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>According to <a href=\"http:\/\/au.ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?p=9992451\" rel=\"nofollow\">this thread<\/a>, you can just use a different prefix:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>--prefix=\/opt\/mono28\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"answer_id":11365,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/11365\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":1992,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Roland Taylor","reputation":6690,"email_hash":"d629b6ac45d58dbd918c0246b364748d"},"creation_date":1288885870,"last_activity_date":1288885870,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>If you're command line savy, you can compile it from source, using sudo make checkinstall instead of sudo make install, to get debs that you can downgrade later (you'll have a load of debs to downgrade though, <em>YOU HAVE BEEN WARNED<\/em>!!!!!)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":11364,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/11364\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":1963,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alex Butum","reputation":111,"email_hash":"f1447330d1577366fc35ae732a4a7cd3"},"creation_date":1288885726,"last_activity_date":1288885726,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>You can always get the latest Mono version by using the VMware image provided at: <a href=\"http:\/\/www.go-mono.com\/mono-downloads\/download.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mono Downloads Page<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":27484,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/27484\/comments","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":3241,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Tom Opgenorth","reputation":11,"email_hash":"955323838b1c111c5e9b1936dc44d9fd"},"creation_date":1298347071,"last_activity_date":1298347071,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>Looks like the script has just been updated to <a href=\"http:\/\/www.integratedwebsystems.com\/2011\/02\/mono-2-10-install-script-for-ubuntu-fedora\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">install Mono 2.10 on Fedora and Ubuntu<\/a>. The scripts themselves are on <a href=\"https:\/\/github.com\/nathanb\/iws-snippets\/tree\/master\/mono-install-scripts\" rel=\"nofollow\">GitHub<\/a>.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":29649,"favorite_count":8,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/5304\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/5304\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/5304\/answers","question_id":5304,"owner":{"user_id":449,"user_type":"moderator","display_name":"Oli","reputation":20546,"email_hash":"f0af40756420859b5b63cbceb6d30505"},"creation_date":1286443268,"last_edit_date":1299674945,"last_activity_date":1300424261,"up_vote_count":18,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":2271,"score":18,"community_owned":false,"title":"Upgrading to latest stable Mono","body":"<p>Mono 2.8 was recently released boasting a couple of large performance improvements. It's far too late for it to make it into Maverick and I'm fairly inpatient.<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't use Mono for anything mission-critical (<em>just<\/em> playing music and sorting photos) and if it breaks everything related to Mono, I can probably either live with it or fix it. I'm aware of how much I stand to lose if I mess things up.<\/p>\n\n<p>So with that acknowledged, does anybody here know how to build Mono in a way where it could be dropped in to replace the current Mono (2.6.7)? By this I mean ideally mirroring the packages that Ubuntu uses so that if the worse does happen, I can just downgrade the packages.<\/p>\n\n<p>Or is there a PPA that does all this for me?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","rhythmbox","ipod"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26578,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26578\/comments","question_id":26574,"owner":{"user_id":8515,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"djeikyb","reputation":1431,"email_hash":"6255793373939f9531d46761e40e55d7"},"creation_date":1297827513,"last_activity_date":1297827513,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":123,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"I can't use my iPod touch (32GB)","body":"<p>Apparently Apple borked linux support with iOS 4 and Nano 6+, and it's proven difficult to hack the music database to allow access to non-iTunes apps. I suspect your device is included in the bug.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/bugzilla.gnome.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=631006\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/bugzilla.gnome.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=631006<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/26574\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/26574\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/26574\/answers","question_id":26574,"owner":{"user_id":10064,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Silambarasan","reputation":11,"email_hash":"4658be34f9b12a3ac336a4b99a3e8c56"},"creation_date":1297824859,"last_edit_date":1297829680,"last_activity_date":1300422817,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":123,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"I can't use my iPod touch (32GB)","body":"<p>Hi All..<\/p>\n\n<p>I have connected my ipod touch 32gb in my ubuntu 10.10 os.It's connected on os and shows in desktop. but it's not showing as a device in Rhythmbox music player. and also I can't open directly like folder or drive or usb device. when I try to open it show this Error:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Could not display \"gphoto2:\/\/[usb:001,003]\/\".\n\nError: DBus error org.freedesktop.DBus.Error.ServiceUnknown: The name :1.207 was not provided by any .service files\n\nPlease select another viewer and try again.\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Any solution for this problem?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["installation"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30866\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30866\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30866\/answers","question_id":30866,"owner":{"user_id":12580,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Registered User","reputation":101,"email_hash":"9f39cdeea20d66e2d87b47a000c1049d"},"creation_date":1300422747,"last_activity_date":1300422747,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":11,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"how to create a mirror of minimum size to install Ubuntu","body":"<p>I need to create an http url at my laptop to have a Ubuntu installation begin within my laptop on a Xen environment.\nThis is how the final thing will look like \n<a href=\"http:\/\/bderzhavets.wordpress.com\/2008\/10\/28\/install-ubuntu-intrepid-server-pv-domu-at-xen-33-port-via-httpgetco-centos-52-dom0\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/bderzhavets.wordpress.com\/2008\/10\/28\/install-ubuntu-intrepid-server-pv-domu-at-xen-33-port-via-httpgetco-centos-52-dom0\/<\/a>\nthe host and client are both going to be my laptop,\nI Google d and came across apt-mirror and some other packages.\nI do not want to archive entire 15 GB Ubuntu repositories on my machine.\nIt is not possible to use a CD,ISO,loop mounted disk (reason mentioned below).\nI have tried using netboot image on local machine which failed because \nif you are attempting to create a virtual machine on a hardware which does not support VT\nvirt-manager installer necessarily needs a URL of this sort <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/archive.ubuntu.com\/ubuntu\/dists\/hardy\/main\/installer-i386\/current\/images\/netboot\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/archive.ubuntu.com\/ubuntu\/dists\/hardy\/main\/installer-i386\/current\/images\/netboot\/<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>any other option to create guest OS is simply grayed out.\nThe unfortunate part is my Ethernet connections do not work when I boot with Xen-4.0 and a pv-ops Dom0 kernel from Jeremy's tree.Which is where I have to do this work.So I have to create a URL structure which is similar to Ubuntu mirrors.So how can I do this in bare minimum so that at least the console boots and once the console comes I can do some work.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["email"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30863,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30863\/comments","question_id":30859,"owner":{"user_id":114,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"DoR","reputation":11168,"email_hash":"866e936ec416d60edf052821b1f38e78"},"creation_date":1300422453,"last_activity_date":1300422453,"up_vote_count":4,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":125,"score":4,"community_owned":false,"title":"Can anyone get an myname@ubuntu.com email address?","body":"<p>An @ubuntu.com email address is a benefit of <a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/Membership\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ubuntu Membership<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <h1>Benefits of Membership<\/h1>\n  \n  <p>Membership entitles you to the following\n  benefits:<\/p>\n  \n  <ul>\n  <li><p>Voting privileges to confirm Ubuntu Community Council nominations.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p><strong>An @ubuntu.com email alias that forwards to your real email address.\n  See UbuntuEmail for more details.<\/strong><\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>An ubuntu\/member\/your_nick cloak on freenode - See IRC\/Cloaks.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>The right to print business cards with the Ubuntu logo - The business\n  cards can be found at the\n  BusinessCards page, you will need to\n  take care of the printing yourself.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>Syndication on Planet Ubuntu of your Ubuntu blog or the Ubuntu category\n  posts in your blog, if you have one.\n  Follow the registration instructions\n  on PlanetUbuntu to add your blog!<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>An Ubuntu Member title at the Ubuntu Forums. See this post for more\n  information.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>A subscription to Linux Weekly News - see this page for instructions on how to apply.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>Ability to join the Official Ubuntu Members group on LinkedIn. See\n  Membership\/LinkedIn for more\n  information.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>Signing up for SixXS account with an Ubuntu email address and a link to\n  your Launchpad page will grant you an\n  \"Ubuntu Credit Bonus\" of 25 credit\n  points.<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>SFTP access to a Web-accessible directory on people.ubuntu.com<\/p><\/li>\n  <\/ul>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><sup>(Emphasis mine)<\/sup><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30865,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30865\/comments","question_id":30859,"owner":{"user_id":2585,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"NBK","reputation":11,"email_hash":"05945c6132d334e28bccaacbff22303d"},"creation_date":1300422711,"last_activity_date":1300422711,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":125,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Can anyone get an myname@ubuntu.com email address?","body":"<p>Yes you too can get myname@ubuntu.com email. For this you should become an active participant in Ubuntu development. Get started with <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/launchpad.net<\/a> . Report bugs you encounter in launchpad, try to help by making patches. The best method to get into it is through packaging. For this you need to become a member of MOTU. It takes time to learn the whole thing. Do check <a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/MOTU\/FAQ\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/wiki.ubuntu.com\/MOTU\/FAQ<\/a> to get started with MOTU.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30859\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30859\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30859\/answers","question_id":30859,"owner":{"user_id":8673,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Gonzalo","reputation":217,"email_hash":"288759e1f8f5f551d9c490f477dfbfd3"},"creation_date":1300420072,"last_activity_date":1300422711,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":125,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Can anyone get an myname@ubuntu.com email address?","body":"<p>If it is possible how can I get one?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["multiple-monitors","android"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30862,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30862\/comments","question_id":28608,"owner":{"user_id":12435,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"ali1234","reputation":106,"email_hash":"ac30c18585f7dd9fab0c37fe2af82f08"},"creation_date":1300421498,"last_activity_date":1300421498,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do you use an android tablet as a second display?","body":"<p>Get a VNC client for Android, start up a new VNC server session on your computer (don't just share the current display - use vnc4server not x11vnc), connect to it from the Android VNC client, and (the clever bit) share the PC keyboard and mouse between the two sessions using synergy.<\/p>\n\n<p>All necessary software to do this is available in the standard repos for the Ubuntu side, and there's a few free VNC clients available for Android in the market.<\/p>\n\n<p>You won't be able to drag windows across the displays using this method. For that I think you would need to use Xdmx to bond the two sessions. This is a lot harder and would probably cause you to lose 3D acceleration.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also be aware that synergy and vnc don't use encryption by default so you need to tunnel the connections if you are not on a trusted network.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/28608\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/28608\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/28608\/answers","question_id":28608,"owner":{"user_id":347,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Mark B","reputation":178,"email_hash":"ea0af3fb97e5e13e95968859739108a1"},"creation_date":1299002140,"last_edit_date":1299002295,"last_activity_date":1300421498,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do you use an android tablet as a second display?","body":"<p>I've noticed people using a product for Windows and Mac called <a href=\"http:\/\/www.shapeservices.com\/en\/products\/details.php?product=idisplay&amp;platform=none\" rel=\"nofollow\">iDisplay<\/a> which lets you use your Android or iPad as a secondary display. This seems like a great idea, and something that could be done on Ubuntu. Unfortunately, I've got no idea how to get started.<\/p>\n\n<p>How could you re-create this setup on Ubuntu?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["thunderbird","compression","mozilla"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":29735,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29735\/comments","question_id":29624,"owner":{"user_id":12057,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"mulllhausen","reputation":16,"email_hash":"16cc0c71b62a5f8fa2ae1b3aad18e663"},"creation_date":1299715630,"last_edit_date":1300421356,"last_activity_date":1300421356,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":63,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Thunderbird compact is taking forever","body":"<p>i found a much quicker solution! just right click on the each inbox and select properties. then under the 'general information' tab select 'rebuild index'. this took about 30 seconds and cleaned the whole thing up!<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ df -h\nFilesystem            Size Used Avail Use% Mounted on\n\/dev\/sda1             895G  120G  730G  15% \/\nnone                  4.0G  300K  4.0G   1% \/dev\nnone                  4.0G  1.5M  4.0G   1% \/dev\/shm\nnone                  4.0G  140K  4.0G   1% \/var\/run\nnone                  4.0G     0  4.0G   0% \/var\/lock\nnone                  4.0G     0  4.0G   0% \/lib\/init\/rw\n$ du -ch | grep [0-9]G\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\/Machines\/iBike\/Snapshots\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\/Machines\/iBike\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\/Machines\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\n4.3G    .\n4.3G    total\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>far out! from 667GB to less than 1GB in 30 seconds!! that was quick! :)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":29670,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29670\/comments","question_id":29624,"owner":{"user_id":8500,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"psusi","reputation":1989,"email_hash":"ce0150ff68789389639241c568dca423"},"creation_date":1299685855,"last_activity_date":1299685855,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":63,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Thunderbird compact is taking forever","body":"<p>Since you are using IMAP, the mail is stored on the server, and just cached locally.  You can shut down thunderbird and go into that directory and just delete the giant file.  You also might want to make sure that you have the checkbox to sync the folder locally for offline access cleared.<\/p>\n\n<p>Given that the directory is SO large, it looks like there is a bug that somehow caused it to fill with garbage.  Also moving messages to the trash has nothing to do with compacting a mailbox.  The trash is just another folder, so if you want to really delete the mail, you have to empty the trash.<\/p>\n\n<p>When using IAMP, compacting a folder just has thunderbird throw out the cached email.  For local mailboxes ( used with POP ), compacting rewrites the mailbox, removing any unused space.  Space normally becomes unused when you delete mail, and can be reused by new mail that fits within that space, but sometimes the spaces can be so small that they can't be reused, and if there are many of them, it adds up.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":29735,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29624\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29624\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29624\/answers","question_id":29624,"owner":{"user_id":12057,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"mulllhausen","reputation":16,"email_hash":"16cc0c71b62a5f8fa2ae1b3aad18e663"},"creation_date":1299655122,"last_edit_date":1299659925,"last_activity_date":1300421356,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":63,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Thunderbird compact is taking forever","body":"<p>The other day I came in to work and found that our development server - a Ubuntu box -  had a full hard disk. I did a bit of investigation and it seems like mozilla thunderbird is the major culprit. After burning off some backup files which did not need to be on the machine, the disk was left at 94%:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ df -h\nFilesystem            Size Used Avail Use% Mounted on\n\/dev\/sda1             895G  791G   59G  94% \/\nnone                  4.0G  300K  4.0G   1% \/dev\nnone                  4.0G  1.4M  4.0G   1% \/dev\/shm\nnone                  4.0G  140K  4.0G   1% \/var\/run\nnone                  4.0G     0  4.0G   0% \/var\/lock\nnone                  4.0G     0  4.0G   0% \/lib\/init\/rw\n$ cd\n$ du -ch | grep [0-9]G\n666G    .\/.thunderbird\/ccsmcruu.default\/ImapMail\/mail.adofms.com.au\n666G    .\/.thunderbird\/ccsmcruu.default\/ImapMail\n667G    .\/.thunderbird\/ccsmcruu.default\n667G    .\/.thunderbird\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\/Machines\/iBike\/Snapshots\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\/Machines\/iBike\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\/Machines\n2.2G    .\/.VirtualBox\n670G    .\n670G    total\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I did some reading and found that Mozilla Thunderbird does not compact files by default - i.e. all of the old emails that were sent to trash are still kept. One of the mailboxes used to get a lot of spam so I guess this accounts for the 667GB. I opened up Thunderbird to see how much space the inbox actually takes up and it turns out to be approximately 500MB - over 1000 times less than the stuff that has not been compacted over the years.<\/p>\n\n<p>So i right clicked on the inbox directory in the tree on the left of Thunderbird and selected 'compact'. I left it for about 12hours but even after that it still said 'compacting folder' on the status bar. I don't use Thunderbird on this PC - it belonged to a colleague who has left the company, however I do occasionally need to look through the inbox for references to the project I am working on, so deleting all traces of Thunderbird is not an option.<\/p>\n\n<p>My question is - is there any way I can monitor the progress of Thunderbird's compacting function? I would really like to know how long it is going to take.<\/p>\n\n<p>If there is any way I can speed up the compacting process i would also like to know.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","password","vmware","recovery"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30860,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30860\/comments","question_id":30858,"owner":{"user_id":7878,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"asoundmove","reputation":128,"email_hash":"6827312b7ffbe149b4aae9506de6da24"},"creation_date":1300421121,"last_activity_date":1300421121,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":16,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to reset lost user password, Ubuntu 10.10 guest on VMWare server","body":"<p>I don't know VMWare, but is there any way you can mount the guest's disk image in your host system?<\/p>\n\n<p>If yes, then you can edit the password file and set the password to the empty string.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30861,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30861\/comments","question_id":30858,"owner":{"user_id":6055,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Rog","reputation":158,"email_hash":"dd6c985d22e3bf6ea849e8d2e6750d76"},"creation_date":1300421155,"last_activity_date":1300421155,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":16,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to reset lost user password, Ubuntu 10.10 guest on VMWare server","body":"<p>I just figured it out, adding this line to the .vmx file made sure the bios and the subsequent grub menu both appeared.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>bios.bootDelay = \"15000\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This causes the bios to delay for 15 seconds so you can press keys.  It's kind of odd that it also affects the subsequent grub menu, but there you go.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30858\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30858\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30858\/answers","question_id":30858,"owner":{"user_id":6055,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Rog","reputation":158,"email_hash":"dd6c985d22e3bf6ea849e8d2e6750d76"},"creation_date":1300418348,"last_activity_date":1300421155,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":16,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to reset lost user password, Ubuntu 10.10 guest on VMWare server","body":"<p>I have a ubuntu 10.10 VMWare image that I set up a while back and have forgotten the login details.  Normally I'd boot into single user mode to fix this, but I'm having trouble doing this on the vmware image.  No grub screen comes up on boot, and attempts to hold down or press shift, space or escape during boot do nothing, the machine just boots up as before to the login prompt.<\/p>\n\n<p>Any ideas?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["hardware","java","arduino"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26491,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26491\/comments","question_id":26474,"owner":{"user_id":41,"user_type":"moderator","display_name":"Marco Ceppi","reputation":9125,"email_hash":"c127c8150f8052e4b89d66f42b99be56"},"creation_date":1297782657,"last_activity_date":1297782657,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":128,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Ubuntu 10.04 - unable to install Arduino","body":"<p>This was solved by copying <code>librxtxParallel.so<\/code> and <code>librxtxSerial.so<\/code> to <code>\/usr\/lib\/<\/code> and the details on this post: <a href=\"http:\/\/www.arduino.cc\/cgi-bin\/yabb2\/YaBB.pl?num=1238062036\/all\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/www.arduino.cc\/cgi-bin\/yabb2\/YaBB.pl?num=1238062036\/all<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/26474\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/26474\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/26474\/answers","question_id":26474,"creation_date":1297758833,"last_edit_date":1297782561,"last_activity_date":1300419217,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":128,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Ubuntu 10.04 - unable to install Arduino","body":"<p>Hello!\nAt the moment, I try to install Arduino on my Ubuntu 10.04 (32 Bit) computer.\nI downloaded the latest release at <a href=\"http:\/\/arduino.cc\/en\/Main\/Software\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/arduino.cc\/en\/Main\/Software<\/a>, cd'ed to the directory and unziped the package.\nWhen I try to run .\/arduino , I get following error:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Exception in thread \"main\" java.lang.ExceptionInInitializerError\n    at processing.app.Base.main(Base.java:112)\nCaused by: java.awt.HeadlessException\n    at sun.awt.HeadlessToolkit.getMenuShortcutKeyMask(HeadlessToolkit.java:231)\n    at processing.core.PApplet.&lt;clinit&gt;(Unknown Source)\n    ... 1 more\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Here is my java -version output:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>java version \"1.6.0_20\"\nOpenJDK Runtime Environment (IcedTea6 1.9.5) (6b20-1.9.5-0ubuntu1~10.04.1)\nOpenJDK Server VM (build 19.0-b09, mixed mode)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Any suggestions on this? I try to install arduino without the 'arduino' package.<\/p>\n\n<p>I tried to install it with apt-get (<code>sudo apt-get install arduino<\/code>).<\/p>\n\n<p>When I try to start arduino (using <code>arduino<\/code> command) will cause following error: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Exception in thread \"main\" java.lang.ExceptionInInitializerError\n    at processing.app.Preferences.load(Preferences.java:553)\n    at processing.app.Preferences.load(Preferences.java:549)\n    at processing.app.Preferences.init(Preferences.java:142)\n    at processing.app.Base.main(Base.java:188)\nCaused by: java.awt.HeadlessException\n    at sun.awt.HeadlessToolkit.getMenuShortcutKeyMask(HeadlessToolkit.java:231)\n    at processing.core.PApplet.&lt;clinit&gt;(PApplet.java:224)\n    ... 4 more\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>Update:<\/strong>\nI saw that I installed several versions of jre (sun and open). So I uninstalled the open jre.<\/p>\n\n<p>Now, when calling <code>arduino<\/code> I get a new error:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: no rxtxSerial in java.library.path thrown while loading gnu.io.RXTXCommDriver\nException in thread \"main\" java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: no rxtxSerial in java.library.path\n    at java.lang.ClassLoader.loadLibrary(ClassLoader.java:1734)\n    at java.lang.Runtime.loadLibrary0(Runtime.java:823)\n    at java.lang.System.loadLibrary(System.java:1028)\n    at gnu.io.CommPortIdentifier.&lt;clinit&gt;(CommPortIdentifier.java:123)\n    at processing.app.Editor.populateSerialMenu(Editor.java:965)\n    at processing.app.Editor.buildToolsMenu(Editor.java:717)\n    at processing.app.Editor.buildMenuBar(Editor.java:502)\n    at processing.app.Editor.&lt;init&gt;(Editor.java:194)\n    at processing.app.Base.handleOpen(Base.java:698)\n    at processing.app.Base.handleOpen(Base.java:663)\n    at processing.app.Base.handleNew(Base.java:578)\n    at processing.app.Base.&lt;init&gt;(Base.java:318)\n    at processing.app.Base.main(Base.java:207)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["10.10"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26320,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26320\/comments","question_id":25309,"owner":{"user_id":10212,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Ilias el Matani","reputation":397,"email_hash":"a61a51e1614d7ec1fcb35889943ebfc2"},"creation_date":1297689358,"last_activity_date":1297689358,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":72,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why doesn't Evolution send outgoing emails?","body":"<p>Please check your outgoing email settings!<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/25309\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/25309\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/25309\/answers","question_id":25309,"owner":{"user_id":8230,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Brian Buck","reputation":24,"email_hash":"f7129b34cbce0af095cb1c9c013c4af1"},"creation_date":1297189817,"last_edit_date":1300418625,"last_activity_date":1300418625,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":72,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why doesn't Evolution send outgoing emails?","body":"<p>I have recently installed Ubuntu 10.10 but have had a problem with the Evolution E-Mail system which accepts incoming E-Mails perfectly but will not sent any outgoing E-Mails.<\/p>\n\n<p>When I attempt to send an E-Mail message this just moves to the outbox and stays there.<\/p>\n\n<p>What could I have done wrong when setting up Evolution to have caused this?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","nvidia","thinkpad","hdmi"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30857\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30857\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30857\/answers","question_id":30857,"owner":{"user_id":12579,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"skorgon","reputation":1,"email_hash":"2034512f0705e01123501c045af15306"},"creation_date":1300417675,"last_activity_date":1300417675,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":14,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Thinkpad (T510) Display Port to HDMI TV","body":"<p>I'd like to connect my laptop via a displayport2HDMI adapter to a TV. I tried simply connecting everything, but unfortunately that didn't work. I also didn't see any option in nvidia-settings to configure any output via the displayport. Has anybody such a setup working, or the displayport at all?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm running Ubuntu 10.10.\nMy machine is a Lenovo Thinkpad T510 with a NVS 3100M graphics card.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["power-management","monitor","flicker"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26568,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26568\/comments","question_id":26541,"owner":{"user_id":8036,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"theprise","reputation":686,"email_hash":"dd7c9fae51d35c04ceb11d2a23e8e335"},"creation_date":1297822332,"last_activity_date":1297822332,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":36,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"what exactly is --no-daemon function in gnome-power-manager","body":"<p>The description of the <code>--no-daemon<\/code> option from <code>man gnome-power-manager<\/code> is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>--no-daemon<\/p>\n  \n  <blockquote>\n    <p>Do not detach gnome-power-manager into the background so that error messages will be displayed on console.<\/p>\n  <\/blockquote>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>From this it looks like the option is merely preventing gnome-power-manager from forking output into a background process (e.g. it will write to the console rather than a log file or similar), so running with this option shouldn't be a problem.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/26541\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/26541\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/26541\/answers","question_id":26541,"owner":{"user_id":4921,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Shark","reputation":56,"email_hash":"de0b492680bc22e8d4ee84c6d16a1636"},"creation_date":1297807731,"last_activity_date":1300415617,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":36,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"what exactly is --no-daemon function in gnome-power-manager","body":"<p>Hi<\/p>\n\n<p>I have problem with monitor flickering and <a href=\"https:\/\/bugs.launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/hal-info\/+bug\/415023\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> i found that possible solution is to run gnome-power-manager like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>gnome-power-manager --no-daemon\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>For some people this fixed the issues. I am asking what exactly is this --no-daemon function and can it negatively affect the system? Put it other way: can i always run gnome-power-manager with --no-daemon function?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thx for the answer<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","desktop","icons"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":29413,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29413\/comments","question_id":29405,"owner":{"user_id":1992,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Roland Taylor","reputation":6690,"email_hash":"d629b6ac45d58dbd918c0246b364748d"},"creation_date":1299514619,"last_activity_date":1299514619,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"\"clean up by name\" to the right, like on a mac","body":"<p>To my understanding this feature is not available in nautilus. A lot of discussion has gone on over the years about this but as yet, there has been no final decision.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30855,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30855\/comments","question_id":29405,"owner":{"user_id":8515,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"djeikyb","reputation":1431,"email_hash":"6255793373939f9531d46761e40e55d7"},"creation_date":1300412568,"last_activity_date":1300412568,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"\"clean up by name\" to the right, like on a mac","body":"<p>Hack the GNOME source and publish your patch. I'm half tempted to give it a go myself, but I'm wondering how many things would need to be recompiled just for one silly little thing.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":2,"closed_date":1300452834,"closed_reason":"exact duplicate","question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29405\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29405\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29405\/answers","question_id":29405,"owner":{"user_id":10698,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alvar","reputation":367,"email_hash":"f01cf0cc14447f738b549ab015b0e559"},"creation_date":1299512015,"last_edit_date":1299513770,"last_activity_date":1300412568,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"\"clean up by name\" to the right, like on a mac","body":"<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>Possible Duplicate:<\/strong><br>\n  <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/20728\/how-can-i-auto-align-desktop-icons-on-right-side\">How can I auto align desktop icons on right side?<\/a>  <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n\n\n<p>Hi, <\/p>\n\n<p>How do I \"clean up by name\" so that my icons are sorted from the right instead from the left as it is now.\nI have ubuntu 10.04 LTS.\nIf you right click in your desktop in ubuntu you get a list where you can \"clean up by name\".<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/yAFa5.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["ssh","printer","remote-access","tunnel"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":26435,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26435\/comments","question_id":26433,"owner":{"user_id":8851,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"luri","reputation":1202,"email_hash":"fae09ce7fae86755c3283a0b1e3c6a71"},"creation_date":1297731276,"last_edit_date":1297732470,"last_activity_date":1297732470,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":140,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to print over ssh?","body":"<p>Well... I'd say you can <code>ssh<\/code> your U machine and then issue the necessary <code>lp<\/code> or <code>lpr<\/code> commands. It's a bit of DIYish, but if ssh is already configured there's no need to open any ports.<\/p>\n\n<p>Maybe this would work, from command line:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>cat yourfile.pdf | ssh user@yourubuntumachine lpr\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>But maybe there's a quicker way... Let's see what others say.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":26481,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26481\/comments","question_id":26433,"owner":{"user_id":10879,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Ali Sheikh","reputation":1,"email_hash":"ebadedde2f9d54af6f90cf4e5877a7bf"},"creation_date":1297777408,"last_activity_date":1297777408,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":140,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to print over ssh?","body":"<p>If you have FreeNX server installed you can actually access the box in video mode with collaboration of ssh server.<\/p>\n\n<p>This will help you in a way that you can actually view the file :) and do the stuff.<\/p>\n\n<p>BUT THIS WILL MAKE THINGS a bit lengthier.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":26484,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26484\/comments","question_id":26433,"owner":{"user_id":3550,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"hhlp","reputation":4080,"email_hash":"096126abf903bd5c988f01846ee42c64"},"creation_date":1297780017,"last_activity_date":1297780017,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":140,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to print over ssh?","body":"<p>i found this how to i think it can be your solution<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntuforums.org\/showthread.php?t=774213\" rel=\"nofollow\">HOWTO Print remotely through ssh access<\/a> <\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/26433\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/26433\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/26433\/answers","question_id":26433,"owner":{"user_id":1467,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"mit","reputation":41,"email_hash":"c5a1457e089d8bfcf9190127689f3338"},"creation_date":1297727723,"last_edit_date":1297776436,"last_activity_date":1300412017,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":140,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to print over ssh?","body":"<p>I have the following configuration:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>P == U ---------------- W\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>P is a HP Laserjet, connected to U, which is an Ubuntu 10.04 desktop machine with a standard gnome setup from the live cd. I just selected the HP Laserjet in the gnome printer admin and it works, I can print locally.<\/p>\n\n<p>W is a remote windows machine, server 2003, and --- is an untrusted connection.<\/p>\n\n<p>I wonder if I can create an ssh tunnel between U and W, so W can print using U's printer service. Which ports will I need to forward and what kind of printer must I add then on the windows machine?<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>EDIT: I found out I can go to <a href=\"http:\/\/localhost:631\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/localhost:631\/<\/a> on the U machine and there is the CUPS browser gui. I will try and forward port 631 to W, and add a printer on W like <a href=\"http:\/\/localhost:631\/printers\/hp\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/localhost:631\/printers\/hp<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","pulseaudio","8.04"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":28041,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28041\/comments","question_id":28039,"owner":{"user_id":3940,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Takkat","reputation":4785,"email_hash":"633c6a15cf0dddfeb7da340f39d19bd8"},"creation_date":1298647497,"last_edit_date":1298934706,"last_activity_date":1298934706,"up_vote_count":14,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":289,"score":14,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to stream music over the network to multiple computers?","body":"<p>Yes, with <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pulseaudio.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">pulseaudio<\/a> this can easily be done. You will need to install and run <a href=\"http:\/\/packages.ubuntu.com\/maverick\/paprefs\" rel=\"nofollow\">paprefs<\/a> that makes your sound devices available over the network.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/glDuy.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/pdMMO.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>These settings allow both sound sources and sinks to be published over the network, ideally to another pulseaudio server. <\/p>\n\n<p>In case you have your server setup without desktop manager you will need to install a sound system first (see <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/q\/28176\/3940\">this question<\/a>). You can then edit <code>\/etc\/pulse\/default.pa<\/code> uncommenting these lines in the <em>Network access<\/em> section:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>load-module module-esound-protocol-tcp\nload-module module-native-protocol-tcp\nload-module module-zeroconf-publish\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you want to use RTP sender uncomment these lines the <em>RTP sender module<\/em> section:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>load-module module-null-sink sink_name=rtp format=s16be channels=2 rate=44100 description=\"RTP Multicast Sink\"\nload-module module-rtp-send source=rtp.monitor\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The pulseaudio server needs to be started as a daemon with <code>pulseaudio -D<\/code> in case it's not yet running. For optimizing sound qualitity settings in the <code>\/etc\/pulse\/daemon.conf<\/code> may be adapted to personal needs.<\/p>\n\n<p>An alternative method to stream audio in your network would be to setup an Icecast Server (see <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/q\/28496\/3940\">this question<\/a>).<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":28081,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/28081\/comments","question_id":28039,"owner":{"user_id":11342,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"loxs","reputation":185,"email_hash":"64363b718fbf9ad97a6af8c0b13b47e6"},"creation_date":1298666510,"last_edit_date":1298908710,"last_activity_date":1298908710,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":289,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to stream music over the network to multiple computers?","body":"<p>Your best option is called Music Player Daemon (mpd).<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/secure.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/wiki\/Music_Player_Daemon\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/secure.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/wiki\/Music_Player_Daemon<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>It is a client server application. You store your music on the server, then connect with your clients (lots of people can do it at once) and control the server.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is already in ubuntu, just apt-get install mpd<\/p>\n\n<p>And also some good documentation:\n<a href=\"https:\/\/wiki.archlinux.org\/index.php\/Mpd\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:\/\/wiki.archlinux.org\/index.php\/Mpd<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>MPD can stream music, so you can have lots of clients (or speakers if you so wish to call them) to play the music.<\/p>\n\n<p>But don't really expect any good quality. Streaming spoils sound badly (no matter if you use mpd or pulseaudio). It's a much better idea to connect real speakers to the server and use the laptops only to control it.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30853,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30853\/comments","question_id":28039,"owner":{"user_id":8515,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"djeikyb","reputation":1431,"email_hash":"6255793373939f9531d46761e40e55d7"},"creation_date":1300411231,"last_activity_date":1300411231,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":289,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to stream music over the network to multiple computers?","body":"<p>This guy comes up with a sweet looking VLC solution:\n<a href=\"http:\/\/biozshock.blogspot.com\/2010\/01\/audio-output-streaming-on-ubuntu-linux.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/biozshock.blogspot.com\/2010\/01\/audio-output-streaming-on-ubuntu-linux.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>I haven't tried it yet, but if\/when I do, I'll come back and edit my post with the details. Or someone else can turn this into a community wiki and flesh it out.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":3,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/28039\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/28039\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/28039\/answers","question_id":28039,"owner":{"user_id":10698,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alvar","reputation":367,"email_hash":"f01cf0cc14447f738b549ab015b0e559"},"creation_date":1298646124,"last_edit_date":1300411984,"last_activity_date":1300411984,"up_vote_count":16,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":289,"score":16,"community_owned":true,"title":"How to stream music over the network to multiple computers?","body":"<p>I have a server (Ubuntu 8.04 server) that I want to use as a music player. I want my laptop  Ubuntu 10.04 to be one speaker and my mac pro (mac os x 10.6) to be the other.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>I have found and setup the software according to <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/28039\/is-there-a-way-to-play-music-from-a-server-through-the-network-and-have-two-compu\/28041#28041\">this answer<\/a> <\/li>\n<li>All of the softwares in both computers and server is setup how should I continue?\n<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pulseaudio.org\/wiki\/FirstSteps\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/www.pulseaudio.org\/wiki\/FirstSteps<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Is there a tool for compressing sound files before sending them to the device? Example (my idea) sending the whole file, store in RAM memory and on a signal from the server play! then it would be lower data streams.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","software-recommendation","dvorak"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30850,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30850\/comments","question_id":30833,"owner":{"user_id":8515,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"djeikyb","reputation":1431,"email_hash":"6255793373939f9531d46761e40e55d7"},"creation_date":1300410196,"last_activity_date":1300410196,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Are there any good programs to learn Dvorak","body":"<p>You can use any existing typing program (say, <code>junior-typing<\/code> or <code>klavaro<\/code>) and run with it.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/klavaro.sourceforge.net\/en\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/klavaro.sourceforge.net\/en\/<\/a><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30852,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30852\/comments","question_id":30833,"owner":{"user_id":1951,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Mikel","reputation":1322,"email_hash":"85af3cb1fb8076180db3ab964c9699ed"},"creation_date":1300411094,"last_activity_date":1300411094,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Are there any good programs to learn Dvorak","body":"<p>I learned Dvorak using <a href=\"http:\/\/www.typefastertypingtutor.com\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">TypeFaster<\/a> for Windows.<\/p>\n\n<p>On Linux, <a href=\"http:\/\/ktouch.sourceforge.net\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">ktouch<\/a> is supposed to be very good, or there is <a href=\"http:\/\/www.gnu.org\/software\/gtypist\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">gtypist<\/a> if the others aren't suitable.<\/p>\n\n<p>KTouch comes with a configuration file called <code>sv.dvorak.keyboard<\/code>, so I think it will work for you.<\/p>\n\n<p>See also: <a href=\"http:\/\/superuser.com\/questions\/541\/is-there-any-software-to-help-me-learn-the-dvorak-layout\">http:\/\/superuser.com\/questions\/541\/is-there-any-software-to-help-me-learn-the-dvorak-layout<\/a><\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30833\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30833\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30833\/answers","question_id":30833,"owner":{"user_id":10698,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alvar","reputation":367,"email_hash":"f01cf0cc14447f738b549ab015b0e559"},"creation_date":1300400454,"last_edit_date":1300411387,"last_activity_date":1300411387,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Are there any good programs to learn Dvorak","body":"<p>Hi,<\/p>\n\n<p>How do I learn Dvorak typing in Ubuntu?\nI have Ubuntu 10.04 and I'm planning to learn one of the <a href=\"http:\/\/tlundqvist.org\/sv_dvorak\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Swedish dvorak versions.<\/a>\nIt's included in ubuntu 10.04.\nI used to play a game called <a href=\"http:\/\/www.mousebreaker.com\/games\/grandprixtycoon\/playgame\" rel=\"nofollow\">Grand Prix Tycoon<\/a> on mousebreaker.com . I know it's a silly game but if you use a game of some sort you can get better so much faster.<\/p>\n\n<p>A) Is there a program that I can use to learn Dvorak?<\/p>\n\n<p>B) Is there a game of some sort to learn Dvorak?<\/p>\n\n<p>C) Is the Swedish version I linked to supported?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["hard-drive","format"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30854,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30854\/comments","question_id":21688,"owner":{"user_id":12575,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"vasista","reputation":1,"email_hash":"74e2204e367f8b5c684eecca011746d0"},"creation_date":1300411284,"last_activity_date":1300411284,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":145,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Maxtor OneTouch Hardisk Not Recognised","body":"<p>i installed ubuntu just two days back to my hp laptop. the problem is it cannot recognise the internet i.e., wifi and wired internet. Same i can connect through windows. What to do????? kindly help<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/21688\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/21688\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/21688\/answers","question_id":21688,"owner":{"user_id":8960,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"LinDoc","reputation":1,"email_hash":"bc7e0eef5d2f0de446a2ff4213c38c1c"},"creation_date":1295109343,"last_activity_date":1300411284,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":145,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Maxtor OneTouch Hardisk Not Recognised","body":"<p>I have a Maxtor OneTouch External Harddisk 160gb that i purchased recently. At first my Ubuntu 10.10 could not mount it. I opened disk utility which recognized it but with no filesystem. I proceeded to try formatting it but this error popped up <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Blockquote\n  Error creating partition table: helper exited with exit code 1: Error calling fsync(2)    on \/dev\/sdb: Input\/output error \n  Blockquote<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I resorted to Gparted. Things turned worse; it wasn't even listed in the list of devices. Does anyone have a solution to this problem? Any help is appreciated.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["benchmarks"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30849\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30849\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30849\/answers","question_id":30849,"owner":{"user_id":2405,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Chris Wilson","reputation":2207,"email_hash":"ba6aba5790e7412dd4f6041c42a24c7e"},"creation_date":1300410012,"last_activity_date":1300410012,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":6,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I test the footprint of applications?","body":"<p>I am about to start my masters project and I will need to gather some data, for the requirements stage, about the performance footprint applicants have on my system. The main things I am look for are load times, memory and CPU usage, shutdown times. Anything else I can get would be a bonus, and the more the merrier. I know I can use the system monitor to get some of this stuff, but I need precise data as I am going to be doing some before and after tests during my project. Is there anything in the Software Centre that can do this, and if not, is there anything out there (preferably open source) that will suffice?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["installation","usb-drive","freeze"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30847,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30847\/comments","question_id":30845,"owner":{"user_id":8515,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"djeikyb","reputation":1431,"email_hash":"6255793373939f9531d46761e40e55d7"},"creation_date":1300409132,"last_activity_date":1300409132,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":19,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"If Ubuntu freezes when running off a USB drive, will it freeze after full installation?","body":"<p>Is it possible that your freezes are related to running off the USB drive? <strong>Yes<\/strong>. Is it likely? <strong>*shrug*<\/strong>. You'd have to track down what is causing the freeze. It could be freezing because:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>the usb disk is bottlenecking your throughput.<\/li>\n<li>the usb disk is dying.<\/li>\n<li>network manager misbehaved, causing a kernel panic.<\/li>\n<li>etc..<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30845\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30845\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30845\/answers","question_id":30845,"owner":{"user_id":12572,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"fearoffours","reputation":106,"email_hash":"11a2f9750e4db4104619d2e12c0a5b7e"},"creation_date":1300407163,"last_activity_date":1300409132,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":19,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"If Ubuntu freezes when running off a USB drive, will it freeze after full installation?","body":"<p>I'm planning to install Ubuntu on an aging Compaq Presario V5000.<\/p>\n\n<p>I've established that the Unity desktop is not suited to this laptop, and am now using the standard (Gnome?) desktop.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm grappling with ndiswrapper and my wireless chipset.<\/p>\n\n<p>But I'm still running it off a USB drive before I take the plunge and install properly to my internal HD. Part of my reticence in completing the installation is I'm experience freezes after about 10-20 minutes usage. Is this likely to be in any way related to running it off the USB drive?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","resume","trackpad","sleep"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30810\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30810\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30810\/answers","question_id":30810,"owner":{"user_id":12551,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Slickt10","reputation":1,"email_hash":"d2cca5497a5b80e4ff56dd9d086e06ed"},"creation_date":1300384911,"last_edit_date":1300408852,"last_activity_date":1300408852,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":5,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Touchpad frozen after resume on a Gateway MX6650\/MA2A","body":"<p>After the computer is resumed from sleep, the trackpad no longer works. I've tried different settings using the s2ram command, just to see if it would change anything. But that doesn't seem to be the problem. Where else do I check?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["software-center","synaptic","segmentation-fault"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":17959,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/17959\/comments","question_id":17953,"owner":{"user_id":1697,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Frxstrem","reputation":490,"email_hash":"ef45f65b4ef028a5aaaeae69cdcd17db"},"creation_date":1292620314,"last_activity_date":1292620314,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":128,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Synaptic and Software Centre Segmentation fault","body":"<p>The definition of a <strong>segmentation fault<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n<p><em>A segmentation fault (often shortened to segfault) or bus error occurs when the hardware notifies a Unix-like operating system about a memory access violation.<\/em> (Source: <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Segmentation_fault\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<p>This basically means that there's an error in the program's code, where the program tries to access a part of the computer's memory that it does not have access to. As this is a very generic error that can occur for very many reasons, it is hard for me to say the exact reason why this happens, and give you a solution.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/17953\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/17953\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/17953\/answers","question_id":17953,"owner":{"user_id":7578,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"islam","reputation":11,"email_hash":"99bbf4d346ff50b8c4a0bf979180dc76"},"creation_date":1292618995,"last_edit_date":1292620094,"last_activity_date":1300408417,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":128,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Synaptic and Software Centre Segmentation fault","body":"<p>Synaptic windows disappear after a few seconds when opened. This happens also for the Software Center. On running from the terminal it gives me this phrase \"Segmentation fault\" how can I fix that?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","boot","live-cd"],"answer_count":5,"answers":[{"answer_id":29292,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29292\/comments","question_id":29280,"owner":{"user_id":11921,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Martin Eve","reputation":41,"email_hash":"3645eb2857da226a58ca23a582a0b859"},"creation_date":1299435785,"last_edit_date":1299469256,"last_activity_date":1299469256,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":241,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why is my Ubuntu 10.10 CD not booting?","body":"<p>As Allan suggests, some more info would be helpful, but I'll post some suggestions here, as I can't \"comment\" at the moment.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Have you definitely set the CD drive higher than the HDD in the BIOS boot settings?<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Can you boot a different CD?<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>If the CD is booting, but crashing with some form of kernel panic, you can try the various options in the CD menu (like <code>ACPI=off<\/code>, which is needed on some models of laptop, such as the Toshiba Satellite)<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n"},{"answer_id":29817,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29817\/comments","question_id":29280,"owner":{"user_id":3226,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"jet","reputation":958,"email_hash":"2f26e4f64eb5657f7d260bda02c7ba45"},"creation_date":1299778527,"last_activity_date":1299778527,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":241,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why is my Ubuntu 10.10 CD not booting?","body":"<p>one of the possible problem is if the file is not downloaded properly. The easy check is to calculate sha or md5 checksum and compare it with the original placed on the site you downloaded from.<\/p>\n\n<p>the other problem can be if you burnt the ISO as a file not as an image<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30512,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30512\/comments","question_id":29280,"owner":{"user_id":11616,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"bitwelder","reputation":61,"email_hash":"f333aea9ed658ae25f730d9512af80d0"},"creation_date":1300211771,"last_edit_date":1300295416,"last_activity_date":1300295416,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":241,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why is my Ubuntu 10.10 CD not booting?","body":"<p>If you boot your computer with... anything bootable, and then you insert the 10.10 CD you burned, is it recognized and mounted (i.e. is it readable)? <\/p>\n\n<p>If not, and you have an Ubuntu distro running, you can test with <code>wodim -atip<\/code> and <code>wodim -toc<\/code> (they are in Ubuntu package wodim, the old cdrecord) whether the CD media is recognized as writable and if there are tracks.<\/p>\n\n<p>If it is recognized, there is another package that can help you, <code>cdck<\/code>: it can tell you what's the content of that CD and if it's bootable. E.g. with a Knoppix CD that I burned myself I get:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Try to find out what sort of CD this is...\nCD-ROM with iso9660 fs\niso9660: 688 MB size, label 'KNOPPIX'\nCreating software: 'KNOPPIX'\nbootable CD  \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This won't probably answer to your question 'why', but it should help you track where is the cause of the problem.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":29818,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29818\/comments","question_id":29280,"owner":{"user_id":5118,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"CentaurusA","reputation":222,"email_hash":"e7ce7eab5f0d0ec26abe69285b77b860"},"creation_date":1299779774,"last_activity_date":1299779774,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":241,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why is my Ubuntu 10.10 CD not booting?","body":"<p>At what speed did you burn the CD?  I have had problems with bootable CD's not booting, but when I burn the same ISO image to a CD at the lowest speed that the drive offers, the new CD will boot.  Since your CD doesn't boot in two machines, but other CD's do, you really have to suspect the CD that you have burnt.  Making another will take a few minutes, but if it solves the problem... you have a coaster, and a new bootable CD! <\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":29875,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29875\/comments","question_id":29280,"owner":{"user_id":10998,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"nelaar","reputation":71,"email_hash":"4784644a7b852ad6458f0e6e93abb77c"},"creation_date":1299831362,"last_activity_date":1299831362,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":241,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why is my Ubuntu 10.10 CD not booting?","body":"<p>Simple check, have you enabled boot from CD\/DVD rom in your bios settings. <\/p>\n\n<p>As your computer boots up \nyou need to press\nDel\nor \nF1<\/p>\n\n<p>Navigate to boot options and select boot from DVD CD rom<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":2,"bounty_amount":50,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29280\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29280\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29280\/answers","question_id":29280,"owner":{"user_id":5304,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Tom Brito","reputation":176,"email_hash":"936b33523e4b1ad063fe4124dc0e2335"},"creation_date":1299430091,"last_edit_date":1300408008,"last_activity_date":1300408008,"up_vote_count":7,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":241,"score":7,"community_owned":false,"title":"Why is my Ubuntu 10.10 CD not booting?","body":"<p>I have downloaded Ubuntu 10.10 and burned the ISO but it will not boot.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>I discarded problems with the ISO, as I've downloaded from the official website with no errors, and burned it with no errors.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>I discarded problems with the burning, as looks like it was recorded with no errors here and later in another computer.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>I discarded problems with my DVD reader as other cds boots fine.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>I'm currently using Ubuntu 9.10, I know I can upgrade via internet, but I have this same problem with my Windows XP cd, so I really would like to discover what's going on here.. My Ubuntu 9.10 cd boots just right, but the new one not.<\/p>\n\n<p>What else can be? Or what more precise tests can I make to discover where's the problem? <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>--More info<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>What happens when I try to boot with the Ubuntu 10.10 cd is that it behaves like there's no bootable cd in the drive. It just don't find the boot on the cd, and start the HD system.<\/p>\n\n<p>My notebook is an Amazon PC Intel Celeron 1.5 with 2Gb memory, a DVD-RW driver, HD samsung with 260GB.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>--update<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>If you put the media agains the light and see the other side, does that means that it's a bad quality dvd media? (it's a Philips)<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["nvidia","tv"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30844,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30844\/comments","question_id":30828,"owner":{"user_id":8500,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"psusi","reputation":1989,"email_hash":"ce0150ff68789389639241c568dca423"},"creation_date":1300405901,"last_activity_date":1300405901,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":15,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Over-scan Issues when using HDTV through VGA","body":"<p>Televisions do not have a native resolution of 768 lines.  Standard def is 540, and HD is either 720 or 1080.  It probably expects 1280 x 768 from a VGA connector and scales it.  When you give it the wider resolution, it scales wider than the TV.  Stick to the resolution that works.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30828\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30828\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30828\/answers","question_id":30828,"owner":{"user_id":593,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"RPG Master","reputation":140,"email_hash":"a747f745287ea3984eadc209209e1c73"},"creation_date":1300398951,"last_edit_date":1300401230,"last_activity_date":1300405901,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":15,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Over-scan Issues when using HDTV through VGA","body":"<p>Right now all we can do is set the TV to 1280x768 instead of its native resolution of 1360x768. Setting it to its native resolution gives you a screen with a large portion of the left side of the screen cut off. We've tried everything with the TV so now we're turning to the innards of Ubuntu in hopes of fixing this. The computer is using an NVIDIA GeForce GT240. This is its current xorg.conf: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code># nvidia-settings: X configuration file generated by nvidia-settings\n# nvidia-settings:  version 1.0  (buildd@palmer)  Fri Apr  9 10:35:18 UTC 2010\n\n\nSection \"ServerLayout\"\n    Identifier     \"Layout0\"\n    Screen      0  \"Screen0\" 0 0\n    InputDevice    \"Keyboard0\" \"CoreKeyboard\"\n    InputDevice    \"Mouse0\" \"CorePointer\"\n    Option         \"Xinerama\" \"0\"\nEndSection\n\nSection \"Files\"\nEndSection\n\nSection \"InputDevice\"\n\n    # generated from default\n    Identifier     \"Mouse0\"\n    Driver         \"mouse\"\n    Option         \"Protocol\" \"auto\"\n    Option         \"Device\" \"\/dev\/psaux\"\n    Option         \"Emulate3Buttons\" \"no\"\n    Option         \"ZAxisMapping\" \"4 5\"\nEndSection\n\nSection \"InputDevice\"\n\n    # generated from default\n    Identifier     \"Keyboard0\"\n    Driver         \"kbd\"\nEndSection\n\nSection \"Monitor\"\n\n    # HorizSync source: builtin, VertRefresh source: builtin\n   # HorizSync       28.0 - 55.0\n    # VertRefresh     43.0 - 72.0\n    Identifier     \"Monitor0\"\n    VendorName     \"Unknown\"\n    ModelName      \"CRT-0\"\n    HorizSync       28.0 - 55.0\n    VertRefresh     43.0 - 72.0\n    Option         \"DPMS\"\nEndSection\n\nSection \"Device\"\n    Identifier     \"Device0\"\n    Driver         \"nvidia\"\n    VendorName     \"NVIDIA Corporation\"\n    BoardName      \"GeForce 6600\"\nEndSection\n\nSection \"Screen\"\n\n# Removed Option \"metamodes\" \"1360x768 +0+0; 800x600 +0+0\"\n    Identifier     \"Screen0\"\n    Device         \"Device0\"\n    Monitor        \"Monitor0\"\n    DefaultDepth    24\n    Option         \"TwinView\" \"0\"\n    Option         \"TwinViewXineramaInfoOrder\" \"CRT-0\"\n    Option         \"metamodes\" \"1360x768 +0+0\"\n    SubSection     \"Display\"\n        Depth       24\n    EndSubSection\nEndSection\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"},{"tags":["compiz"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30843,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30843\/comments","question_id":30841,"owner":{"user_id":5297,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Reuben Swartz","reputation":337,"email_hash":"1d88ea49e14be3dea7db64fd2bc42d87"},"creation_date":1300405591,"last_activity_date":1300405591,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":24,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I switch windows only in one workspace?","body":"<p>The scale plugin might help (Press Super+W)<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30841\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30841\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30841\/answers","question_id":30841,"owner":{"user_id":10477,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Kejia\u67ef\u5609","reputation":6,"email_hash":"2487e33ee1d3dd72f1464642d8b454c5"},"creation_date":1300404478,"last_edit_date":1300404996,"last_activity_date":1300405591,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":24,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How can I switch windows only in one workspace?","body":"<p>I enable compiz and switch windows by tab, but I don't want to iterate all windows in all workspaces. How can I switch windows in one workspace?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["partitioning","desktop","icons","customization","gconf"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30842,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30842\/comments","question_id":30830,"owner":{"user_id":10409,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"jwillar","reputation":1,"email_hash":"80e18f2e4c391b3ad28ccd74dd927ca9"},"creation_date":1300405420,"last_activity_date":1300405420,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I hide a specific volume from the desktop, but keep all others?","body":"<p>To hide a partition, mount the partitions in your '\/mnt' folder.  I use the fstab file to accomplish this automaticaly on boot up.<\/p>\n\n<p>jwillar <\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30830\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30830\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30830\/answers","question_id":30830,"owner":{"user_id":12569,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Hector","reputation":1,"email_hash":"5da3489d1a8a9d9a62f269757e7f7a8d"},"creation_date":1300399577,"last_activity_date":1300405420,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":28,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I hide a specific volume from the desktop, but keep all others?","body":"<p>I find the icons that show up when I plug a flash drive useful, as much as SD cards and devices. However, the icon to my Windows partition is useless. How can I hide it?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["shutdown","upstart"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30385,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30385\/comments","question_id":30383,"owner":{"user_id":11775,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"geekosaur","reputation":614,"email_hash":"7c081000f3681dc93be5ec6d1587936e"},"creation_date":1300138625,"last_activity_date":1300138625,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":65,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Best way to make a shutdown hook?","body":"<p><code>starting<\/code> and <code>runlevel<\/code> are separate events, so you can't meaningfully say <code>starting runlevel N<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The <code>runlevel N<\/code> event is emitted at the start of entering the runlevel.  If you <code>start on runlevel N<\/code> then your task runs on entry.  The way to run when entry to the runlevel is completed is <code>run on started rc RUNLEVEL=N<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>As I understand it, you need a <code>start on runlevel [056]<\/code> to do what you want; it should in theory run before anything else is stopped.  For finer control you might use <code>start on stopping apache or stopping mysql or ...<\/code> so that your task runs before any of them are allowed to be shut down.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30705,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30705\/comments","question_id":30383,"owner":{"user_id":12234,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Binarus","reputation":74,"email_hash":"d417f7d05750e27aed93bb07a2e742a4"},"creation_date":1300316466,"last_activity_date":1300316466,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":65,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Best way to make a shutdown hook?","body":"<p>Geekosaur, thank you very much for your help.<\/p>\n\n<p>In the meantime, I have tried the \"start on runlevel [016]\" method, but it did not work, and I think I understand why:<\/p>\n\n<p>The job has been started indeed, but the shutdown process has not been blocked until the job's task was finished. I am quite sure now that the events \"starting\" and \"stopping\" are the only events which can be used in a job definition to block other jobs, and I think that this is what Upstart's manuals try to tell us. Therefore, using the runlevel event will never lead to blocking other jobs or the shutdown process; thus, it is useless for my purpose.<\/p>\n\n<p>Instead, I seem to have two possibilites:<\/p>\n\n<p>1) Following one of your propositions, find out all jobs which the repective applications need, and include all of them in the start event for the script like that:<\/p>\n\n<p>start on stopping job1 or stopping job2 or ...<\/p>\n\n<p>This is so much work that I am seriously thinking of dumping the job list and running it through sed to automatically produce a start stanza for my job which includes <em>all<\/em> jobs which normally are running on the system.<\/p>\n\n<p>The advantage would be that the respective applications would be shut down even when somebody stops one of the prerequisites manually (as opposed to stopping them by a runlevel change \/ shutdown \/ reboot).<\/p>\n\n<p>2) Find the one job which will be stopped at first when rebooting \/ shutting down the system (let's call this job \"FirstJob\") and use that job in a stanza like:<\/p>\n\n<p>start on stopping FirstJob<\/p>\n\n<p>The main disadvantages would be that I don't know if such a job exists at all and if that job really depends on <em>all<\/em> other jobs which the repective application actually depends on (\"depends on other job\" in this case means \"will be stopped completely before other job begins to stop\").<\/p>\n\n<p>I am not sure which of the two possibilities is the better one...<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":30385,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30383\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30383\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30383\/answers","question_id":30383,"owner":{"user_id":12234,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Binarus","reputation":74,"email_hash":"d417f7d05750e27aed93bb07a2e742a4"},"creation_date":1300135882,"last_edit_date":1300405192,"last_activity_date":1300405192,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":65,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Best way to make a shutdown hook?","body":"<p>Since Ubuntu relies on upstart for some time now, I would like to use an upstart job to gracefully shutdown certain applications on system shutdown or reboot. It is essential that the system's shutdown or reboot is stalled until these applications are shut down.<\/p>\n\n<p>The applications will be started manually on occasion, and on system shutdown should automatically be ended by a script (which I already have). Since the applications can't be ended reliably without (nearly all) other services running, ending the applications has to be done before the rest of the shutdown begins.<\/p>\n\n<p>I think I can solve this by an upstart job which will be triggered on shutdown, but I am unsure which events I should use in which manner. So far, I have read the following (partly contradicting) statements:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>There is no general shutdown event in upstart<\/li>\n<li>Use a stanza like \"start on starting shutdown\" in the job definition<\/li>\n<li>Use a stanza like \"start on runlevel [06S]\" in the job definition<\/li>\n<li>Use a stanza like \"start on starting runlevel [06S]\" in the job definition<\/li>\n<li>Use a stanza like \"start on stopping runlevel [!06S]\" in the job definition<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>From these recommendations, the following questions arise:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Is there or is there not a general shutdown event in Ubuntu's upstart?<\/li>\n<li>What is the recommended way to implement a \"shutdown hook\"?<\/li>\n<li>When are the events runlevel [x] triggered; is this when having entered the runlevel or when entering the runlevel?<\/li>\n<li>Can we use something like \"start on starting runlevel [x]\" or \"start on stopping runlevel [x]\"?<\/li>\n<li>What would be the best solution for my problem?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Thank you very much<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["upstart","events"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30692,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30692\/comments","question_id":30691,"owner":{"user_id":11775,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"geekosaur","reputation":614,"email_hash":"7c081000f3681dc93be5ec6d1587936e"},"creation_date":1300312623,"last_activity_date":1300312623,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":20,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Sense of \"stop on...\" stanza when job is a task","body":"<p>That would abort the task; if you tell the system to reboot because of a failure of some kind while bringing the system up, you generally don't want it to finish trying to boot first, or (worse) try to bring the system up and shut it down at the same time.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":30692,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30691\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30691\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30691\/answers","question_id":30691,"owner":{"user_id":12234,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Binarus","reputation":74,"email_hash":"d417f7d05750e27aed93bb07a2e742a4"},"creation_date":1300312494,"last_edit_date":1300405159,"last_activity_date":1300405159,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":20,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Sense of \"stop on...\" stanza when job is a task","body":"<p>Hi,<\/p>\n\n<p>an upstart question (I think I have read all relevant man pages but could not find the answer there): What is the sense of using a \"stop on ...\" stanza in the definition of a job which is a task?<\/p>\n\n<p>The manuals tell us that such a job, after being started, just waits until its script (or exec stanza) is executed completely, and then stops automatically. Given that, what is the point in using \"stop on ...\" stanzas in such job definitions?<\/p>\n\n<p>For example, this is the job definition for Upstart's (very important) rc job in Natty 11.04 (leaving out comments and empty lines):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>start on runlevel [0123456]\nstop on runlevel [!$RUNLEVEL]\nexport RUNLEVEL\nexport PREVLEVEL\nconsole output\nenv INIT_VERBOSE\ntask\nexec \/etc\/init.d\/rc $RUNLEVEL\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>IMHO, the job, after being started by a runlevel event, will be stopped automatically as soon as <code>\/etc\/init.d\/rc $RUNLEVEL<\/code> has finished.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you very much for any explanation!<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["evolution","upstart","system"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30699,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30699\/comments","question_id":30697,"owner":{"user_id":11775,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"geekosaur","reputation":614,"email_hash":"7c081000f3681dc93be5ec6d1587936e"},"creation_date":1300314921,"last_activity_date":1300314921,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"How does rc job work \/ order of (contradicting) \"start on ...\" and \"stop on ...\" stanzas","body":"<p>Did you see my answer to <a href=\"http:\/\/askubuntu.com\/questions\/30691\/upstart-sense-of-stop-on-stanza-when-job-is-a-task\">Upstart: sense of &quot;stop on...&quot; stanza when job is a task<\/a>?  Same answer applies to the first part of your question, it's used to abort the runlevel startup if the user switches to another runlevel before it's finished.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have no idea about the second part, though.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30697\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30697\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30697\/answers","question_id":30697,"owner":{"user_id":12234,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Binarus","reputation":74,"email_hash":"d417f7d05750e27aed93bb07a2e742a4"},"creation_date":1300314536,"last_edit_date":1300405128,"last_activity_date":1300405128,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":33,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How does rc job work \/ order of (contradicting) \"start on ...\" and \"stop on ...\" stanzas","body":"<p>Hi,<\/p>\n\n<p>I just can't understand how Upstart's rc job definition in Natty 11.04 works. To illustrate the problem, here is the definition (empty lines and comments are left out):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>start on runlevel [0123456]\nstop on runlevel [!$RUNLEVEL]\nexport RUNLEVEL\nexport PREVLEVEL\nconsole output\nenv INIT_VERBOSE\ntask\nexec \/etc\/init.d\/rc $RUNLEVEL\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Let's suppose we currently are in runlevel 2 and the rc job is stopped (that is exactly the situation after booting my box and logging in via SSH). Now, let's assume that the system switches to runlevel 3, for example due to a command like \"telinit 3\" given by root. What will happen to the rc job?<\/p>\n\n<p>Obviously, the rc job will be started since it is currently stopped and the event runlevel 3 is matching the start events. But from now on, things are unclear to me: According to the manual $RUNLEVEL evaluates to the new runlevel when the job is started (that means 3 in our example).<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the next stanza \"stop on runlevel [!$RUNLEVEL]\" translates to \"stop on runlevel [!3]\"; that means we have a first stanza which will trigger the job, but the second stanza will never stop the job and seems to be useless.<\/p>\n\n<p>Since I know that the Ubuntu \/ Upstart people won't do useless things, I must be heavily misunderstanding something. I would be grateful for any explanation.<\/p>\n\n<p>While trying to understand this, an additional question came to my mind. If I had contradicting start and stop triggers, for example<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>start on foo\nstop on foo\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>what would happen? I swear I never will do that, but I am nevertheless very interested in how Upstart handles that on the theoretical level.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you very much!<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Editing the question as a reaction on geekosaur's first answer:<\/p>\n\n<p>I can see the parallelism, but it is not that easy (at least, not to me).<\/p>\n\n<p>Let's assume the job aurrently is still running, and a new runlevel event comes in (of course, the new runlevel is different from the current one). Then, the following should happen:<\/p>\n\n<p>1) The job is single instance. That means that \"start on ...\" won't be triggered since the job is currently running; $RUNLEVEL is not touched.<\/p>\n\n<p>2) \"stop on ...\" will be triggered since the <em>new<\/em> runlevel is different from $RUNLEVEL, so the job will be aborted.<\/p>\n\n<p>3) Now, the job is stopped and waiting. I can't see how it is restarted with the <em>new<\/em> runlevel. AFAIK, initctl emits events only once, so \"start on ...\" won't be triggered and the new runlevel won't be entered.<\/p>\n\n<p>I know that I still misunderstanding something, and I am grateful for explanations.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you very much!<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","firefox-beta"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":30840,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30840\/comments","question_id":30814,"owner":{"user_id":5297,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Reuben Swartz","reputation":337,"email_hash":"1d88ea49e14be3dea7db64fd2bc42d87"},"creation_date":1300404466,"last_activity_date":1300404466,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":44,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Firefox 4 stability?","body":"<p>If you want the most stable just wait until next Tuesday (March 22nd) for the final release. If waiting isn't out of the question.<\/p>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":30840,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30814\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30814\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30814\/answers","question_id":30814,"owner":{"user_id":8357,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Rob","reputation":182,"email_hash":"864c30e28a25aa0f153c8a275617d308"},"creation_date":1300387599,"last_activity_date":1300404466,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":44,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Firefox 4 stability?","body":"<p>Of all the different ways to get Firefox4, which is the most stable, if there is such a thing? (Running 10.10)<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["ubuntu-one"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"closed_date":1300404017,"closed_reason":"off topic","migrated":{"new_question_id":1137,"to_site":{"name":"Ask Ubuntu Meta","logo_url":"http:\/\/sstatic.net\/askubuntumeta\/img\/logo.png","api_endpoint":"http:\/\/api.meta.askubuntu.com","site_url":"http:\/\/meta.askubuntu.com","description":"Q&A about the Stack Exchange site for Ubuntu users and developers","icon_url":"http:\/\/sstatic.net\/askubuntumeta\/img\/apple-touch-icon.png","aliases":["http:\/\/meta.ubuntu.stackexchange.com"],"state":"linked_meta","styling":{"link_color":"#222","tag_foreground_color":"#5E5E5E","tag_background_color":"#E8E7E5"}},"on_date":1300404017},"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30838\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30838\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30838\/answers","question_id":30838,"locked_date":1300404017,"owner":{"user_id":8357,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Rob","reputation":182,"email_hash":"864c30e28a25aa0f153c8a275617d308"},"creation_date":1300403467,"last_activity_date":1300403467,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":1,"view_count":14,"score":-1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How do I \"accept\" an answer?","body":"<p>I was told my accept rate is awful, but I can't find anything to tell me how to do that?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["partitioning","devices"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30837,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30837\/comments","question_id":30826,"owner":{"user_id":8500,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"psusi","reputation":1989,"email_hash":"ce0150ff68789389639241c568dca423"},"creation_date":1300402074,"last_activity_date":1300402074,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":30,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Ubuntu confuses my partitions","body":"<p>Use the UUID instead of the device name.  \/dev\/sda and \/dev\/sdb can change places.<\/p>\n\n<p>UUID=BCD83AE3D83A9B98 \/media\/Data ntfs nls=iso8859-1,ro,users,umask=000 0 0<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30835,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30835\/comments","question_id":30826,"owner":{"user_id":12568,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Turk182","reputation":1,"email_hash":"7b8e0a2ed5075e6a88840a27106e7dbc"},"creation_date":1300400669,"last_activity_date":1300400669,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":30,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Ubuntu confuses my partitions","body":"<p>let me see if i understand, you have 2 HDD...right?...into this you have 3 partitions??..could you explain me why you dont have 1 HHD with ubuntu and windows partition, and 2nd HDD just to storage data?<\/p>\n\n<p>run:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>blkid\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and post the result.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30826\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30826\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30826\/answers","question_id":30826,"owner":{"user_id":12566,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Diego","reputation":101,"email_hash":"b224143d051ec4bcde05ad1508b9ee1e"},"creation_date":1300398217,"last_edit_date":1300400929,"last_activity_date":1300402074,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":30,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Ubuntu confuses my partitions","body":"<p>I have 3 relevant partitions split between 2 disks, <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>sda2: Windows 1 partition<\/li>\n<li>sda3: Ubuntu partition<\/li>\n<li>sdb1: Data partition<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>I was using pysdm to add a label to my partitions and somehow I seem to have screwed up my installation. Now, every time I access the Data partition mounted in \/media\/Data I see the files in my Windows partition, and viceversa. I've tried unmounting and remounting correctly to no avail, it seems that wherever I mount sda2, if I access that folder I get the files in sdb1, and viceversa.<\/p>\n\n<p>Anyone know what may have happened and how to solve this?<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Update:<\/p>\n\n<p>This is the result of blkid:<\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sda1: LABEL=\"System Reserved\" UUID=\"C62603F02603E073\" TYPE=\"ntfs\" <\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sda2: LABEL=\"Windows\" UUID=\"00A6D498A6D49010\" TYPE=\"ntfs\" <\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sda5: UUID=\"033cac3b-6f77-4f09-a629-495dc866866a\" TYPE=\"ext4\" <\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sdb1: LABEL=\"Data\" UUID=\"BCD83AE3D83A9B98\" TYPE=\"ntfs\" <\/p>\n\n<p><br><\/p>\n\n<p>These are the contents of my ftsab file:<\/p>\n\n<p>UUID=033cac3b-6f77-4f09-a629-495dc866866a  \/                ext4  errors=remount-ro,user_xattr      0  1  <\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sda1                                  \/media\/Boot_old  ntfs  defaults                          0  0  <\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sda2                                  \/media\/Windows   ntfs  defaults                          0  0  <\/p>\n\n<p>\/dev\/sdb1                                  \/media\/Data      ntfs  nls=iso8859-1,ro,users,umask=000  0  0  <\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.10","touchpad","dell"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":15004,"accepted":true,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/15004\/comments","question_id":14988,"owner":{"user_id":4409,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Roddie","reputation":364,"email_hash":"eecb91285d2262b239d265da4fa4aeec"},"creation_date":1290791201,"last_activity_date":1290791201,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":237,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Touchpad too slow -- how do I adjust it?","body":"<p>I had the same problem with my Dell. In the mouse options, try increasing the speed but decreasing the sensitivity.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":15030,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/15030\/comments","question_id":14988,"owner":{"user_id":861,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Scaine","reputation":3462,"email_hash":"0f9bda74e3a976957db2ab8bb277cb58"},"creation_date":1290803191,"last_edit_date":1290804691,"last_activity_date":1290804691,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":237,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Touchpad too slow -- how do I adjust it?","body":"<p>Might be worth installing the new <a href=\"https:\/\/launchpad.net\/ubuntu\/+source\/gpointing-device-settings\" rel=\"nofollow\">gpointing-device-settings<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/apt.ubuntu.com\/p\/gpointing-device-settings\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http:\/\/bit.ly\/software-small\" alt=\"Install gpointing-device-settings\"><\/a>\n package to see if that makes a difference.  It has a fairly extensive number of options to control speed, acceleration and so on.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get install gpointing-device-settings\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><img src=\"http:\/\/i.imgur.com\/VU76n.png\" alt=\"alt text\"><\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":14994,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/14994\/comments","question_id":14988,"owner":{"user_id":2461,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Ivo Danihelka","reputation":46,"email_hash":"38168395787df89e47a79d059c4ef70a"},"creation_date":1290788219,"last_activity_date":1290788219,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":237,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Touchpad too slow -- how do I adjust it?","body":"<p>What laptop do you have?\nSome Lenovo Thinkpads have options in the following files:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$ cat \/sys\/devices\/platform\/i8042\/serio1\/speed\n97\n$ cat \/sys\/devices\/platform\/i8042\/serio1\/sensitivity\n128\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"}],"accepted_answer_id":15004,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/14988\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/14988\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/14988\/answers","question_id":14988,"owner":{"user_id":2413,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"user2413","reputation":340,"email_hash":"39c115a166788050ce9f1d1f5eacdd96"},"creation_date":1290783542,"last_edit_date":1300401766,"last_activity_date":1300401766,"up_vote_count":3,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":237,"score":3,"community_owned":false,"title":"Touchpad too slow -- how do I adjust it?","body":"<p>Apparently this is a recurring problem. I tried <strong>System->Preferences->Mouse<\/strong> but it didn't help. <\/p>\n\n<p>There's a lot of info on the web on this, but it is outdated (Ubuntu 7.04 and 8.04).<br>\nAny tips on how to fix this?<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["network","bandwidth","network-monitoring"],"answer_count":0,"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30812\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30812\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30812\/answers","question_id":30812,"owner":{"user_id":12383,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Malcolm X","reputation":33,"email_hash":"5585b7a8bfd22d9b0965fb1c88c11ba9"},"creation_date":1300386511,"last_edit_date":1300401602,"last_activity_date":1300401602,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":19,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Network control and monitoring with Netams","body":"<p>Has anyone ever used Netams for network, bandwidth management?\nWhen I search Google and Ubuntu sites, I can only find very basic installation and configuration information, and most are in Russian.<\/p>\n\n<p>I would like to know if anyone knows where can I find a complete step by step guide to install and configure it in Ubuntu.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks in advance.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["10.04","server","usb"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26465,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26465\/comments","question_id":26448,"owner":{"user_id":10874,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Anmol Sharma","reputation":1,"email_hash":"174c4029b0c66ab4c44b75d15bc1df9e"},"creation_date":1297766196,"last_edit_date":1300401438,"last_activity_date":1300401438,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"USB devices are not working on server","body":"<p>Please check to make sure that your USB ports are working: try to connect a mic, or a USB laptop flashlight, or another USB device to ensure they draw power from USB.  Then update your question with the results. <\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/26448\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/26448\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/26448\/answers","question_id":26448,"creation_date":1297750827,"last_edit_date":1297781207,"last_activity_date":1300401438,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":51,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"USB devices are not working on server","body":"<p>I have installed Ubuntu server 10.04 and my server doesn't detect the external USB devices. Mouse, keyboard and usb harddisk.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["kernel","ati","fglrx"],"answer_count":1,"answers":[{"answer_id":26416,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/26416\/comments","question_id":23955,"owner":{"user_id":10838,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"cako","reputation":29,"email_hash":"d3b33292d2db6b785dffba466aa184d4"},"creation_date":1297720096,"last_activity_date":1297720096,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":133,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Cannot boot: FGLRX 8.780 + Kernel 2.6.35-25","body":"<p>Try to reinstal fglrx with<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get purge xorg-driver-fglrx\nsudo apt-get install xorg-driver-fglrx\n<\/code><\/pre>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/23955\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/23955\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/23955\/answers","question_id":23955,"owner":{"user_id":9887,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"pluc","reputation":11,"email_hash":"c451dc037b47b54dfff1ee06a8e986d0"},"creation_date":1296347967,"last_edit_date":1296382202,"last_activity_date":1300401217,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":133,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Cannot boot: FGLRX 8.780 + Kernel 2.6.35-25","body":"<p>The situation before this all happened is pretty standard. I have a HP Pavillion dv5 laptop with an ATI Mobility Radeon 4200 series. It always worked fine with Ubuntu for as long as I can remember. However, at one point, something happened and truly made a majestic mess of things. It might've been extra repos I enabled with Ubuntu Tweak - I do not know. But something made it so that my system would not boot any longer.<\/p>\n\n<p>And when I say \"won't boot\", this is what I mean:\n- Durning a normal bootup, any entries (except Windows) selected with GRUB (or BURG, not even sure which one I'm using anymore) will spawn the Ubuntu loading screen - then try to start X (or GDM) 5 times. The screen goes to dark, black and back to the Ubuntu loading screen. Then it just stays there until I spawn another TTY.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have no idea what is happening or why. There are no errors in my logs, and I'm truly at a loss here.<\/p>\n\n<p>I've linked three files: Xorg.0.log, the output of dmesg and the GDM log:<\/p>\n\n<p>Xorg.0.log: <a href=\"http:\/\/ubuntu.pastebin.com\/tpVKc2tc\" rel=\"nofollow\">http:\/\/ubuntu.pastebin.com\/tpVKc2tc<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>dmesg: ubuntu.pastebin.com\/Nd5aYj45<\/p>\n\n<p>gdm's :0.log: <em>couldn't post due to lack of points :(<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>Let me know if any of you more knowledgeable folks can restore some sanity in my life.<\/p>\n\n<p>Any help is greatly apreciated.<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["video","nvidia","x"],"answer_count":3,"answers":[{"answer_id":29270,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/29270\/comments","question_id":29269,"owner":{"user_id":9940,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Alexander","reputation":183,"email_hash":"bd5300964013803c41479ac03d70ff1d"},"creation_date":1299426628,"last_activity_date":1299426628,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Change X settings to boot into laptop with non working screen using an external monitor","body":"<p>Just plug in a monitor, and the monitor will mirror what the laptop screen ought to be showing. You can use System -> Preferences -> Monitors to get the resolution right, and turn off the laptop screen (so Ubuntu doesn't try to render everything twice).<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30836,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30836\/comments","question_id":29269,"owner":{"user_id":5287,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Mark Shuttleworth","reputation":1807,"email_hash":"8b438b0f3cf559a34c4a9a7ae2a0b01b"},"creation_date":1300400973,"last_activity_date":1300400973,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"Change X settings to boot into laptop with non working screen using an external monitor","body":"<p>Ctrl-Alt-F1 should get you into a terminal. In there, install openssh-server so you can log into the machine from the network, which will be more comfortable:<\/p>\n\n<p>sudo aptitude install openssh-server (from memory)<\/p>\n\n<p>Then, log in locally (you will lose your screen initially).<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, log in remotely via ssh.<\/p>\n\n<p>Set your remote ssh session environment so you can affect the X server:<\/p>\n\n<p>export DISPLAY=:<\/p>\n\n<p>Now you can play around with variations on xrandr --auto etc on the remote ssh session, and you will be driving your desktop login. For example:<\/p>\n\n<p>xrandr -q<\/p>\n\n<p>... which should tell you the current status.<\/p>\n\n<p>xrandr --auto<\/p>\n\n<p>... which might Just Work. Or maybe (as a guess from memory)<\/p>\n\n<p>xrandr --output LVDS1 --off --output VGA1 --auto<\/p>\n\n<p>Good luck ;-)<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30827,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30827\/comments","question_id":29269,"owner":{"user_id":12067,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Hossam Riyad","reputation":98,"email_hash":"49eb15afcb55e8d592394326e45c2e71"},"creation_date":1300398792,"last_activity_date":1300398792,"up_vote_count":0,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":0,"community_owned":false,"title":"Change X settings to boot into laptop with non working screen using an external monitor","body":"<p>press on Fn+ your button that contains projector on it . tell me your laptop model ?<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":0,"bounty_closes_date":1300754087,"bounty_amount":50,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/29269\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/29269\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/29269\/answers","question_id":29269,"owner":{"user_id":982,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"dassouki","reputation":78,"email_hash":"ca625a9a85d2668c09d08150976a7175"},"creation_date":1299426440,"last_edit_date":1299437065,"last_activity_date":1300400973,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":47,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"Change X settings to boot into laptop with non working screen using an external monitor","body":"<p>My laptop committed suicide. Is there a way I can boot into my ubuntu using an external screen? <\/p>\n\n<p>Ubuntu 10.10\nvideo: Nvidia 9500 gm i think<\/p>\n\n<p>I can get dual screen upto and until the ubuntu login screen at which point it goes back into laptop display only. Then I can just type and enter my password. The system (i assume boots into ubuntu) but I got no way of going onto the x or nvidia settings to change my display to external monitor<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>well I booted into terminal using control shift F1 i think, and now I'm trying to reporgram x.org, but strangely it seems bland with not a lot of settings in it<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT 2<\/strong>\nxrandr returns \"Can't open display\"<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>EDit 3<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>after some messing around with xrandr and xinit ... my x.org only displays one monitor instead of two in its settings although both, i.e. the laptop and external screens are both connected.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT 4<\/strong>\nit seems that x.org now has a \"screen\" and \"monitor\" section, I can't seem to be able to boot linux into monitor. I get a \"Monitor is not a valid keyword\" in this subsection<\/p>\n"},{"tags":["update-manager","cron"],"answer_count":2,"answers":[{"answer_id":30832,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30832\/comments","question_id":30825,"owner":{"user_id":449,"user_type":"moderator","display_name":"Oli","reputation":20546,"email_hash":"f0af40756420859b5b63cbceb6d30505"},"creation_date":1300400223,"last_activity_date":1300400223,"up_vote_count":2,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":2,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to schedule time-of-day upgrades","body":"<p>Not an answer to your exact issue but a workaround that presents you with significant benefits: why don't you just use a proxy?<\/p>\n\n<p>There are numerous options but I'd start with <code>squid-deb-proxy<\/code>. You'll need one machine to serve as the host but this could easily be one of the machines you're dealing with. Similarly it could be a separate server. Doesn't need to be powerful.<\/p>\n\n<p>The idea is updated packages need only be downloaded once. They get cached and all the other machines download from the local cache.<\/p>\n\n<p>You still need to stagger the update process. One machine needs to download the updates to fill the cache. You could use one machine to download the updates at night (using a simple <code>@daily<\/code> cron job -- happens at midnight). The other machines could be turned off over night (saving a lot of money) and then could just grab their updates when they like. They'd only use internal bandwidth so would fly.<\/p>\n\n<p>Some tips on setting it up can be <a href=\"http:\/\/cad.cx\/blog\/2010\/11\/10\/squid-deb-proxy-or-how-updates-fly-at-work\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">read here<\/a>.<\/p>\n"},{"answer_id":30829,"accepted":false,"answer_comments_url":"\/answers\/30829\/comments","question_id":30825,"owner":{"user_id":11976,"user_type":"registered","display_name":"Adam Byrtek","reputation":245,"email_hash":"6a29caa1a66ae5e3772ed976f6b63527"},"creation_date":1300399260,"last_activity_date":1300399260,"up_vote_count":1,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":1,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to schedule time-of-day upgrades","body":"<p>Looks like you are using two independent update mechanisms: cron-apt and the Update Manager. Try disabling automatic updates in the Update Manager. If cron-apt is configured correctly, you will get a notification email each time a new update is installed.<\/p>\n"}],"favorite_count":1,"question_timeline_url":"\/questions\/30825\/timeline","question_comments_url":"\/questions\/30825\/comments","question_answers_url":"\/questions\/30825\/answers","question_id":30825,"owner":{"user_id":12567,"user_type":"unregistered","display_name":"Richard","reputation":36,"email_hash":"4c0945452a19398abb1b3ee86e6c5e85"},"creation_date":1300398148,"last_edit_date":1300398336,"last_activity_date":1300400223,"up_vote_count":7,"down_vote_count":0,"view_count":46,"score":7,"community_owned":false,"title":"How to schedule time-of-day upgrades","body":"<p>Hello, I'm responsible for about 30 Ubuntu computers at a private K-8 school.  We have only a 3Mbps internet connection serving the entire campus, and I would like to ensure that updates are done in the middle of the night - so that daytime tasks are not slowed down.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm using Ubuntu 10.04, and have set all computers to download and install security updates via the update manager.  I have also installed cron-apt, and modified the config file to stagger the start times of the upgrades from about 10pm to 4am local time.<\/p>\n\n<p>HOWEVER - this morning I arrived at the school at 7:30am and all the computers were busy downloading a large security based update.  Needless to say, all internet activity was slowed to a crawl (for the next 2 hours), and the computer users were very very upset.  This was the event I'm trying so hard to prevent.<\/p>\n\n<p>It seems that my scheme to ensure middle of the night downloads failed, and I'm not sure why.<\/p>\n\n<p>I've also tried some schemes using unattended-upgrades &amp; crontab, but there always seemed to be something scheduling upgrades to occur in addition to the ones I try to force at middle of the night.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Is there a sure fire way to absolutely positively guarantee that updates will occur only at one specific time?<\/strong>  It would be nice if the update manager just had a drop down menu to specify a designated time.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks in advance for any help you can give me.<\/p>\n"}]}